</P>
<P>In the mene tyme, a prynce of Macedoyne broghte &thorn;e kyng a
horse vn-teme&dtail;, a grete and a faire; & he was tye&dtail;
o&ntail; ilke side wit chynes of Ire&ntail;, for he walde wery
me&ntail; and ete &thorn;a&mtail;.  This ilke horse was calle&dtail;
Buktiphalas, bi-cause of his vgly lukynge, For he hade a heue&dtail;
lyke a bu&llbar;e, & knotti&llbar;s in his frount, as &thorn;ay had
hene &thorn;e bygynnyng of hournes.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e kyng saw
&thorn;e bewtee of this horse, he said ti&llbar; his seruandis,
'Take&yogh; this horse and putte&yogh; hym in a stable, and makes
barre&yogh; of yre&ntail; be-fore hym, that thefe&yogh; and o&thorn;er
mysdoers, &thorn;at sa&llbar; be done to dede, may be putt
in-ti&llbar; hym, to be slae&ntail; of hym.  And &thorn;ay did&dtail;
soo.  In &thorn;e mene tyme &thorn;e kynge Philippe ha&dtail; ane
answere of his goddes, that hee schulde regne nexte after hym, the
whilke myghte ryde that wylde horse wit-owtte&ntail; harme. So it
fe&llbar;e &thorn;at Alexander &thorn;e whilke was &thorn;a&ntail;
twelue &yogh;ere alde, wexe strange & re&yogh;te hardy, & was wysse
and discrete; for he was wele lere&dtail; & connan&dtail; in a&llbar;
&thorn;e seue&ntail; sciences, &thorn;e whilke twa philosophirs had
teche&dtail; hym : &thorn;at es to say, Arestotle & Calistene.  And
one a day, as Alexander passe&dtail; for-by &thorn;e place &thorn;are
als &thorn;e foresaide stode, he luked in betwene &thorn;e
barre&yogh; of yrnne and saw, bifore &thorn;e horse, mens hen&dtail;
and fete, & o&thorn;er of &thorn;aire membris, liggan&dtail;
scatere&dtail; here & thare, and he ha&dtail; grete wonder
&thorn;are-off.  And he putt in his
<PB N="9">
hande bitwene &thorn;e barre&yogh;, And &thorn;e horse<MILESTONE
N="1 bk." UNIT="leaf"> strekede oute his nekke, als ferre als he myghte, and likke&dtail; Alexander
han&dtail;; and he kneli&dtail; dou&ntail; o&ntail; his kneesse, and
bi-helde Alexander in &thorn;e vesage langly.  And Alexander
vnderstode wele &thorn;e wi&llbar; of &thorn;e horse, and opyn&dtail;
the barre&yogh;, and went into &thorn;e horse, and strake&dtail; him
softely on &thorn;e bakke wit his ri&yogh;te han&dtail;; And belyfe
&thorn;e horse wexe wonderly meke ti&llbar; Alexander; and ri&yogh;te
as a honde wi&llbar; couche whe&ntail; his maister biddes hym, so dide
he ti&llbar; Alexander; and Alexander lukede besides hym, & sawe a
sadi&llbar; & a bryde&llbar; hyng thare; and he tuke &
dy&dtail;&thorn;a&mtail; o&ntail; hy&mtail;, & leppe one his bakke &
