<P>And he tuke wit hym also a philosop&hbar;re &thorn;at highte Eufestius, whilke he trayste&dtail; meki&llbar; in, And twelue childre &thorn;at he chese to be his playfers, and went hym furthe, and come
in-ti&llbar; a contreth &thorn;at es called Polipone.  And whe&ntail;
the kynge of &thorn;e lan&dtail; her&dtail; te&llbar;, &thorn;at
swilke me&ntail; ware entre&dtail; in-to his rewme in swilke araye, he
rayse&dtail; a gret Oste, and come agaynes Alexander for to feghte wit
hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; he come nerehan&dtail; hym, he sai&dtail;
vn-ti&llbar; hym.  'Te&llbar; me' quo&thorn; he 'whatt &thorn;ou ert
?'  And Alexander ansuer&dtail; 'I am Alexander' quo&thorn; he
'&thorn;e so&ntail; of Philippe, &thorn;e kynge of Macedoyne.'  'And
what hope&yogh; &thorn;ou &thorn;at I be ?' quo&thorn; &thorn;e kynge
ti&llbar; hym.  And Alexander ansuer&dtail;.  '&THORN;ou ert kynge of
Arridouns' quo&thorn; he.  'Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse, if a&llbar; I do
&thorn;e &thorn;at wirchippe &thorn;at I calle &thorn;e kynge, empride
&thorn;e nathynge &thorn;are-of. For me&ntail; see&yogh; ofte tymes
me&ntail; &thorn;at ere in heghe astate co&mtail; to lawe degree, &
me&ntail; &thorn;at ere in lawe degree, come ti&llbar; heghe astate.'
'&THORN;ou sais ri&yogh;te wele' quo&thorn; &thorn;e kynge. 'Take hede
to thy&ntail; awe&ntail; selfe!'  And Alexander ansuer&dtail; & said
'Ga hethe&ntail; away fra me' quo&thorn; he 'for &thorn;ou ca&ntail;
say noghte to mee, ne I hafe noghte at do wit &thorn;e.'  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e kyng was worder wrathe, And said
ti&llbar;Alexander
 
<PB N="10">
'Luke on me'<MILESTONE N="2" UNIT="leaf"> quo&thorn; he '&thorn;at spekes to the: Fore I swere the
be my Fader hele, & I anes spitte in thi face, &thorn;ou schale dye.'
And wit &thorn;at he spitte at Alexander, & sai&dtail;: 'Take &thorn;e
&thorn;are, &thorn;ou biche whelpe, &thorn;at &thorn;e seme&yogh;
ti&llbar; hafe.'  And Alexander steppe&dtail; furthe, & sai&dtail;
vn-ti&llbar; hy&mtail;.  'For &thorn;ou' quo&thorn; he 'hase dispised
me, by-cause I ame litti&llbar;; I swere &thorn;e, bi &thorn;e pete of
my Fader, & by my moders wambe, in &thorn;e whilke I was consayued of
godd Amo&ntail;, &thorn;at &thorn;ou scha&llbar; see mee, are oughte
lange, in &thorn;i rewme, redi to feghte wit &thorn;e; and ow&thorn;er
I scha&llbar; wy&ntail; thi rewme wit dynte of swer&dtail;, & brynge
it vnder my subieccion&ntail;, or &thorn;ou scha&llbar; make me
subiecte vn-to &thorn;e.'  And &thorn;are &thorn;ay assignede day of
Bate&llbar;e; and ayther of &thorn;a&mtail; went hame fra o&thorn;er.
</P>
<P>And agaynes &thorn;e day of Bate&llbar;e, Alexander, bi ascent &
ordynance of kynge Philippe, gadird a grete Oste, & went to the place
&thorn;are &thorn;e Bate&llbar;e was assigned, and fand a&llbar; redy
&thorn;are, kyng Nico&llbar; and his oste.  And &thorn;ay
trumppe&dtail; vp appo&ntail; bathe &thorn;e parties, and biga&ntail;
to feghte, & many me&ntail; ware slae&ntail; o&ntail; bathe &thorn;e
syde&yogh;.  Bot at &thorn;e laste, Alexander hade &thorn;e felde, &
tuke kyng Nicho&llbar;, & gart smytte of his heue&dtail;, & went
in-ti&llbar; his land, and conquered it; and his knyghtes went and
coroun&dtail; hym kynge &thorn;are-off.  And sythe&ntail; he went hame
ti&llbar; his fader, kyng Philippe, and fan&dtail; hym sittan&dtail;
at the mete at a bridale: For he had put awaye fra hym his wyfe
Olympias, Alexander moder, and take&ntail; hym an-o&thorn;er &thorn;at
highte Cleopatra; And Alexander went in-to &thorn;e hau&llbar;e, and
said vn-to &thorn;e kynge Philip&ptail;: 'Fader,' quo&thorn; he, 'I
pray &yogh;ow, &thorn;at for a rewarde of my firste iournee &thorn;at
I hafe now made, &yogh;ee graunte me to take my Moder Olympias agayne
vn-to &yogh;ow, & do to hir as awe to be done to a qwenne, rathere
&thorn;a&ntail; I gyffe hir to ano&thorn;er kynge; so &thorn;at I be
no&yogh;te &yogh;oure enemy for euer.  For this weddyng, &thorn;at
&yogh;e hafe now made here, es vnlefu&llbar;!'  Whe&ntail; he
had&dtail; sai&dtail; thir wordes, ane of &thorn;e &thorn;at satt at
&thorn;e kynges burde, whase name was Lesias, ansuer&dtail; &
sai&dtail; to &thorn;e kyng: 'lor&dtail;' quo&thorn; he '&thorn;ou
schall hafe a so&ntail; of Cleopatra, and he scha&llbar; regne after
&thorn;e !'  Alexander, tha&ntail;, was gretly greuede at his wordes,
and wit a wardrere &thorn;at he hade in his hande, he went
<PB N="11">
ti&llbar; hym and kellede hym.  Whe&ntail; kyng P&hbar;ilippe sawe
this, he was gretly stirre&dtail;, and rase vp, & gatt a swerde<MILESTONE
N="2 bk." UNIT="leaf"> & ranne to-warde&yogh; Alexander, for to hafe smytte&ntail; hy&mtail;.
Bot onane he fe&llbar;e dow&ntail;; and ay &thorn;e nerre Alexander
&thorn;at he drewe, &thorn;e mare he fe&llbar;e to the erthe
ri&yogh;te as he bene fer&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Alexander said
vn-ti&llbar; hym: 'Philippe' quo&thorn; he 'how es it soo, that
&thorn;ou, &thorn;at hase won&ntail; wit dynt of swerde a&llbar;e
Grece, ne hase now na strenghe to stande on thi fete.'  And
&thorn;a&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;e hau&llbar;e was troubbled, and the
brydale letted.  And Alexander went abowte &thorn;e hau&llbar;e, and
keste dou&ntail; &thorn;e bourde&yogh; wit &thorn;e mete, & &thorn;e
drynke &thorn;at ware appo&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail;, and tuke Cleopatra,
and schotte hir oute at &thorn;e hau&llbar;e dore.  And the kynge
Philippe, for sorowe &thorn;at he tuke ti&llbar;, fe&llbar;e grefe
seke.  And a litti&llbar; afterwarde&yogh;, Alexander went ti&llbar;
hym for to vesett hym & comforthe hym, and sai&dtail; vn-ti&llbar; hym
'Philippe,' quo&thorn; he, 'if a&llbar; it be no&yogh;te semely,
&thorn;at I calle &thorn;e be &thorn;i propre name;
neuere-&thorn;e-lesse, no&yogh;te as &thorn;i so&ntail;, bot as
&thorn;i gu&dtail; fren&dtail;, I sa&llbar; te&llbar;e the my&ntail;
avice.  It es fully my consaile &thorn;at &thorn;ou reconnselle agayne
vn-to the my lady, my Moder Olympias, and at &thorn;ou grefe &thorn;e
na-thynge at &thorn;e dede of Lesias, ne take na heuynes to the
&thorn;are-fore.  For vnkyndely me thynnke &thorn;at &thorn;ou
did&dtail;, and vngudely, &thorn;at &thorn;ou drewe &thorn;i swerde
for to smytte me &thorn;are-wit.'  And whe&ntail; Philippe her&dtail;
&thorn;ir wordes, his hert tendir&dtail;, & he bigane to wepe.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; Alexander went ti&llbar; his Moder Olympyas, and
sai&dtail; vn-ti&llbar; hir: 'Be no&yogh;te ferde' quo&thorn; he 'ne
be no&yogh;te heuy to my fader, for if a&llbar;e thi trespas be
preuee, & no&yogh;te knawe&ntail;, neuer-&thorn;e-lesse &thorn;ou erte
in party to blame.'  And whe&ntail; be hade sayde thus, he led&dtail;
hir furthe to &thorn;e kyng Philippe.  And he tuk & kyssid hir, and
thus was scho reconnselde vn-ti&llbar; hym agayne.
</P>
<P>After &thorn;is, &thorn;are come messengers Fra Darius, &thorn;e
emperour of Perse, to kyng Philippe, and aske&dtail; hym tribute  And
Alexander answer&dtail; to thir messengers, & saide, 'Saise to Darius,
&yogh;our lorde,' quo&thorn; he, '&thorn;at se&ntail; &thorn;e tyme
&thorn;at Philippe so&ntail; was waxe&ntail; of age &thorn;e hen
&thorn;at ay es waxe&ntail; barayne & consume&dtail;
 
<PB N="12">
awaye, and so es Darius pryuede of his trybute.'  And [when] thir
messengers her&dtail; thir wordes; &thorn;ay hade grete wounder of
&thorn;am & of &thorn;e witt & &thorn;e wisedome of Alexander.
</P>
<P>In &thorn;e mene tyme tythynge&yogh; come to kyng Philippe,
&thorn;at Ermonye, &thorn;e whilke bi-fore was suget vn-ti&llbar; hym,
was rebe&llbar;e & raysse agaynes hym.  And he garte<MILESTONE N="3" UNIT="leaf"> semble a grete
Oste, and sent Alexander thedir &thorn;are wit to feghte wit
&thorn;a&mtail;, and to putt &thorn;a&mtail; agayne vnder his
subieccion&ntail;. Alexander tha&ntail;went wit this Oste ti&llbar;
Ermony & broghte it agayne in subieccio&ntail;, as it was bi-fore.
</P>
<P>An in &thorn;e mene tyme, whils he was &thorn;are, a lorde of
Macedoyne &thorn;e whilke highte Pansamy, a strange ma&ntail; & a
balde, suget vn-to Philippe, and bade of lange tyme couette for to
hafe &thorn;e quene Olympias, conspirede agaynes &thorn;e kynge, and
come with a grete multytude of folke appo&ntail; &thorn;e kynge, to
for-do hym.  And whe&ntail; tythynge&yogh; here of come to kyng
Philippe, he went to mete hym in &thorn;e felde wit a fewe
men&yogh;ee.  And whe&ntail; he sawe &thorn;e grete multitude
&thorn;at Pansamy hade wit hym, he turne&dtail;& fled&dtail;, and
Pansamy persue&dtail; after hy&mtail;, and ouerhie&dtail; hym, and
strake hym thurghe wit a spere, and &yogh;itt ife a&llbar; he were
greuosely wonde&dtail;, he dye&dtail; no&yogh;te alsone, bot he laye
halfe dede in the waye.  And than &thorn;e Macedoynes, &thorn;at
wenede he bade bane dade, made meki&llbar; sorowe.  And when &thorn;is
iournee was done Pansamy was gretly empridede &thorn;are offe, & went
in to &thorn;e kynges palace for to take &thorn;e qwene Olympias oute
of it and hafe hir with hym.  And eue&ntail; &thorn;e same tyme,
Alexander come fra Hermony, & sawe swylke trouble & styrrynge in the
rewme, and hye&dtail; hym faste towarde &thorn;e kynges palace, and
when Olympias her&dtail; te&llbar;e &thorn;at Alexander hir so&ntail;
had &thorn;e victorye of his enemys, & was comande nere, Scho went
furthe of &thorn;e palace at a preuee posterne to mete hir so&ntail;,
and to welcome hym hame.  And alsone als scho come nere hym, scho
criede appo&ntail; hy&mtail; & sai&dtail;.
</P>
<P>'A A, my son Alexander, whare es &thorn;e grace & &thorn;e fortune
&thorn;at oure goddes highte the, &thorn;at es to say, &thorn;at
&thorn;ou scholde alwaye ouercome thyn&ntail; enemys & no&yogh;te be
ouercome&ntail;, &thorn;at Pansamy hase one &thorn;is wyse slaen thi
Fader.'  And alsone the worde come to Pansamy &thorn;at Alexander was
come&ntail;, and he went furthe of palace for to mete hy&mtail;.  And
also faste als Alexander sawe hym, he oute wit a swer&dtail; and clafe
his heue&dtail;
<PB N="13">
in to &thorn;e tethe, & slewe hym.  And ane of &thorn;e Oste
sai&dtail; ti&llbar; Alexander: 'Philippe &thorn;i fader' quo&thorn;
he, 'lyas dade in &thorn;e felde.'  And &thorn;an Alexander went
thedir thare he laye, and saw hym eue&ntail; at &thorn;e dyinge.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he bega&ntail; faste for to wepe.  And Philippe luked
apo&ntail; hy&mtail;, & sai&dtail; 'A A, my dere son Alexander,'
quo&thorn; he, 'wit a glade hert [I] may now dye, for &thorn;at
&thorn;ou so soune hase venge&dtail; my dede,' & eue&ntail; wit<MILESTONE
N="3 bk." UNIT="leaf">
&thorn;at worde he &yogh;alde &thorn;e gaste.  And Alexander
wirchipfully gert hym be entere&dtail;.
</P>
<P>When kyng Philippe was entered, Alexander went and sett hym in his
trone, and gerte calle by-fore hym alle &thorn;e folke &thorn;at was
gader&dtail; thedir, lordes & o&thorn;er, and sai&dtail; vn-to
&thorn;a&mtail; on &thorn;is wyse.  'Me&ntail;,' quo&thorn; he, 'of
Macedoyne of Tracy, and of Grece byhalde&yogh; &thorn;e fegure of
Alexander and putte&yogh; oute of &yogh;our hertes drede of a&llbar;e
&yogh;our enemys.  For sekerly, and &yogh;e wi&llbar; take gude hertis
to &yogh;ow, thurghe &thorn;e helpe of oure goddis he scha&llbar; hafe
&thorn;e ouerhande of a&llbar; &yogh;oure neghtebours, and &yogh;our
name scha&llbar; spre&dtail; ouer alle the werlde.  And
&thorn;are-fore ilkane of &yogh;ow &thorn;at hase Armour, makes it
redy, and he &thorn;at hase nane come to my palace & I sa&llbar; gerre
delyuer hy&mtail; a&llbar; &thorn;at hym nedis, and ilk a ma&ntail;
make hym redy to &thorn;e werre.'  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e lordes and
knyghtis &thorn;at ware of grete age, her&dtail; thir wordes &thorn;ay
ansuer&dtail; Alexander, & sai&dtail; vn-ti&llbar; hy&mtail;: 'lorde,'
quo&thorn; thaye, 'we hafe seruede &yogh;oure fader a longe tyme &
trauel&dtail; wit hym in his werres, & &thorn;are-fore we ere now so
brysse&dtail; in armes &thorn;at &thorn;are [es] no myghte lefte in vs
for to suffre disesse &thorn;at ofte&ntail; tymes falles to me&ntail;
of werre.  For we ere streke&ntail; in grete age.  And
&thorn;are-fore, if it be plesynge vn-to &yogh;ow, we consaile
&yogh;ow & we beseken &yogh;owe, that &yogh;e chese &yogh;ow &yogh;ong
lordes & &yogh;ong knyghtes, &thorn;at ere listy me&ntail; & able for
to suffre disesse for to be wit &yogh;ow.  For here we giffe vp att
armes if it be &yogh;our wi&llbar; & forsakes &thorn;a&mtail; for
euer.'  And &thorn;a&ntail; Alexander answer&dtail; & sai&dtail;: 'I
wi&llbar; rathere,' quo&thorn; he, 'chese &thorn;e sadnesse of an alde
wyse ma&ntail; tha&ntail; &thorn;e vnavesy lightenesse of &yogh;onge
me&ntail;.  For &yogh;ong me&ntail; often tymes traystan&dtail; to
meki&llbar; in thaire awen&ntail; doghtynes thurgh &thorn;aire
awe&ntail; foly ere mescheue&dtail;.  Bot alde me&ntail; wirkes
a&llbar; by consaile & by witte.'  Whe&ntail; he had said thir wordes
a&llbar; me&ntail;
 
<PB N="14">
alowe&dtail; his hie witte and hally &thorn;ay assentede to hym for to
do his lyste.
</P>
<P>Sone after Alexander assemblede a grete Oste, & went bi Schippe
to-warde&yogh; Ytaly, and als he come by Calcedoyne, he
assaylle&dtail; it re&yogh;te strangly, and &thorn;e folke of
Calcedoyne<MILESTONE N="4" UNIT="leaf"> went to &thorn;e walles of &thorn;e Citee and
defendi&dtail; manly.  Bot at the laste Alexander wa&ntail; the Citee,
and fra thethy&ntail; he Schippede in-ti&llbar; Italy.  And alsone als
&thorn;e Romaynes her&dtail; of his comynge &thorn;ay were wonder
ferde for hy&mtail;, and the grete lordes of &thorn;e lande tuke
fourty thowsande&yogh; of besande&yogh; and I<HI REND="sup">c</HI>
corounes of golde, and went vn-ti&llbar; hy&mtail;, and presant hym
wit &thorn;a&mtail; & bysoughte hym &thorn;at he scholde no&yogh;te
werrey appo&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail;, ne do &thorn;a&mtail; na harme.
And than Alexander tuke trybute of &thorn;e Romaynes, and of a&llbar;e
the folkes &thorn;at duelt bitwixe that & &thorn;e weste Occeane,
&thorn;e whilke regione es callede Europe, & lefte &thorn;a&mtail; in
gude pesse.
</P>
<P>Fra thethyn he Schippede in-ti&llbar; Affrice, in thee whilke he
fande bot fewe &thorn;at rebelle&dtail; agaynes hym and
&thorn;are-fore als [men] swa saye, eneil sodeynly he conqueri&dtail;
it & broghte it vnder his subieccio&ntail;. And fra Affric he went by
Schippe ti&llbar; ane Ile, &thorn;at es calle&dtail; Frontides, for to
consaile wit a god&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;ay calle&dtail; Amo&ntail;.
And as Alexander & his me&ntail; went to-warde&yogh; &thorn;e temple
of &thorn;is for-sai&dtail; god&dtail;, &thorn;ay mett in &thorn;e
waye a grete hert &thorn;e whilke Alexander bad his me&ntail; sla wit
arowes.  And &thorn;ay schott at hym; bet nane of &thorn;a&mtail;
myghte hitt hym.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Alexander tuke a bowe & schotte
at hym & hitt hym & slewe hym.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Alexander went
in-to &thorn;e temple, & made sacrafyce of &thorn;is hert vn-to
god&dtail; Amon, and by-soughte hym &thorn;at he schulde gyffe hym
ansuares. Whe&ntail; Alexander hade made his prayers &thorn;are to
god&dtail; Amo&ntail;, he went wit his Oste in-ti&llbar; a place
&thorn;at highte Taphoresey, In &thorn;e whilke were feftene gude
townues, & &thorn;ay bade twelne grete reuers &thorn;at rane in-to
&thorn;e see, and at &thorn;e entree of &thorn;a&mtail; in-to &thorn;e
see &thorn;are was drawe&ntail; ouer grete chynes of yryne, and thare
Alexandir made Sacrafice ti&llbar; his godde&yogh;.  And on &thorn;e
same nyghte, a god&dtail; &thorn;at [hight] Serapis apperid
vn-ti&llbar; hym in his slepe, cled&dtail; in riche clothynge in ane
horrible forme & a dredefu&llbar;, and sai&dtail; vn-ti&llbar;
<PB N="15">
hym.  'Alexander,' quo&thorn; he, 'may &thorn;ou take &thorn;is
montayne on &thorn;i schulder & bere it a-way?' Quo&thorn; Alexander,
'how myghte any ma&ntail; do pat?'  And Serapis ansuer&dtail; &
sai&dtail;, 'righte as &thorn;is montayne sa&llbar; neuer wit-owten<MILESTONE
N="4 bk." UNIT="leaf">
end be remowe&dtail; hethe&ntail;, so thi name & thi dedes schall be
made mynde of to the worldes en&dtail;.'  And tha&ntail; Alexander
prayed hym &thorn;at he walde prophycye hym what kyns dede he scholde
die.  Serapis ansuerd and said, 'It es noghte spedfu&llbar; ti&llbar;
a man to knawe his paynefu&llbar; endynge.  For if he knewe it,
perauenture, he scholde neuer hafe Ioye in his hert.  Neuer &thorn;e
lesse bi-cause &thorn;ou hase prayede me to telle &thorn;e, I
sa&llbar; say the.  After a drynke &thorn;ou schall take thi dede.
For in thi &yogh;outhe &thorn;ou sa&llbar; make thy&ntail; endynge.
Bot spirre me no&thorn;er &thorn;e tyme ne &thorn;e houre whe&ntail;
it schal be, For I will on na wyse te&llbar;e it to the.  For-whi
godde&yogh; of &thorn;e este partie&yogh; of &thorn;e werdle sa&llbar;
te&llbar;e the a&llbar;e thi werde&yogh;.'  Whe&ntail; Alexander
wakkene&dtail; of his dreme, he was reghte heuy, and sent &thorn;e
maste substance of his Oste to &thorn;e Cite of Askalo&ntail; and bad
&thorn;ai&mtail; habide hym thare, and hym selfe & a certane of
men&yogh;e wit hym habade & thare he garte make a Citee & calle&dtail;
it Alexander after his awen&ntail; name.
</P>
<P>In the mene tyme , Egipcyens her&dtail; of &thorn;e comynges of
Alexander, & &thorn;ay went agaynes hym & submytt &thorn;a&mtail;
vn-ti&llbar;hym & resayffe&dtail; hym wirchipfully. And whe&ntail;
Alexander come in-ti&llbar; Egipte, he fand ane ymage of a kyng made
of blake stane curiousely corue&ntail;, and he askede &thorn;e
Egipciens whase ymage it was, and &thorn;ay ansuer&dtail; & said, 'It
es &thorn;e ymage,' quop &thorn;ay, 'of Anectanabus that was kynge of
Egipte no&yogh;te lange sythe&ntail; gane, &thorn;e wyseste & &thorn;e
worthiest &thorn;at euer was &thorn;are-i&ntail;.'  For sothe
quo&thorn; Alexander, 'Auectanabus was my Fader.'  And &thorn;an he
knelid dou&ntail; with grete reuerence & kysse&dtail; &thorn;e ymage.
Fra thethy&ntail; he went wit his Oste to Surry.  But &thorn;e
Surriens agayne-stude hym and faghte wit hy&mtail; and slewe many of
his knyghtes.  Neuer &thorn;e lesse Alexander had &thorn;e victorye.
And &thorn;a&ntail; he went to Damaske, & Ensegge&dtail; it & wanne
it, and fra thethy&ntail; he went to Sydon & wan it.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he went vnto &thorn;e Citee of Tyre and layde Ensegge
abowte it, and [in] &thorn;is Ensegge he laye many a day. And thare
 
<PB N="16">
his Oste suffre&dtail; many dysesse&yogh;.  For &thorn;at Cite was so
strange in it-selfe by-cause of &thorn;e groun&dtail;, &thorn;at it
was sett apo&ntail;, and by-cause of grete towres & many &thorn;at
ware abowte it, and also bicause it was so enclose&dtail; wit the see
&thorn;at it myghte noghte lightly<MILESTONE N="5" UNIT="leaf"> be wonne&ntail; by nane assawte. Alexander &thorn;a&ntail; vmbithoghte hym, one what wyse he myghte best co&mtail; to for to destruy &thorn;is citee, and he gerte make a
grete baste&llbar; of tree, and sett it apo&ntail; schippes in
&thorn;e see eue&ntail; forgaynes &thorn;e cete, so &thorn;at
&thorn;are myghte no shippe&yogh; come nere the haue&ntail; for to
vetaille &thorn;e Citee or suppoe&llbar; it wit me&ntail; by-cause of
&thorn;e baste&llbar;e.  In &thorn;e mene tyme Alexander Oste hade
grete defawte of vetay&llbar;s, and &thorn;a&ntail; he sent lettres
vnto Iadus, &thorn;at at that tyme was bischoppe & gouernoure of
