<P>Whe&ntail; &thorn;e messangers &thorn;at were sent fra Darius come
to king Alexander, &thorn;ay gaffe hym the lettres, and &thorn;e
ba&llbar;e & o&thorn;er certane Iapes, &thorn;at &thorn;e emperour
sent hym in scorne.  And Alexander tuke &thorn;e lettres, and gert
rede it openly by-fore alle me&ntail;, and Alexander knyghtes when
&thorn;ay herde &thorn;e tenour of &thorn;e lettres ware gretly
astonayde and wonder heuy.  And whe&ntail; Alexander sawe
&thorn;a&mtail; so heuy by cause of &thorn;e lettre, he saide vn-to
&thorn;am: 'a a, my worthy knyghtis,' quo&thorn; he, 'are &yogh;e
fere&dtail; for &thorn;e prowde worde&yogh; &thorn;at are contened in
Darius lettres, wate &yogh;e noghte wele &thorn;at hunde&yogh;,
&thorn;at berkes<MILESTONE N="8" UNIT="leaf"> meki&llbar;, byte&yogh; me&ntail; noghte so sone, als
doe&yogh; hundes &thorn;at comme&yogh; one me&ntail; wit-outten
berkynge.  We trewe wele &thorn;e lettre says sothe of some
thynge&yogh;, &thorn;at es to saye, of &thorn;e grete plentee of
golde, &thorn;at Darius sais he hase.  And &thorn;arefore late vs
manly feghte wit hym and we sa&llbar; hafe &thorn;at golde.  For
&thorn;e grete multitude of his golde, als me thynke, schulde gare vs
be balde and hardy for to fighte wit hym manly.'
</P>
<P>When Alexander ha&dtail; saide thir worde&yogh; he bade his
knyghtis take the messangers of Darius and byn&dtail; &thorn;aire
hande&yogh; bi-hynde &thorn;a&mtail;, & lede &thorn;a&mtail; furthe to
the galowes, & hynge &thorn;a&mtail;.  And &thorn;ay tuke &thorn;e
messangers & bande &thorn;a&mtail;, and began for to lode &thorn;am
furthe to &thorn;e galowes-warde, and &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
messengers biga&ntail; for to crye rewfully vnti&llbar; Alexander &
say&dtail;: 'A, A wirchipfu&llbar; lorde & kynge', quo&thorn;
&thorn;ay, ' whate hafe we trespaste, &thorn;at we scha&llbar; be
haungede for oure kynges dedis'.  And &thorn;a&ntail; kyng Alexander
ansuer&dtail;: '&thorn;e worde&yogh; of &yogh;our Emperour',
quo&thorn; he, ' gers me do &thorn;is, &thorn;at sent &yogh;ow vn-to
me, as vnto a theeffe, as &thorn;e
<PB N="23">
lettre whilke &yogh;e broghte witnesse&yogh;': 'A, A lorde',
quo&thorn; &thorn;ay, 'oure emperour sent thus to &yogh;ou: for
&yogh;our powere & &yogh;our myghte was unknawwen vn-ti&llbar; hym.
Bot we be-seke &yogh;ow late&yogh; vs gaa, and we scha&llbar; mak
aknawe&ntail; vnti&llbar; hym &yogh;our grete glory, &yogh;our
ryaltee, & &yogh;our noblaye.'
</P>
<P>&THORN;a&ntail; kyng Alexander bad&dtail; his knyghtis lowse
&thorn;a&mtail;, and bryng &thorn;a&mtail; in-ti&llbar; his
hau&llbar;e, to &thorn;e mete.  And thare he made &thorn;a&mtail; a
grete feste & a rya&llbar;.  And as &thorn;ay satt at the mete,
&thorn;ir messangers saide vn ti&llbar; Alexander, 'lorde,' quo&thorn;
&thorn;ay, 'if it be plesynge to &yogh;our hye maiestee sende&yogh;
with vs a thowsand of doghty me&ntail; of armes, and we sa&llbar;
delyuer &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;e Emperour Darius,' and Alexander
ansuerde agayne & sai&dtail; 'Sittes sti&llbar;e', quo&thorn; he, '&
makes &yogh;ow mery.  For I te&llbar; &yogh;ow in certayne, for
&thorn;e betrayinge of &yogh;our kynge, I wi&llbar; noghte graunt
&yogh;ow a knyghte wit &yogh;ow'.  Apon &thorn;e morne, Alexander gart
write a lettre vn-to Darius, whareoffe &thorn;e tenour was this.</P>
<Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<HEAD REND="gothic">&THORN;e letter of Alexandere</HEAD>
<P>'Alexander, the so&ntail; of Philippe & of qwene Olympias, vn-to
Darius, kyng of &thorn;e lan&dtail; &thorn;at schynes wit &thorn;e
godde&yogh; of Perse, we sende.  If we graythely & sothefastly
be-halde oure selfe &thorn;are es na thynge &thorn;at we here hafe
&thorn;at we may bi righte ca&llbar;e ours, bot a&llbar; it es lent vs
for a tyme.  For a&llbar;e we &thorn;at ere whirlede aboute wit
&thorn;e whele of fortune, now ere we broghte fra reches in-to
pouerte: now fra myrthe & ioy in-to Sorowe & heuynssse; and
agaynwarde&yogh; : and now fra heghte, we are plungede in-to lawnesse.
&THORN;are-fore &thorn;are schulde na ma&ntail; &thorn;at es sett in
hye degre triste to meki&llbar; in his hyenesse, that, thurgh pride &
vayne glorye, he schulde despyse &thorn;e dedis of o&thorn;er
me&ntail; lesse<MILESTONE N="8 bk." UNIT="leaf"> &thorn;an he.  For he wate neuer how sone &thorn;e
whele of fortune may turne abowte, and caste hym doune to lawe
degree, &thorn;at sitte&yogh; hye o&ntail;-lofte: and rayse hym to hye
wirchipe and grete noblaye &thorn;at bifore was pore and in lawe
degree.  And &thorn;arefore the aughte to thynke grete schame,
&thorn;at swilke a worthy emperour as me&ntail; halde&yogh; the,
schulde sende swylke
 
<PB N="24">
a message vnto me so littill a ma&ntail; and so pore.  For &thorn;ou
ert euen lyke to &thorn;e sonne, as thi selfe says, sittande in
&thorn;e trone of Nitas wit &thorn;e godde&yogh; of Perse.  Bot
godde&yogh; &thorn;at euermare are liffaunde & neuermare dye&yogh;,
deyne&yogh; no&yogh;te for to hafe &thorn;e felachipe of dedely
me&ntail;.  Sekerly I am a dedely ma&ntail;; and to &thorn;e I come as
to a dedely man, for to feghte wit the.  Bot &thorn;ou &thorn;at arte
so grete & so gloryous & calle&yogh; thi selfe vndedely, &THORN;ou
sa&llbar; wynne na thynge of me, if a&llbar;e &thorn;ou hafe &thorn;e
ouerhande of me.  For &thorn;ou hase ouercomme&ntail; bot a
litti&llbar; ma&ntail;, and a theeffe als &thorn;ou sayse. And if I
hafe &thorn;e ouerhande ouer the, It sa&llbar; be to me &thorn;e
gretteste wirchipe &thorn;at euere byfe&llbar; me, for als meki&llbar;
als I sa&llbar; hafe &thorn;e victorye of &thorn;e worthieste emperour
of &thorn;e werlde.  Bot &thorn;are &thorn;ou saide, &thorn;at, in
&thorn;e rewme of Perse, es so grete plentee of golde, &thorn;ou hase
scharpede oure herti&yogh;, and made mare balde for to feghte with
the, & for to wynne &thorn;at golde; for to relefe oure pouerte
wit-a&llbar;, & putte awaye our nede whilke &thorn;ou says we hafe.
In &thorn;at also, &thorn;at &thorn;ou sent vs a hande-ba&llbar;e and
o&thorn;er barne-laykaynes, &thorn;ou prophicyed ri&yogh;te, and
betaken&dtail; bi-fore, thynges &thorn;at we trewe, thurg&hbar;
godde&yogh; helpe, sa&llbar; fa&llbar;e vn-ti&llbar; vs.  By &thorn;e
rowndenes of &thorn;e ba&llbar;e, we vnderstande all the werl&dtail;
aboute vs, &thorn;e whilke sa&llbar; fa&llbar;e vnder oure
subieccio&ntail;.  Bi &thorn;e tane of &thorn;e laykanes &thorn;at
&thorn;ou sent vs, &thorn;e whilke es made of wande&yogh; and
cruke&yogh; donwarde&yogh; at &thorn;e oueren&dtail;, we vnderstand
&thorn;at a&llbar; &thorn;e kynges of &thorn;e werlde, and a&llbar;
&thorn;e grete lorde&yogh;, sa&llbar; lowte ti&llbar; vs.  Bi &thorn;e
to&thorn;er layka&ntail;, &thorn;at es of golde, and hase apon it, as
it ware, a manne&yogh; hede, we vnderstande &thorn;at we sa&llbar;
hafe &thorn;e victorye of a&llbar; me&ntail; and neuer be
ouercomme&ntail;.  And &thorn;ou &thorn;at ert so grete & so myghty
hase now onwarde&yogh; sent vs trybute, in als meke&llbar; als
&thorn;ou sent vs a handba&llbar;e, and &thorn;ir o&thorn;er thynges
&thorn;at I rehersed by-fore, the whilke contene&yogh; in
&thorn;a&mtail; so grete dignyte&yogh;.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>
<P>Whe&ntail; &thorn;is lettre was wrete&ntail;, Alexander
calle&dtail; till &thorn;e messangers of &thorn;e Emperour of Perse,
and gaffe &thorn;a&mtail; riche gyftes and betuke &thorn;am &thorn;e
lettre, and bad&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; bere it to &thorn;aire lorde.
And &thorn;a&ntail; Alexander semble&dtail; his Oste, and by-ga&ntail;
for to wende towarde Perse.  When the messangers of Perse come to
&thorn;e emperour &thorn;ay talde hym of &thorn;e grete ryaltee of
kyng Alexander<MILESTONE N="9" UNIT="leaf"> and tuke hym the letters &thorn;at Alexander sent
hy&mtail;.  And
<PB N="25">
&thorn;e emperour garte rede &thorn;a&mtail;.  And when he her&dtail;
&thorn;a&mtail; redde he was wonder wrathe, and sent a lettre belyue
vn-ti&llbar; twa grete lorde&yogh; that had&dtail; &thorn;e gouernance
of &thorn;e empire vnder hym sayan&dtail; to &thorn;am on this wiese.
<Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P>'Darius kyng of kynges and lorde of lordes vnti&llbar; oure trewe
lege&yogh; Primus & Antyochus, gretynge and ioy. We here te&llbar;
&thorn;at Alexander, Philippe sonne of Macedoyne, es so heghe raysede
in pryde, &thorn;at he es rebe&llbar;e agaynes vs, & es comme&ntail;
in-ti&llbar; Asye, and hase distroye&dtail; it vtterly.  And &yogh;itt
hym thynke no&yogh;te this ynoghe, bot he purpose&yogh; hym for to
come nere vs, and do &thorn;e same ti&llbar; o&thorn;erre cuntre&yogh;
of oure empire as he hase done ty&llbar; Asye.  Whare-fore we comande
&yogh;owe o payne of &yogh;our legeance, &thorn;at &yogh;e semble
&thorn;e grete me&ntail; & &thorn;e worthy of ours empyre, wit
o&thorn;er of our trewe lege&yogh;; and, in a&llbar; &thorn;e haste
&thorn;at &yogh;e may, gase & counters &yogh;one childe, takan&dtail;
hym, and bryngan&dtail; hym bi-fore oure presence, &thorn;at we may
lasche hym wele, als a wanto&ntail; childe schulde be: and clethe hym
in purpoure; & so sen&dtail; hym ti&llbar; his moder Olympias wele
chastyede.  For it seme&yogh; no&yogh;te to be a feghter: but for to
vse childe gamme&yogh;.
</P>
</BODY></TEXT></Q> </P><P>Thire twa lordes Primus and Antyochus, when
&thorn;ay hadde redde this lettre of &thorn;e emperour, &thorn;ay
wrate agayne vnti&llbar; him on this wyse.  <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT><BODY><P>'Vn-to Darius, kyng of kynge&yogh;, grete
god&dtail;, Primus & Antiochus, seruyce &thorn;at &thorn;ay ka&ntail;
do.  To &yogh;our heghe maieste we make it aknawe&ntail;, &thorn;at
&thorn;e childe Alexandere, whilke &yogh;e speke off, hase a&llbar;
vtterly distroye&dtail; &yogh;our cuntree.  And we semble&dtail; a
grete multytude of folke, and faughte wit hym; bot he hase discomfit
vs, and we were fayne for to flee.  For unnethe myghte any of vs wynne
awaye wit &thorn;e lyfe.  &THORN;are-fore we &thorn;at &yogh;e say ere
helpers vnto &yogh;owe, beseke&yogh; &yogh;our hye maiestee that
&yogh;e sen&dtail; su&mtail; socoure ti&llbar; vs &yogh;our trewe
leges.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q> Whe&ntail; Darius hadde redde &thorn;is
lettre, &thorn;are come ano&thorn;er messanger till hym and talde hym
&thorn;at Alexander and his Oste hade lugede &thorn;am appon the water
of Strume.  And whe&ntail; Darius her&dtail; &thorn;at he wrate
ano&thorn;er lettre vnti&llbar; Alexander, of whilke &thorn;is was
&thorn;e tenour.
</P>
<P><Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT><BODY><P>' Darius, kyng of kynges, and lorde
of lorde&yogh;, vn-ti&llbar; oure seruande Alexander.  Thorowte
a&llbar; &thorn;e werlde &thorn;e name of
 
<PB N="26">
Darius es prayse&dtail; & commende&dtail;.  Oure godde&yogh; also hase
it wrete&ntail; in thaire bukes.  How tha&ntail; durste &thorn;ou be
so balde, for to passe so many waters, and see&yogh;, Mountaynes &
cragge&yogh;, for to werraye agaynes oure roya&llbar;e maiestee.  A
grete wirchi&ptail; me thynke it<MILESTONE N="9 bk." UNIT="leaf"> ware to &thorn;e, if &thorn;ou myghte
mawgre oures, hafe in possessiou&ntail; &thorn;e kyngdome of Macedoyne
a&llbar; anely, wit-owtten mare. Thare-fore the es better amen&dtail;
&thorn;e of thi mysededis, &thorn;an we take swilke wreke appo&ntail;
the, &thorn;at o&thorn;er me&ntail; take bisne &thorn;areby, se&ntail;
a&llbar;e &thorn;e erthe wit-owtten oure lordchipe, may be callede
wedowe.  Torne agayne &thorn;are-fore, we consaile &thorn;e, in-to
thy&ntail; awen&ntail; cuntree, are oure wrethe and oure wreke
fa&llbar;e apo&ntail; &thorn;e.  Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse, &thorn;at oure
wirchippe & oure grete noblaye be sumwhate knawe&ntail; to &thorn;e,
we sende the a malefu&llbar; of chesebo&llbar;e sede, in takennyng
&thorn;are-of.  Luke if &thorn;ou may nombir & te&llbar;e a&llbar;
&thorn;ir chessebo&llbar;e sede&yogh;, & if &thorn;ou do &thorn;att
&thorn;a&ntail; may &thorn;e folke of oure oste be nowmer&dtail;.  And
if &thorn;ou may no&yogh;te do &thorn;at oure folke may no&yogh;te be
nowmer&dtail;.  &THORN;arefor turnee hame agayne in-to &thorn;i
cuntree and lefe &thorn;i foly &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase bygu&ntail;,
and take na mare apo&ntail; &thorn;e swilke a presumpcion, for I
te&llbar; &thorn;e we haffe me&ntail; of armes wit-oute
nowmmere'.</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>

</P> <P>Whe&ntail; &thorn;e Messangers
of Darius come ti&llbar; Alexander, &thorn;ay tuk hym &thorn;e lettre
and &thorn;e malefu&llbar; of chessebo&llbar;e sede&yogh;.  Alexander
&thorn;a&ntail; gerte rede &thorn;e letter.  And sythe&ntail; he putt
his han&dtail; in &thorn;e male, and tuke of &thorn;e chessebo&llbar;e
sede&yogh; & putt in his mouthe, & chewe&dtail; it, & said, 'I see
wele', quo&thorn; he, '&thorn;at he hase many me&ntail;, bot &thorn;ay
are ri&yogh;te softe as this sede&yogh; are.'  In &thorn;e mene tyme
&thorn;are come a Measanger ti&llbar; Alexander fra Macedoyne: and
talde hym &thorn;at his Moder Olympias was grefe seke.  And [when]
Alexander her&dtail; &thorn;is, he was wonder heuy.  Neuer &thorn;e
lesse, he wrate vn to Darius a lettre, &thorn;at spakke o&ntail; this
wyse.  <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P>'Alexander &thorn;e so&ntail; of Philippe & of qwene Olympias vn-to
Darius kynge of Perse, we sende.  We do &thorn;e wele to wiete
&thorn;at we hafe herde certane tythynge&yogh;, whilke gers vs
agayne&yogh; oure wi&llbar; do &thorn;at we now sa&llbar; saye.  Bot
trow &thorn;ou no&yogh;te &thorn;at we for fere or dowte of thi pride
and &thorn;i vayne glorye turne hame agayne now ti&llbar; oure
awen&ntail; cuntre, Bot a&llbar; anely for to vesett
<PB N="27">
oure Moder Olympias, whilke lygges grefe seke.  Bot wete pou wele, wit
in schorte ty&mtail;, we scha&llbar; haste vs agayne, wit a grete
nowmere of fresche knyghtis.  And ri&yogh;te als &thorn;ou sent vs a
malefe&llbar; of chessobolle sede&yogh;; so we sende &thorn;e here a
litti&llbar; peper.  For &thorn;ou schulde witte &thorn;at ri&yogh;te
as &thorn;e scharpenes of &thorn;is litti&llbar; peper passe&yogh;
&thorn;e multitude of &thorn;e chessebo&llbar;e sede&yogh;, ri&yogh;te
so &thorn;e grete multitude of &thorn;e Persyenes sa&llbar; be
ouer-come&ntail; wit a fewe knyghtis of
Macedoyne.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>
</P>
<P>This lettre be-kende Alexander to &thorn;e knyghtis of Darius,
&thorn;e peper also, & ba&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; bere &thorn;a&mtail;
to &thorn;e emperour.  And he gaffe &thorn;a&mtail; grete gyftes and
riche, and sent &thorn;a&mtail; furthe.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he
turnede<MILESTONE N="10" UNIT="leaf"> agayne wit his Oste towarde Macedoyne.
</P>
<P>Thare was &thorn;e same tyme a wonder wyse ma&ntail; of werre
&thorn;e whilke highte Amorca, and he was prynce-werres in Araby, and
lay &thorn;are wit a grete multitude of me&ntail; in awayte of
Alexander & his Oste. And whe&ntail; he herde te&llbar; of &thorn;e
commyng of Alexander, he redie&dtail; hym for to kepe hym.  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;ay mett, &thorn;ay faught to-geder a&llbar; &thorn;e
daye fra &thorn;e morne ti&llbar; &thorn;e eue&ntail;.  And so
&thorn;ay dide a&llbar; &thorn;ase thre deyes.  And &thorn;are was so
meki&llbar; folke dede in &thorn;at bataile, &thorn;at &thorn;e sone
wexe eclipte & wit-drewe his lighte, vggande for to see so meki&llbar;
scheddynge of blude.  Bot at laste &thorn;e Percyenes ware so
thikke-falde felle&dtail; to &thorn;e grounde, &thorn;at &thorn;aire
prynce Amorca turne&dtail; &thorn;e bakke & fled&dtail;, and
vnnethe&yogh; myghte wyn&ntail; awaye, and a fewe wit hym.  So hastyly
fled&dtail; Amorca, &thorn;at he come nerehan&dtail; alsone to Darius,
as his measagers di&dtail; &thorn;at come fra Alexander, and
fan&dtail; Darius haldan&dtail; &thorn;e lettre in his hande,
&thorn;at Alexander sent hy&mtail;, and spirrande what Alexander
di&dtail; wit &thorn;e chessbolle sede&yogh;.  And &thorn;e messangers
ansuer&dtail; & sai&dtail;: ' He tuke of &thorn;o chessbo&llbar;e
sede&yogh;', quo&thorn; &thorn;ay, 'and chewe&dtail; of
&thorn;a&mtail;, & sai&dtail;. I see wele,' quo&thorn; he, '&thorn;at
Darius hase many me&ntail;, bot &thorn;ay are wonder softe'; And than
Darius tuk of &thorn;e peper, &thorn;at Alexander sent, and putt in
his mouthe and chewe&dtail; it.  And when he felide &thorn;e strenghe
of it, and &thorn;e grete hete, he syghede sare, and saide: 'Alexander
knyghtis', quo&thorn; he, 'are bot fewe, bot and &thorn;ay be als
strange in &thorn;a&mtail; selfe, as &thorn;is peper es in it selfe,
&thorn;ay sa&llbar; fynde nane in &thorn;is werlde &thorn;at may
agaynestande &thorn;a&mtail;.'  And &thorn;an ansuerde Amorca & saide,
'Forsothe, lorde', quo&thorn; he, '&yogh;e
 
<PB N="28">
say sothe, Alexander hase few knyghtis, bot &thorn;ay ere strange,
&thorn;at hase slae&ntail; my knyghtis &thorn;at ware so many, so
&thorn;at vnnethe&yogh; myghte I eschappe owte of &thorn;aire
hande&yogh;.'  Alexander, if a&llbar;e he hade &thorn;e victorye of
his enemys, he bare hym neuer &thorn;e hiere &thorn;are-fore, ne
empridede hym no&yogh;te &thorn;are-of.  Bot bathe Percyene&yogh; &
the Macedoyns &thorn;at ware slae&ntail;, he gert brynge to
berye&llbar;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he come wit his Oste in-to
Ceci&llbar;, whare many Cite&yogh; submyt
&thorn;a&mtail; v&ntail;-ti&llbar; hym, and of that rewme, &thorn;are
went wit hy&mtail;: xvij. M. <NOTE ID="n3">In printed text, "&lbar;" inserted superscript above "M."</NOTE> feghtynge me&ntail;.  And fra thethy&ntail; he come ti&llbar; Ysaury, &thorn;e whilke,
wit-owtte&ntail; any agayne standynge, was &yogh;olden vnti&llbar;
hym.  And Alexander went vp apo&ntail; &thorn;e Mounte Taurus, and
fande &thorn;are a citee &thorn;at me&ntail; callede Persypolis, and
thare he tuk wit hym a certane of me&ntail; of Armes, and went so
thurgh Asye, and wa&ntail; many Cite&yogh;.  And so he come in-to
Frigy, and went in-to &thorn;o temple of &thorn;e so&ntail;, and thare
he made sacrafyce to &thorn;e so&ntail;.  Fra thethy&ntail;, he come
to a reuere, &thorn;at es calle&dtail; Stamandra, and &thorn;are he
sai&dtail; ti&llbar; his men.  'Blyste mote &yogh;e be',<MILESTONE
N="10 bk." UNIT="leaf"> quo&thorn; he, '&thorn;at hase gety&ntail; &thorn;e comendacions & &thorn;e
