</P>
<P>The Athenyenes red&dtail; &thorn;is lettre and &thorn;an &thorn;ay
bigan to crye one highte.  And ane, &thorn;at highte Eschi&llbar;e,
stode vp amange&yogh; &thorn;a&mtail;, and sai&dtail;: 'It es fully my
conse&llbar;,' quo&thorn; he, '&thorn;at we o&ntail; na wise assent
[to thise] worde&yogh; of Alexander.'  Alle &thorn;e folke
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;at was gadirde &thorn;are, prayed &thorn;e
philosophre Demostines, &thorn;at he walde te&llbar; &thorn;a&mtail;
his conselle, as touchynge &thorn;at matere. And he stude vp, &
bad&dtail; a&llbar; me&ntail; be sti&llbar;. And &thorn;a&ntail; he
sai&dtail; vn-to &thorn;a&mtail;.  'Sirs,' quo&thorn; he, 'I pray
&yogh;ow takes tent vn-to my worde&yogh; & herkenes gudly what I
sa&llbar; say.  If &yogh;e fele &yogh;ow of power, for ti&llbar;
agayne-stande Alexander, & to supprise hym, &thorn;a&ntail; feghtes
wit hym manly, and obeys no&yogh;te ti&llbar; his worde&yogh;.  And if
&yogh;e suppose &yogh;e be no&yogh;te strange ynoghe to feghte wit
hy&mtail; &thorn;an here&yogh; hy&mtail;, and obeys vn-ti&llbar;
hy&mtail;.  &yogh;e knawe wele, &thorn;at als oure eldirs telles vs,
&YOGH;erses was a grett kynge, & a myghty, and many victories he gatt.
And neuer &thorn;e lesse in Ellada he suffrede grete meschefe.  Bot
he, this Alexander, hase done many batai&llbar;es, in &thorn;e whilke
he suffrede neuer disese bot alwaye had &thorn;e ouerhande.  &THORN;e
Thirienes, I pray &yogh;ow, ware [&thorn;ai] no&yogh;te balde knyghtes
and strange, and a&llbar; &thorn;aire lyfe hade bene excercysede in
Armes ?  And whate profitede &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;aire strenghe?
&THORN;e Thebienes also &thorn;at were so wyse, and so grete exercyse
hadde in armes, fra &thorn;e firste tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e citee was
bygge&dtail;, whare-off seruede &thorn;aire grete witt &thorn;a&mtail;,
and &thorn;aire grete strength, whe&ntail; Alexander assailede
&thorn;a&mtail;? &THORN;e Poliponiens faghte wit Alexander, bot
&thorn;ay myghte na while agayne-stande his men of armes.  Bot
also&ntail; &thorn;aire ware disconfit and slae&ntail;.  It es
no&yogh;te vnknawen vn-to &yogh;owe, how many citee&yogh;
caste&llbar;s & townne&yogh; for fere submittis &thorn;a&mtail;
vn-ti&llbar; hy&mtail; wit-owtte&ntail; any assawte gyffyng.
&THORN;arefore, it es no&yogh;te my consaile &thorn;at &yogh;e be
heuy, ne wrathe ti&llbar; Alexander
 
<PB N="34">
for Scrassageras.  For a&llbar; men knawes wele &thorn;at Alexander es
a wonder wyse ma&ntail; & a warre, & a ma&ntail; &thorn;at gouernes
hym by reso&ntail;; and &thorn;are-fore &yogh;e may wele wete, he
walde no&yogh;te putt Scrassageras oute of his lordechipe upo&ntail;
lesse &thorn;a&ntail; forfett vn-ti&llbar; hym.'  Whe&ntail; &thorn;e
Athenyenes had herde &thorn;ir worde&yogh;, &thorn;ay commedi&dtail;
gretly the consei&llbar;e of Demostines, and tha&ntail; they
ordeyne&dtail; a corou&ntail; of golde &thorn;e weghte of
<HI>.</HI>1<HI>.</HI> pounde, and sent Messangers &thorn;arewit, and
wit tribute vn-ti&llbar; Alexander, bot philosophres sent &thorn;ay
nane.<MILESTONE N="13" UNIT="leaf">  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ire Messangers come ti&llbar; Alexander,
&thorn;ay gaffe hym &thorn;e corou&ntail;. and &thorn;e tribute,
&thorn;at &thorn;e Athenyenes sent hy&mtail;, and talde hym &thorn;at
&thorn;ay ha&dtail; highte hym a grete nowmer of cate&llbar;e. And
whe&ntail; Alexander had her&dtail; &thorn;am, he vnderstode wele
&thorn;e conce&llbar; of Eschilus &thorn;at conce&llbar;&dtail;
&thorn;e Athenyenes to agaynestan&dtail; hy&mtail;, and also &thorn;e
conce&llbar; of Demostenes that conce&llbar;de &thorn;a&mtail;
&thorn;e contrary, and &thorn;a&ntail; he wrate a lettre to
&thorn;a&mtail; whare-of the Tenoure was this.  </P><Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P>'Alexander &thorn;e son of Philippe and quene Olympias, for
&thorn;e name of kynge wi&llbar; we no&yogh;te take apon vs, before we
hafe oure enemys vnder oure subieccion: vn-to &thorn;e Athenyenes
gretyng.  It es no&yogh;te oure entent to come in &yogh;our citee wit
oure oste, Bot allanly to come & dispuyte wit &yogh;our philosophres,
and to asche &thorn;a&mtail; certane questyons, Oure purposse was also
to hafe declare&dtail; for oure trewe legge&yogh; & oure gude
Frende&yogh;.  Bot &yogh;our dede&yogh; proues &thorn;e contrary, as
it done vs ti&llbar; vnderstande. Oure godde&yogh; we take to
witnesse, &thorn;at whilke of &yogh;ow so ryse&yogh; agayne&yogh; vs,
we sa&llbar; take swilke wreke apo&ntail; hym &thorn;at o&thorn;er
me&ntail; sa&llbar; take ensample &thorn;are-by.  Bot &yogh;e ale
schrewes, and euy&llbar; men, euer mare trowe&yogh; i&llbar;, and
thynkes i&llbar;.  Wate &yogh;e no&yogh;te wele &thorn;at &thorn;e
Thebienes &thorn;at raise agaynes vs, had&dtail; &thorn;aire mede als
&thorn;ay disserue&dtail;. And &yogh;e haffan&dtail; in vs a wrange
consayte, blame&yogh; vs, For we putt Scrassageras owte of his Office
the whilke forfett gretly agaynes oure maieste.  We sent vn-to
&yogh;ow bi lettre for te&ntail; philosophres, bot &yogh;e, no&yogh;te
knawande oure grete powere & oure myghte, despyse&dtail; oure
maundement and walde no&yogh;te fulfi&llbar; it.  Neuer &thorn;e les
if a&llbar; &yogh;e hafe offendid agaynes
<PB N="35">
vs whider-towarde and bene disobeyande ti&llbar; oure maiestee, we
forgiffe &yogh;ow a&llbar; &yogh;our gilt, and &thorn;e greuance
&thorn;at &yogh;e hafe don vs, so &thorn;at &yogh;e be obeyande
vn-ti&llbar; vs, fra &thorn;is tyme forwarde.  Comforthes &yogh;ow
&thorn;arefore & bee&yogh; mery, for of vs &yogh;e scha&llbar; hafe na
greuance ne na disesse be-cause &yogh;e di&dtail; after &thorn;e
conce&llbar; of Demostynes.</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>

<P>Whe&ntail; &thorn;e Athenyenes her&dtail; &thorn;is lettre
red&dtail;, &thorn;ay ware ri&yogh;te glad&dtail;, and &thorn;a&ntail;
Alexander & his Oste went fra thethy&ntail; vn-to Lacedoyne.  Bot
&thorn;e Lacedouns walde one na wyse obey vn-ti&llbar;
Alexander, bot sai&dtail; ilka&ntail; of &thorn;a&mtail; ti&llbar;
o&thorn;er, 'latt vs no&yogh;te be lykke &thorn;e Athenyenes,'
quo&thorn; &thorn;ay, '&thorn;at drede &thorn;e manaschynge, and
&thorn;e boste of Alexander bot late vs schewe oure my&yogh;te, and
oure strenghe and manly defende<MILESTONE N="13 bk." UNIT="leaf"> oure citee agayne&yogh; hym.' Whe&ntail; &thorn;ay had&dtail; saide, &thorn;ay spere&dtail; &thorn;e &yogh;ates of &thorn;e cetee faste, and went manly to &thorn;e walles.
And a grete nowmer of &thorn;a&mtail; tuke &thorn;a&mtail;
schippe&yogh; & went to &thorn;e see, a grete nauy, to feghte wit
Alexander are he come to lande.  And whe&ntail; Alexander saw this, he
sent a lettre to &thorn;a&mtail; sayand on this wyse.  <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P>'Alexander &thorn;e so&ntail; of Philippe and of &thorn;e quene
Olympias vn-to &thorn;e Lacedounes we sende.  We conce&llbar;
&yogh;ow, &thorn;at &thorn;at, that &yogh;our elders hase lefte
&yogh;ow, &yogh;e kepe hale & sound & in sauetee and lyfte&yogh;
no&yogh;te &yogh;our hende ouer hie to &thorn;e thynge&yogh; &thorn;at
&thorn;e may no&yogh;te reche to.  And if &yogh;e desire for to hafe
ioy of &yogh;our strenthe, dose swa &thorn;at &yogh;e be worthy to
hafe wirchipe of vs.  &THORN;arefore we comande &yogh;ow, &thorn;at
&yogh;e turne agayne wit &yogh;our schippe&yogh;, and leue&yogh;
&thorn;a&mtail;, & gase to lande by &yogh;our awen&ntail; fre
wi&llbar;; or sekirly I sa&llbar; sett fire in tha&mtail; & brynne
&thorn;a&mtail;.  And if &yogh;ee dispice oure commandement,
blame&yogh; na ma&ntail; bot &yogh;our selfe, if we wreke vs one
&yogh;owe.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>
</P>
<P>The Lacedounes red&dtail; &thorn;is lettre, and whe&ntail; it was
red&dtail;, &thorn;ay ware wonder heuy.  No&yogh;te for-thi &thorn;ay
redied &thorn;a&mtail; to feghte.  Bot Alexander arryue&dtail; in an
o&thorn;er coste, and come to &thorn;e citee are &thorn;ay wiste and
vmbylappe&dtail; &thorn;e citee one ilke a syde, and assaillede it
strangly & dange &thorn;e Lacedouns of &thorn;e walles & slewe many of
&thorn;a&mtail; & wounde&dtail; many, and sett fyre in &thorn;aire
schippe&yogh; & brynt &thorn;a&mtail;.  &THORN;e remanant of
&thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at ware lefte
<PB N="36">
appon lyfe, whe&ntail; &thorn;ay saw this grete meschefe come owte of
&thorn;e citee vn-ti&llbar; Alexander, & fe&llbar;e dou&ntail; at his
fete, & besoughte hym of mercy & of grace.  And Alexander ansuerd, 'I
come to &yogh;ow,' quo&thorn; he, 'meke & mylde, bot in &thorn;at
degre &yogh;e walde no&yogh;te ressayffe me, &thorn;arefore now are
&yogh;our schippe&yogh; brynne&dtail;, and &yogh;our citee
distruye&dtail;, & &yogh;our folke&yogh; slayne.  Warne&dtail; I
no&yogh;te be-fore &thorn;at &yogh;e schulde no&yogh;te heue &yogh;our
hande&yogh; ouer-hye to &thorn;e sternes, to &thorn;e whilke nane
erthely ma&ntail; may wyn&ntail;.  For wha so euer clymbe&yogh; hier,
&thorn;a&ntail; his fete may wyn&ntail; to su&mtail; halde, he
sa&llbar; falle onane dou&ntail; to &thorn;e grounde.  And
&thorn;arefore es &thorn;are a commone prouerbe: &THORN;at "wha sa
hewes to hie, &thorn;e chippes wi&llbar; fa&llbar;e in his egh."
&YOGH;e wende hafe done ti&llbar; vs as &yogh;our eldirs didde
sumetyme ti&llbar; kynge &yogh;erses, bot &yogh;our wenyng
dessayue&dtail; &yogh;ow. For &yogh;e myghte no&yogh;te agayne-stande
vs whe&ntail; we assaillede &yogh;ow.' Whan<MILESTONE N="14" UNIT="leaf"> he had&dtail; saide on
this wise, he gaffe &thorn;a&mtail; leue to gaa whare &thorn;ay walde.
And tha&ntail; he remouede thethy&ntail; & went to-warde
Cici&llbar;. And whe&ntail; &thorn;e emperour Darius her&dtail; tell
of &thorn;e comyng of Alexander, he was gretly abaiste and sent after
a&llbar; his prince&yogh;, Dukes & Erles, & o&thorn;er grete lordes, &
went ti&llbar; a consaile. And he saide vn-to &thorn;ai&mtail;, 'I see
wele,' quo&thorn; he, '&thorn;at he, this Alexander, &thorn;at gase
thus abowte werrayan&dtail;, waxe&yogh; gretly in wirchipe, and
ay-whare whare he comme&yogh; he hase &thorn;e victory. I wende he
had&dtail; bene a theeffe & a robbour, &thorn;at hadde went ti&llbar;
cuntre&yogh; &thorn;at ere wayke & feble, and durst no&yogh;te agayne-stande hy&mtail;, & robbe&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; & spoyle&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail;. Bot now, I see wele, he es a doghty ma&ntail; of
Armes, & a noble werrayour.  And ay &thorn;e mare &thorn;at I hafe
depraue&dtail; hy&mtail; and despyse&dtail; hym; &thorn;e mare
ryse&yogh; his name, & his wirchipe.  I sent hym a balle, a toppe, & a
scourge, for to lere barne-laykes; bot hym &thorn;at I calle&dtail; a
disciple, he seme&yogh; a mayster & whare-so-euer he gase, Fortune
gase wit hym.  &THORN;are-fore vs byhoue&yogh; to trete of oure hele,
& of oure pople&yogh;, and pute awaye all pride & a&llbar; foly: &
namare despisse Alexander, saynge &thorn;at he es noghte, by cause we
are emperour of Perse.  For his litti&llbar;nes waxes and ours gretnes
decresse&yogh;.  I hafe grete dowte, &thorn;at godde&yogh; forluke
helpe&yogh; hym, so &thorn;at whils we ere abowte, & wene&yogh; to
putte hym out of Ellada, we be spoyled, by hym, of &thorn;e rewme of
Perse.'
</P>
<P>Whe&ntail; Darius had&dtail; said thir worde&yogh;, his broder
Coriather
<PB N="37">
ansuer&dtail; & sai&dtail;, ' &thorn;ou hase here,' quo&thorn; he,
'gretly magnifie&dtail; & commendi&dtail; Alexander, in that,
&thorn;at &thorn;ou sais he es mare feruent for to come in-to Perse,
&thorn;a&ntail; we in-ti&llbar; Ellada.  And &thorn;arefore if it be
plesyng vn-to &yogh;our maiestee, vse &yogh;e &thorn;e maners of
Alexauder, and so sa&llbar; [&yogh;e] wele & peysably welde &yogh;our
empire & couquere many o&thorn;er rewmes.  Alexander, whe&ntail; he
gase to bataile and sa&llbar; feghte, he lates [nane] of his
prynce&yogh; ne his o&thorn;er lorde&yogh; gaa be-fore, & hym selfe
come by-hynde, bot he gase bi-fore &thorn;a&mtail; a&llbar;e, and so
rise&yogh; his wirchi&ptail; & his name.'
</P>
<P>Quo&dtail; Darius, 'whe&thorn;er awe me to take sa ensample at
Alexander, or Alexander at me.'  A prynce ansuerde & saide, '
Alexander,' quo&dtail; he, 'es a warrer ma&ntail; & a wyse, & hase
trespaste in na degree & &thorn;arefore he duse manly by hym selfe
a&llbar; &thorn;at he doe&yogh;.  For he hase taken &thorn;e fourme of
&thorn;e lyon&ntail;.'  'Whare-by knawes &thorn;ou &thorn;at,'
quo&thorn; Darius,<MILESTONE N="14 bk." UNIT="leaf"> and he ansuer&dtail; & saide, 'whate tyme,'
quo&thorn; he, '&thorn;at I was sent to Macedoyne for til aske tribute
of kyng Philippe, I saw, bi his Figure & his wise ansuere, &thorn;at
he schuld be a passyng ma&ntail;, bathe of witt, & of doynges.
Thare-fore, if it be plesyng vn-to &yogh;ow, I conse&llbar; &thorn;at
&yogh;e sende ti&llbar; a&llbar; &thorn;e lande&yogh; & cuntre&yogh;
&thorn;at lange&yogh; to &yogh;our empire, &thorn;at es to say to
Parthy & Medy, Appollamy, Mesopotamy, Ytaly, Bactri, and ti&llbar;
a&llbar; &thorn;e remenant for &thorn;ay ere subiete&yogh; vn-to
&yogh;ow a hundreth : c. and fifty l. of dyuerse folke.  To &thorn;e
lordes of all thire, I rede &yogh;e sende comnandyng &thorn;a&mtail;,
&thorn;at &thorn;ay come to &yogh;ow, in a&llbar; &thorn;e haste
&thorn;at &thorn;ay may, with a&llbar; &thorn;e me&ntail; &thorn;at
&thorn;ay may gett whilk ere able to ga to werre .  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;ay [ere] a&llbar; semble&dtail; to gedir late vs beseke oure
goddis of helpe.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Alexander whe&ntail; he
see&yogh; swilk a multitude of folke agaynes hym, his hert sa&llbar;
faile hy&mtail;, and his mens also.  And ow&thorn;er he sa&llbar; for
fere turne hame agayne ti&llbar; his awe&ntail; cuntree, or e&llbar;s
submytt hym vn-to &yogh;ow.'  And &thorn;a&ntail; ansuer&dtail;
ano&thorn;er prynce, & sayde, 'This es a gud conce&llbar;,' quo&thorn;
he, 'bot it es no&yogh;te profitable. Wate &thorn;ou no&yogh;te wele
&thorn;at a wolfe
 
<PB N="38">
chase&yogh; a grete floke of schepe & gerse &thorn;a&mtail; sparple.
Righte so, and &thorn;e wysdome of &thorn;e grekes passe&yogh;
o&thorn;er nacyons.'
</P>
<P>In this mene ty&mtail;, Alexander semble&dtail; a gret multitude of
folke to &thorn;e nowmer of cc of feghtynge me&ntail;, and remewed to
warde Perse, & come ti&llbar; a reuere &thorn;at es calle&dtail;
Mociona, of whilke &thorn;e water was wonder calde, & faire, & clere.
And Alexander had&dtail; a grete lyste for to be bathede
&thorn;are-in, and went in-to it & bathed hym, & waschede hym
&thorn;are-in, and also so&ntail; he fe&llbar;e in a feuer and a
heued-werke &thorn;are-wit, so &thorn;at he fure wonder i&llbar;.  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;e Macedoyns saw &thorn;aire lorde so grefe seke,
&thorn;ay were wonder heuy and reghte dredan&dtail; and said amanges
selfe: 'And Darius,' quod &thorn;ay, 'wete &thorn;at oure lorde
Alexander be &thorn;us seke, he sa&llbar; come & falle apo&ntail; vs
sodaynly, & fordo vs ilka&ntail;.  For, and we had&dtail; &thorn;e
hele of oure lorde Alexander, we had&dtail; comforth ynoghe & dredde
no nacyo&ntail;.'  Than kyng Alexander calle&dtail; ti&llbar; hym his
Phicisiene &thorn;af highte Philippe & bad&dtail; hym ordeyne hym a
Medcyne for his sekenes.  &THORN;is ilk Phicisiene<MILESTONE N="15" UNIT="leaf"> was bot a &yogh;ong ma&ntail;, bot he was a passyng kunnyng ma&ntail; and a sote&llbar; in
a&llbar; &thorn;e poyntes &thorn;at langed to phisic.  And he highte
Alexander, &thorn;at [by] a certane drynke he sulde onane make hym
a&llbar; hale.  Nowe fe&llbar; it, &thorn;at was wit Alexander a
prynce, &thorn;at highte Parmenius & was lorde of hermony.  This
prynce hade grete envy to &thorn;is phicsiene, bi-cause &thorn;at
Alexander luffede hym so passandly wele & belyfe he wrate ti&llbar;
Alexander, and warne&dtail; hym &thorn;at he schulde be warre wit
Phillippe his phicisiene, and on na wyse resayfe &thorn;at drynke
&thorn;at he walde gyffe hym.  For he sai&dtail; &thorn;at Darius had
highte to giffe hym his doghter to wyffe & his kyngdo&mtail; after his
dissesse if swa ware, &thorn;at he myghte be any crafte make ane ende
of hy&mtail;.  Whe&ntail; Alexander hadda red&dtail; &thorn;is lettre
he was na thynge trubble&dtail;, so meki&llbar; he tristede of &thorn;e
conscience of his phisician.
</P>
<P>In &thorn;e mane tyme, &thorn;is Phisician come ti&llbar; Alexander
wit &thorn;e forsaid drynke, and Alexander tuk &thorn;is drynke in a
hande & &thorn;e forsaid lettre in his o&thorn;er hande and
bihel&dtail; &thorn;e Phisician in &thorn;e vesage ri&yogh;te
scharpely.  To whome &thorn;e Phisician saide:
<PB N="39">
'wirchipfu&llbar; Emperour,' quo&thorn; he 'be na thyng fere&dtail;
bot drynke &thorn;e medcyne baldely,' and &thorn;a&ntail; onane
Alexander tuk this drynke, & schewe&dtail; Philippe &thorn;e lettre.
And whe&ntail; Philippe had redde &thorn;e lettre, he said ti&llbar;
Alexander: 'Now for sothe, my lorde,' quo&thorn; he, 'I take oure
goddes to witnesse &thorn;at I ne am no&yogh;te gilty of this
treso&ntail;, &thorn;at here es wrety&ntail;.'  Alexander
&thorn;a&ntail; was a&llbar; hale als euer he was, & calle&dtail;
vn-ti&llbar; Philyppe his phisician & enbrace&dtail; hym in his armes
& sai&dtail;: Philippe,' quo&thorn; he, 'knawes &thorn;ou how mekill
luffe & triste I hafe in the.  Firste I dranke thi medecyne, & syne I
schewede &thorn;e &thorn;e lettre &thorn;at was sent me agaynes the.'
'Mi lorde,' quo&thorn; Philippe, 'I beseke &yogh;ow &thorn;at
&yogh;e wolle vochesaffe to send after my&ntail; accusour, and do hym
come bi-fore &yogh;our presence &thorn;at &thorn;is lettre sent vn-to
&yogh;ow, and hase lere&dtail; me for to do swilk a hie treso&ntail;.
Be-lyfe &thorn;a&ntail; gerte Alexander send after Parmeny for to come
vn-ti&llbar; hym, and gerte &thorn;e sothe be serche&dtail;, & fande
&thorn;at he was worthy &thorn;e dede.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he gert
girde of his heue&dtail;.
</P>
<P>Fra &thorn;eine kyng Alexander remowe&dtail; his Oste ti&llbar;
hermony &thorn;e mare & onane he conquere&dtail; it, & put it vnder
his subieccio&ntail;.  And fra &thorn;eine he trauaile&dtail; many a
day<MILESTONE N="15 bk." UNIT="leaf"> wit his Oste, and at &thorn;e last e come ti&llbar; a cuntre
wonder drye, & fu&llbar; of creuesce&yogh; of cauerne&yogh;, & alde
cisternes whare na water myghte be funde&ntail;.  And Fra &thorn;eine
&thorn;ay passede thurg&hbar; a cuntree, &thorn;at es calle&dtail; Andrias,
to &thorn;e Reuere of Eufrates. And &thorn;are &thorn;ay lugede
&thorn;a&mtail;.  &THORN;an Alexander garte brynge many grete
tree&yogh;, for to make a brygge of ouer &thorn;at water, appo&ntail;
schippe&yogh;, and garte tye &thorn;a&mtail; Same&ntail; wit chenys of
Ire&ntail; & ire&ntail; nayle&yogh;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e brigge
was a&llbar; redy, he badde his knyghtes wende ouer apo&ntail; it.
Bot wha&ntail; &thorn;ay saw &thorn;e grete reuer ryne so swiftely and
with so a grate a byrre, thay dred &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at &thorn;e
brygge schulde fa&llbar;e.  For &thorn;ay supposede &thorn;e chenys
schuld breke be-cause of grete weghte.  And, when Alexander saw
&thorn;a&mtail; dredan&dtail; on this wyse, he gert hirde-me&ntail;,
&thorn;at were &thorn;are kepan&dtail; katell, wen&dtail; oner before,
and warnede &thorn;at &thorn;e Oste schulde folowe &thorn;a&mtail;.
Bot &yogh;it &thorn;e knyghtis ware ferde & durste noghte wende ouer.
Tha&ntail; was Alexander ri&yogh;te wrathe and callede vnti&llbar;
hym a&llbar; his prynces, & grete lorde&yogh;, and firste he went hym
selfe ouer
 
<PB N="40">
&thorn;e bryges, & a&llbar; his prynce&yogh; folowe&dtail; hym, and
sythe&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;e Oste.  Twa grete ryuers rynnes
thurg&hbar; Medee, Mesopotamy and Babiloyne, &thorn;at es to say Tygre
& Eufrates, and soo rynne&yogh; in-to &thorn;e reuere of Nilus.  When
Alexander & a&llbar; hys Oste ware past ouer Eufrates, he gert smyte
sonder &thorn;e brygge &thorn;at he had&dtail; gert make bifore, and
dissolue ilk a pece &thorn;are-off fra o&thorn;er.  And when his
knyghtis sawe that, &thorn;ay ware reghte heuy and murnede gretly
&thorn;arefore, and sai&dtail; emanges &thorn;am selfe, 'What
sa&llbar; we now doo,' quo&thorn; &thorn;ay, 'when we are harde
by-stadde wit oure enemys & walde flee.  For ouer &thorn;is reuere may
we no&yogh;te wyu&ntail;.'  And when Alexander perceyue&dtail;
&thorn;at murmoure of his folke, he said vn-to &thorn;a&mtail;.  'What
es &thorn;at,' quo&thorn; he, '&thorn;at &yogh;e say amange&yogh;
&yogh;ow, "If it fa&llbar;e &thorn;at we flee owte of &thorn;e
bataile."  Sothely, I late &yogh;ow wele wite, &thorn;at &thorn;is is
&thorn;e cause whi I garte for-do &thorn;is brygg, &thorn;at I gert
make; For-thi, &thorn;at ow&thorn;er we schulde feghte manly or
e&llbar;s if [we] walde flee, we schulde a&llbar; perische at anes and
a&llbar; drynke of a coppe.  For-whi &thorn;e victorye es no&yogh;te
arette&dtail; to &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at flie&yogh;, Bot to
&thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at habyde&yogh;, or folowes on &thorn;e chace.
&THORN;are-fore comforthe&yogh; &yogh;ow wele, & bese balde of hertis,
and thynke it bot a playe stalworthly to feghte.  For I say &yogh;ow
sekerly; we ne scha&llbar; neuer see Macedoyne, be-fore we hafe
ouercome&ntail; a&llbar; oure enemys, And &thorn;a&ntail; wit &thorn;e
victorie we sa&llbar; tourne hame agayne.
</P>
<P>In &thorn;is mene tyme, kyng Darius gadirde a grete multitude of
me&ntail; agaynes Alexander, and ordeyne&dtail; ouer &thorn;a&mtail;
fyve-hundreth<MILESTONE N="16" UNIT="leaf"> chyftaynes of grete lordes and luged hym wit his
me&ntail; apo&ntail; &thorn;e reuere of Tygre.  And one a day thir twa
kynges wit &thorn;aire bather Ostes mett to-gedir apo&ntail; a faire
felde and faughte to-gedir wonder egerly.  Bot sone Darius me&ntail;
hadd &thorn;e werre & &yogh;ode to grounde thikkfalde, slayne in
&thorn;e felde.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e remenante saw &thorn;at,
&thorn;ay tuk &thorn;a&mtail; to &thorn;e flighte. In Darius oste was
a ma&ntail; of Perse, a doghety, & a balde; to whaym Darius highte for
to giffe his doghter to wyfe, if so were, &thorn;at he myghte, by any
way, sla kyng Alexander.  This ma&ntail; gatt hym clethyng and Armour
like vn-to &thorn;e macedoyns, and went amange&yogh; &thorn;a&mtail;,
as &thorn;ay faghte, ay ti&llbar; he come by-hynd kyng Alexander.  And
also&ntail; als he come nere hym, he lifte his
<PB N="41">
swerde on heghte, & lete flye at hy&mtail; wit a&llbar; &thorn;e
myghte &thorn;at he hade, and hitt hym on &thorn;e heue&dtail; so
fercely, &thorn;at he perched his bacenett, and drewe &thorn;e blode
of hym. Whe&ntail; Alexander knyghtis saw that: &thorn;ay tuke hym
anone, & broghte hym bifore Alexander, and Alexander, supposyng
&thorn;at he hadde bene a macedoyne, saide vn-till
hym. 'Wirchipfu&llbar; man,' quo&thorn; he, '& doghety & strange what
ayled &thorn;e at me, for to giffe suylke a strake, knewe &thorn;ou
no&yogh;te wele &thorn;at it was I, Alexander &yogh;our helpere &
&yogh;our allere seruande.'  And [the] Percyene ansuer&dtail;, &
sai&dtail;, 'Wiete &thorn;ou wele wirchipfu&llbar; emperour,'
quo&thorn; he, 'I ne ame na macedoyne, bot I am a ma&ntail; of Perse;
and this dede I did&dtail;.  For kyng Darius made me a promysse of his
doghetir to wife, if I myghte brynge hym thi hei&dtail;.' Than kyng
Alexander called bi-for hym all his knyghtis and askede
&thorn;a&mtail; what &thorn;a&mtail; thoghte was for to do wit this
ma&ntail;.  Su&mtail; ansuerde & saide &thorn;a&mtail; thoghte it
beste to gerre smyte of his hei&dtail;, Sum for to putt hym to &thorn;e
fire for to brynne, Sum to gare drawe & hang hym.  And when Alexander
had herde &thorn;aire conce&llbar;, he ansuer&dtail; & said: 'Sirs,'
quo&thorn; he, 'what wrange or what defawte ca&ntail; &yogh;e fynde in
&thorn;is ma&ntail;, Se&ntail; he hase besie&dtail; hym ti&llbar; obey
ti&llbar; his lordes commandement, and at his power fulfille&dtail;
it.  Whilke of &yogh;ow, so deme&yogh; hym worthy to be dedde, es
worthy in tyme commynge to hafe &thorn;e same dome.  For if I commande
ane of &yogh;ow for to ga & sla Darius, &thorn;e same payne, that
&yogh;e deme &thorn;is ma&ntail; for to suffre, ware &yogh;e worthy
for to suffre &yogh;ourselfe of Darius, if &yogh;e my&yogh;te be
gety&ntail;.'  And<MILESTONE N="16 bk." UNIT="leaf"> &thorn;an he commande&dtail; &thorn;at he schulde
wende hame to his felawes wit-owtte&ntail; any harme.  When Darius
herde &thorn;at his lordes ware slayne in grete nowmer, he
gadere&dtail; a grete multitude of knyghtis and of foteme&ntail;, and
went vp on a hi&llbar; &thorn;at es calle&dtail; Taurisius, and thare
he made his mustre of his me&ntail;, supposynge &thorn;at he schuld
ouercome Alexander thurg&hbar; multitude of folke.  Bot also&ntail;
als &thorn;ay mett wit &thorn;aire bathere oste&yogh;, and biga&ntail;
for to fighte, Darius me&ntail; fled&dtail; and hymselfe also.  And
Alexander persuede hym vn-to &thorn;e citee of Bactria&ntail;, and
&thorn;are he luged hym, and offerde Sacrafice ti&llbar; his
godde&yogh;. And on &thorn;e morne he garte assaile &thorn;e
<PB N="42">
citee, and wanne it on werre. And in &thorn;e cheffe place
&thorn;are-of he sett his trone. And a&llbar; &thorn;ir o&thorn;er
cite&yogh; &thorn;at were abowte it, he wan&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail; o
werre, & putt &thorn;a&mtail; vnder his subieccio&ntail;.  In
&thorn;is ilke citee of Bactria&ntail;, he fande tresour
wit-owtte&ntail; nowmer, and also his moder, and his wyfe.
</P>
<P>And in &thorn;e mene tyme, whils Alexander lay at Batran:
&thorn;are come a prynce of Darius oste vn-ti&llbar; Alexander, & said
vn-ti&llbar; hy&mtail;, 'Wirchipfu&llbar; emperour,' quo&thorn; he, '
I hafe a lang tyme bene a knyght of Darius, and done hym grete
seruyce; and &yogh;itt to this day I had neuer na rewar&dtail; of
hym. And &thorn;are-fore if it like vn-to &yogh;owre maieste; take me
te&ntail; thowsande of &yogh;our me&ntail; of armes; and I hete
&yogh;ow, for to brynge to &yogh;our hande kyng Darius, & &thorn;e
maste parte of his oste.'  And whe&ntail; Alexander had herde
&thorn;is, he said vn-ti&llbar; hym. 'Frende,' quo&thorn; he, 'I
thanke &thorn;e meki&llbar; of thi faire promys. Neuer &thorn;e lesse,
I late &thorn;e wite my me&ntail; wi&llbar; no&yogh;te beleue
&thorn;at &thorn;ou wi&llbar; feghte agaynes thy&ntail; owen&ntail;
peple.'  In &thorn;e mene tyme a Prynce of Darius oste sent vn-till
hym a letter, of whilk &thorn;is was &thorn;e tenour.
</P>
<P><Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT><BODY><P>'To Darius, grete kyng of kynges,
his lordes whilke he hase ordeyned cheftaynes vnder hym Sende&yogh;
meke seruyce. Oftymes be-fore this hafe we wrete&ntail; to &yogh;our
maieste, and now agayne we writte vn-to &yogh;ow, & late&yogh;
&yogh;ow wite &thorn;at &thorn;e macedoynes & kyng Alexander, as wode
lyouns ere enterde<MILESTONE N="17" UNIT="leaf"> oure lande&yogh;, and a&llbar; oure strenthes, as a
wilde raueschande beste he hase destruyed: & oure knyghtes slayne.
And oppressed we are wit so grete tribulacionns, &thorn;at we [may] na
lengare suffre his mawgree, ne his malece bere.  Whare-fore, mekly we
be-seke &yogh;our benyngne maiestee, &thorn;at &yogh;e wi&llbar; drawe
to &yogh;oure mynde oure meke seruyce, and swilke socoure vouchsaffe
to sen&dtail; vs, &thorn;at we put off and agaynestande &thorn;e
violence & &thorn;e malice of oure fore-said enemys.'  Whe&ntail;
Darius had redde &thorn;is lettre, on ane he gert writte a lettir to
kyng Alexander, sayand on &thorn;is wyse.</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>
</P>
<P><Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT><BODY><P>' Daryus kyng of Perse and kyng of
kynge&yogh;, vn-to my seruande Alexander, I say.  Now late &thorn;are
es comme&ntail; ti&llbar; oure eres tythynge&yogh;: &thorn;at
&thorn;ou wene&yogh; to eue&ntail; thi littilhede ti&llbar; oure heghe
magnificence.  Bot Se&ntail; it es inpossible ti&llbar; a heuy asse,
wit<PB N="43">
owtte&ntail; wenges, or o&thorn;er instrumente&yogh; of flying, for to
be lifte vp to &thorn;e sternes, late no&yogh;te thy&ntail; hert be
raysede to hye in pride for &thorn;e victories &thorn;at &thorn;ou
hase gete&ntail;. We hafe wele herd te&llbar; &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase
done gentilly, and schewe&dtail; grete humanytee ti&llbar; oure moder,
oure wyfe, & oure childre, and &thorn;arefore I late &thorn;e wele
wite &thorn;at, als lang als &thorn;ou dose wele to &thorn;a&mtail;,
&thorn;ou sa&llbar; fynde me nane enemy to the. And if &thorn;ou do
i&llbar; to &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;ou sa&llbar; hafe &thorn;e enemytee
of me, and &thorn;are-fore spare &thorn;a&mtail; noghte, bot do to
&thorn;a&mtail; as &thorn;e liste. For somtyme &thorn;ou sa&llbar; see
& fele &thorn;e sentence of oure ire lighte apo&ntail; thi heghe
pride.' </P></BODY></TEXT></Q> Whe&ntail; Alexander had&dtail; redde
&thorn;is lettre he wrate hym Ano&thorn;er agayne whare-off &thorn;e
tenour was this.
</P>
<P><Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT><BODY><P>'Alexander &thorn;e so&ntail; of
Philippe & qwene Olympias to Darius kyng of Perse we write. Pride &
vayne glorie hase oure godde&yogh; a&llbar; way hate&dtail;; and
take&yogh; vengeance of dedly me&ntail; &thorn;at takes apo&ntail;
&thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;e name of immortalitee.  Bot &thorn;ou, als I
wele see, cessee&yogh; no&yogh;te &yogh;itt hider-to for to blasfeme
in a&llbar; &thorn;at &thorn;ou may.  Bot of that &thorn;at &thorn;ou
blame&yogh; me for &thorn;e benygnytes that I schewed &thorn;i moder,
&thorn;i wyfe, & &thorn;i childre; &thorn;ou ert moue&dtail; on a
lewe&dtail; fantasye.  For I late &thorn;e wele wyte, I did it
no&yogh;te<MILESTONE N="17 bk." UNIT="leaf"> for to be thanke&dtail; of the, ne for to hafe thi
Beneuolence &thorn;are-fore.  Bot it come of a gentilnes of oure
awen&ntail; hert, fownded in vertu. Of thee victories also whilke
&thorn;e forluke of god&dtail; hase sent vs, ere we na-thyng
enpriddede. For we knawe wele &thorn;at oure goddis alwaye helpes vs,
whilke &thorn;ou ilk a daye dispyse&yogh; & sette&yogh; at no&yogh;te.
And this sa&llbar; be &thorn;e laste letter &thorn;at I sa&llbar;
writte vn-to &thorn;e.  Beware if &thorn;ou wi&llbar;, For I say the
sekerly, I come to &thorn;e onane.' </P></BODY></TEXT></Q> &THORN;is lettre gaffe Alexander to &thorn;e messangers of Darius and many grete
gifte&yogh; &thorn;are wit.  Seyme, he sent ano&thorn;er lettre,
ti&llbar; his prynce&yogh; & his lorde&yogh;, of &thorn;is tenour.
</P>
<P><Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT><BODY><P>' Alexander, &thorn;e so&ntail; of
Philippe & of &thorn;e quene Olympias vn-to &thorn;e prynce&yogh; &
&thorn;e lorde&yogh; vnder our subieccio&ntail; in Capadoce, In
laodice, or ells whare duellan&dtail;, gretyng, & gude grace.  We charge
&yogh;ou & commande&yogh; &yogh;ow straytly &thorn;at ilka&ntail; of
&yogh;ow ordayne vs in a&llbar; &thorn;e haste &thorn;at &yogh;e may
j<HI REND="sup">m</HI> nete-hydes barke&dtail;, & send &thorn;a&mtail; ti&llbar;
Alexander, &thorn;at we and oure knyghtis may gere
<PB N="44">
make vs of &thorn;a&mtail; clethyng, & schoees; And wit cameles
&thorn;at &yogh;e haue at Alexsander gerre cary &thorn;a&mtail; to
&thorn;e water of Eufrates.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q> In &thorn;is mene
tyme a prynce of Darius, Nostande by name, wrate to Darius on
&thorn;is wise.
</P>
<P><Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT><BODY><P>'To Darius &thorn;e wirchipfull
grete god&dtail; his seruande Nostan&dtail; law seruyce.  Me aughte
no&yogh;te to sende swylk tythynge to &yogh;our ryalle maiestee, bot
grete nede gers me do it.  &THORN;are-fore be it knawe&ntail; vn-to
&yogh;our hie lordchipe, &thorn;at twa grete prynce&yogh; of
&yogh;ours,& I, hase foghte&ntail; wit kyng Alexander, And hy&mtail;
es falle&ntail; &thorn;e victorie, & slayne he hase thir twa worthy
prynce&yogh;, & mekill o&thorn;er folke, and I flee&dtail; greuously
wonde&dtail;.  And many worthi knyghtis of &yogh;ours hase for-saken
&yogh;our lordchipe & ioyned &thorn;a&mtail; ti&llbar; Alexander oste,
&thorn;e whilk he hase wirchipfully, and hase giffen grete lord-chipes
of &yogh;ours.' </P></BODY></TEXT></Q> And whe&ntail; Darius had
red&dtail; &thorn;is lettre, he sent in haste ti&llbar; Nostand, and
commande&dtail; hym for ti&llbar; ordeyne a grete Oste; and manfully
agaynestande &thorn;e folke of Macedoyne.  He sent also a lettre to
Porus kyng of Ynde, prayng hym to helpe hym agaynes Alexander, and
Porus wrate agayne in &thorn;is manere.
</P>
<P><Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT><BODY><P>' Porus, kyng of Ynde, vn-to
Darius, kyng of Perse, gretyng.  For &thorn;ou hase prayed vs to come
to the in helpynge<MILESTONE N="18" UNIT="leaf"> of the agaynes thyn enemys, we late the wete,
&thorn;at we are redy & alwaye hase bene, for to co&mtail; to helpe
&yogh;ow.  Bot as at &thorn;is tyme we are lettede to co&mtail; to
&yogh;ow, be-cause of grete seknesse &thorn;at we ere stad&dtail; in,
Neuer &thorn;e lesse, sekerly, it es ri&yogh;te heuy vn-ti&llbar; vs,
& greuous, vn-ti&llbar; [vs to] here of &thorn;e grete injury
&thorn;at es done vn-ti&llbar; &yogh;ow.  And &thorn;arefore we late
&yogh;ow wite, &thorn;at wit-in schorte ty&mtail;, we sa&llbar; come
for to helpe &yogh;ow wit te&ntail; legyouns of
knyghtis.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>Bot whe&ntail; Rodogorius, Darius
moder, her&dtail; te&llbar;e &thorn;at Darius hir so&ntail;
ordayne&dtail; hym for to feghte agayne wit kyng Alexander scho was
ri&yogh;te sory and wrote a lettre vn-ti&llbar; hym &thorn;at
contene&dtail; this sentence.</P><P><Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT><BODY><P>'To kyng Darius, hir moste biloue&dtail;
son, Rodogorius, his modir sende&yogh; gretyng & ioy.  I hafe
vnderstande&ntail; &thorn;at &yogh;e hafe assemblede &yogh;our
me&ntail;, & meki&llbar; o&thorn;er folke also, for to feghte
<PB N="45">
eftsones wit Alexander.  Bot I late &thorn;e wite it wi&llbar; availe
&thorn;e nathynge.  For &thorn;oghe &yogh;e had&dtail; gadirde to
gedir alle &thorn;e me&ntail; in &thorn;e werlde duellyng, &yogh;it
&yogh;e ware vnable to agayne-stande hym.  For &thorn;e foreluke of
god&dtail; mayntene&yogh; hym, & vphalde&yogh; hym. And &thorn;arefore
dere so&ntail;, it es my conse&llbar;, &yogh;our heghenesse of herte
&yogh;e lefe, & fa&llbar; sumwhate fra &yogh;our glory, and bese
fauorable to &thorn;e gretnes of Alexander.  For better it es to forga
&thorn;at at &yogh;e may no&yogh;te halde, and haffe in pesse
&thorn;an &thorn;at at &yogh;e may halde, &thorn;an for too couett
a&llbar; and be exclude&dtail; & for-ga
a&llbar;.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q> Whe&ntail; Darius redde &thorn;is
lettre, he was gretly troubble&dtail; and wepe&dtail; bitterly,
comman&dtail; vn-ti&llbar; his mynde, his moder, his wyf, & his
childer.
</P>
<P>In the mene tyme kyng Alexander remowe&dtail; his oste, and drew
nere &thorn;e cite of Susis, in &thorn;e whilke Darius was
lengan&dtail; the same tyme, so &thorn;at he my&yogh;te see a&llbar;
&thorn;e heghe hille&yogh; &thorn;at ware abown&ntail; &thorn;e citee.
&THORN;an Alexander commande&dtail; a&llbar; his me&ntail;, &thorn;at
ilka&ntail; of &thorn;a&mtail; suld cutte dow&ntail;e a brawnche of a
tree, and bere &thorn;a&mtail; furth wit &thorn;a&mtail; & dryfe
bi-fore &thorn;a&mtail; a&llbar;e manere of beste&yogh; &thorn;at
&thorn;ay my&yogh;te fynde in &thorn;e way.  And when the Percyenes
saw &thorn;a&mtail; fra &thorn;e heghe hille&yogh; &thorn;ay
wondre&dtail; &thorn;am gretly. And Alexander come wit his oste to
&thorn;e citee of Susis and luged hym nere besyde &thorn;e citee.  And
tha&ntail; he calle&dtail; bis prynnce&yogh; & his o&thorn;er
lorde&yogh; and said vn-to &thorn;a&mtail;, 'Late vs,' quo&thorn; he,
' send a messangere to kyng Darius & bid&dtail; hy&mtail; ow&thorn;er
& co&mtail; feghte wit vs or e&llbar;s<MILESTONE N="18 bk." UNIT="leaf"> submyt hym vn-ti&llbar; vs.'
The nexte nyghte after, God&dtail; Amo&ntail; apperede vnti&llbar;
Alexander in his slepe bryngan&dtail; hym &thorn;e figurre of Mercuri
& a manti&llbar;, and ano&thorn;er manere of garment of Macedoyne, and
saide vn-ti&llbar; hym. 'Alexander, so&ntail;,' quo&thorn; hee, 'euer
mare whe&ntail; &thorn;ou hase nede, sa&llbar; I helpe the.  And
&thorn;arefore luke &thorn;ou sende noghte to Darius &thorn;at
messangere &thorn;at &thorn;ou spake off.  For I wi&llbar; &thorn;at
&thorn;ou thi selfe clethe thee wit my figure & wende thedir &thorn;i
selfe; if a&llbar;e it be perilous for to do, Dred &thorn;e na thynge,
for I sa&llbar; be thi helpe, so &thorn;at &thorn;ou sa&llbar; hafe na
maner of disesse.
</P>
<P>On &thorn;e morne whe&ntail; Alexander rase fra slepe, he was
gretly comforthe&dtail; of his dreme & called ti&llbar; hym his
prynce&yogh; and talde &thorn;a&mtail; alle his dreme, and &thorn;ay
assentede a&llbar;e, &thorn;at he schulde wende to Darius in his
propir person. And onane he calle&dtail; vn-ti&llbar; hym ane of
&thorn;e prince&yogh;, &thorn;e whilke highte Emulus.  This
<PB N="46">
prynce was a wyghte ma&ntail;, & an hardy & wonder trewe ti&llbar;
Alexander.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Alexander bad hym lepe one a horse,
and brynge wit hym a no&thorn;er horse & folow hym.  And he did&dtail;
so.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ay come to gedir to &thorn;e water of
Graunte, &thorn;at in &thorn;e langage of Perse es calle&dtail;
Struma, &thorn;ay fande it frose&ntail; ouer, and Alexander onane
chaunged he wede, & lefte &thorn;e foresai&dtail; prynce wit twa horse
at &thorn;e water-syde and hym selfe, wit &thorn;e horse &thorn;at he
satt apo&ntail;, went ouer &thorn;e water apo&ntail; &thorn;e
Ys&yogh;, towarde &thorn;e citee of Susis.  And his prynce besoghte
hym &thorn;at he walde suffre hym wende wit hym, ne perauenture any
disesse fe&llbar;e hym by &thorn;e waye.  And Alexander ansuer&dtail;
& sayde, 'Habyde me here,' quo&thorn; he, 'For he sa&llbar; be my
helpere, wha&mtail; in dreme&yogh; I sawe appere vn-to me.' This ilke
water I spake of bi-fore, a&llbar; &thorn;e wynter seson ilke a nyghte
was frose&ntail; a&llbar; ouer; bot tymely in &thorn;e mornynge als
sone als &thorn;e warme so&ntail; smate apo&ntail; it, &thorn;a&ntail;
it dissoluede agayne, & ra&ntail; wonder swiftely; &thorn;e brede of
&thorn;at water es &thorn;e space of a furlange.  When Alexander come
to &thorn;e &yogh;ate of &thorn;e citee the Perciens, when &thorn;ay
saw hym, had&dtail; grete wonder of his figure, and wen&dtail; he
had&dtail; bene a god&dtail;, and onane &thorn;ay aske&dtail; hym what
he was ?  And he ansuer&dtail; and sai&dtail; he was a messangere sent
fra kyng Alexander to &thorn;aire lorde Darius, and be-lyfe &thorn;ay
broghte hym til hym.  Darius, when Alexander come bi fore hym, said
vn-til hym.  'Whethy&ntail; ert &thorn;ou,' quo&thorn; he ? 'I ame,'
quo&thorn; Alexander, 'sent vn-to &thorn;e fra kyng Alexander to wiete
where to &thorn;ou taries to come ti&llbar; hymu to gyffe hym
bate&llbar;e.  Owthir come & feghte manfully wit thyne enemys or
e&llbar;s submitte &thorn;e ti&llbar; hy&mtail; &<MILESTONE N="19" UNIT="leaf"> pay hym
tribute.'</P>
<P><ADD>And Darius heard him and said, ' Art thou then
the Alexander who with such madness shaped thy speech, for I see thou
holdest thyself not from words as a messenger doth, but art bold as a
king.  Yet know that by thy words I am not frightened at all.  Come
dine with me this day.'  And with these words, he reached out his hand
to him and took him by his right, and led him into the palace.  And
Alexander, musing, began to say: 'A right good token hath this
barbarian wrought me when he clasped my right hand and drew me into
<PB N="47">
the palace, because, as the gods say sooth, ere long the palace shall
be mine.'  And going in, Darius and Alexander lay by a table, and the
daintiest feast was laid out.  And Darius' marshall gazed hard at
Alexander face to face.  And the table was wreathed in cleanest gold.
But the Persians, seeing Alexander's shape, yet knew nothing of what
wisdom, doughtiness, and strength lurked in this small body.  The
dishes and tables and seats were wrought of the finest gold.  The
cup-bearers bore cups in golden vessels and rarest jewels.  And when a
cup was handed to Alexander, he hid it in his breast. And another cup
was brought to him and he did the same, and thus too with a third.
And those who bore the cups, seeing this, gave the news to the Emperor
Darius.  And he, hearing of it, rose up; saying: 'Friend, what is this
that thou doest, hiding the cups in thy breast?' And Alexander: 'In our
king's feasts the guests are wont, whenever they will, to take their
drinking-vessels.  But, as this seemeth to you unworthy, I will give
them back forthwith.'  And with these words he gave them back to the
cup-bearers.  But the Persians who sate at the feast said each to
each, 'a good custom, indeed, and one to be praised.'  And some lords,
too, praised this way and exalted it.  But one of the Princes of
Darius, called Anapolus, sitting at the feast, gazed hard at Alexander
and his face.  For he had seen him when, at Darius' bidding, he went
into Macedonia to take tribute of Philip.  He, knowing his voice and
looking on his face, began to think to himself and say: 'Is this not
Alexander?'  And rising at once he drew near to Darius, saying: 'This
messenger whom thou beholdest is Alexander, the son of Philip of
Macedon.'  And Alexander, seeing them with each other in talk, knew
they were speaking of him and he was known.  And at this he rose up
from his place and leapt away from the board.  And taking a blazing
torch from a Persian's hand, himself mounted his palfrey, which he
found ready outside Darius's palace, and fled in the swiftest flight.
And the Persian seeing this, taking weapons, mounted their steeds with
a mighty stir, and quickly followed after Alexander.  And in the
darkness of the nightfall, they began to stray, some scratched their
faces by the tree-boughs, some falling into ditches.  But Alexander,
bearing his blazing torch in hand, fared straight
<PB N="48">
forward.  Now, Darius sate on his throne and thought of Alexander and
how great his daring was.  He saw a statue of gold of Xerxes the
Persian king, who sate below the high-seat in the hall.  And at once
the statue broke and was all scattered asunder.  And Darius seeing
this was smitten with heaviness of heart and began to weep sorely and
long.  And he said: 'This foretokeneth the wasting of my life, and the
utter downfall of the Persian kingdom.'  Alexander, however, coming to
the river Grancus, found it swollen, and leapt athwart it.  But ere he
was over the stream burst its banks, and swept his horse away; with
great hardship Alexander escaped and met Eumulus, his lord.  And thus
he went back to his army and told them of Darius, how he had dealt
with him, and the torch with which he had fled away.</ADD></P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>HOW ALEXANDER PUT HEART INTO HIS HOST ANEW.</HEAD> <P><ADD>And on the following day, he gathered his army, which told two hundred and
twenty thousand of weaponed men.  And he went up</ADD>
</P>
<P><MILESTONE N="19" UNIT="leaf">on a hye place & comforthed his me&ntail; and sai&dtail; vn-to
&thorn;a&mtail;: '&THORN;e multitude of &thorn;e percienes,'
quo&thorn; he, 'may no&yogh;te be euend to &thorn;e multitude of
&thorn;e greckes.  For sewrly we are ma &thorn;an &thorn;ay.  And if
&thorn;ay were ane hundreth sythes maa the&ntail; wee, late no&yogh;te
&yogh;our hertis faile &yogh;ow &thorn;arefore.  For I telle &yogh;ow
a grete multitude of flyes may do na harme till a fewee waspes.' And
whe&ntail; &thorn;e Oste had herde thire wordes &thorn;ay commendide
hym halelely wit a voyce.
</P>
<P>Tha&ntail; &thorn;e emperour Darius remowe&dtail; his oste, and
come to &thorn;e reuere of Graunt on &thorn;e nyghte, and went ouer on
&thorn;e ys&yogh;, and &thorn;ar he luge&dtail; hym.  The Oste of
Darius was wonder grete and strange.  For &thorn;ay had&dtail; in
&thorn;aire oste X<HI REND="sup">m</HI> cartes ordayn&dtail; For &thorn;e werre, and grete
multitude of Olyfante&yogh;, wit towres of tree o&ntail;
&thorn;a&mtail;, stuffe&dtail; wit feghtyng me&ntail;.  And sone after
appo&ntail; a day thir twa kynges wit &thorn;aire oste&yogh; mett
same&ntail; on a faire felde, Darius wit his me&ntail;, and Alexander
wit his men.</P> <PB N="49"><P>Than Alexender lept apo&ntail; his
horse, &thorn;at highte Buctiphalas, and rade furthe bi-fore a&llbar;
his oste, and houed in &thorn;e myddes waye bi-twene &thorn;e twa
ostes.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e Percyenes saw hym, &thorn;a had grete
wonder of hym, and ware ri&yogh;te ferde for hym, by cause he was so
vggly. Neuere-&thorn;e-lesse &thorn;ay trompe&dtail; vp & went
to-warde Alexander.  And sone &thorn;e bate&llbar; ioyned, & faghte
to-gedir fersely, and many me&ntail; dye&dtail; on ayther party;
&thorn;are was so thikke schott of arowes, &thorn;at &thorn;e ayer was
couerde, as it had bene wit a clowde.  Some faghte wit swerde&yogh;,
sum wit speres, sum wit axes, & su&mtail; wit arowes.  &THORN;e felde
lay fu&llbar; of folke, su&mtail; dede, su&mtail; halfe-dede, &
su&mtail; greuously wonde&dtail;.  Thay bega&ntail; for to feghte at
&thorn;e so&ntail;-rysynge, and faghte to &thorn;e so&ntail;-settyng.
Bot &thorn;are dye&dtail; many ma of &thorn;e percyenes &thorn;an
&thorn;are dide of Macedoyns.
</P>
<P>And whe&ntail; Darius sawe his me&ntail; fa&llbar;e so thikke in
&thorn;e felde, he lefte &thorn;e felde, and fledd, and &thorn;e
percyenes seyng that, &thorn;ay fled&dtail; also. Bot &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;aire cartes of werre rane amange &thorn;e percyens & slewe of
&thorn;a&mtail; folke wit-owte nouwmer & namely of fote-me&ntail;. For
by &thorn;at tyme it was myrke nyghte, and &thorn;ay ne my&yogh;te
no&yogh;te see for ti&llbar; eschewe &thorn;a&mtail;.  Whe&ntail;
Darius come<MILESTONE N="19 bk." UNIT="leaf"> to the foresai&dtail; watere he fande it
frose&ntail;, and ouer he went. And whe&ntail; he was ouer, &thorn;e
o&thorn;er lordes of perse went appo&ntail; &thorn;e ys&yogh;, so
grete a multitude &thorn;at &thorn;ay couerde &thorn;e ys&yogh; fra
&thorn;e taa banke to &thorn;e to&thorn;er, & &thorn;at a grete brede,
& &thorn;a&ntail; onane &thorn;e ys&yogh; brake als sone als Darius
was paste ouer, & a&llbar; &thorn;at ware on &thorn;e ys&yogh; ware
perischte, ilk a moder so&ntail;, & drownede in &thorn;e water.
&THORN;e remanaunt, whe&ntail; &thorn;ay come to the water, &thorn;ay
my&yogh;te no&yogh;te wy&ntail; ouer.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
Macedoynes come, & dange &thorn;a&mtail; downe.  In this bate&llbar;e
&thorn;are was slaen of &thorn;e percyenes CCC<HI REND="sup">m</HI> wit-owte&ntail; thase
&thorn;at were drownned.
</P>
<P>Kyng Darius fled&dtail; to &thorn;e citee of Susis, & went in
ti&llbar; his palace, & fe&llbar;e downe to &thorn;e grounde, &
sigheand & wepande wit a sare hert, he sai&dtail; theis wordes:
'Allas, fu&llbar; wa es me, vnhappye wriche, &thorn;at euer I was
borne, for &thorn;e ire & &thorn;e indignacion&ntail; of heue&ntail; es
falle&ntail; one mee.  For I Darius &thorn;at lifte my selue&ntail; vp to &thorn;e
sternes, Now am I broghte lawe to &thorn;e erthe.  Now es Darius,
&thorn;at conquerede a&llbar; &thorn;e Este nacyons, & made &thorn;am
subiecte & tributaries vn-ti&llbar; hym, fayne for to flee fra his
enemys and submytte hym vn-to &thorn;a&mtail;.  And it ware
<PB N="50">
knawe&ntail; vn-to &thorn;e wreched ma&ntail;, what schulde falle
ti&llbar; hym after-warde&yogh;, he schulde hafe litti&llbar; thoghte
of &thorn;e tyme presentt, bot one &thorn;e tyme to come solde his
tho&yogh;te be.  In a poynte of a daye it falles, &thorn;at &thorn;e
meke es raysede vp to &thorn;e clowdde&yogh;, and &thorn;e prowde es
putt to no&yogh;te.'  And whe&ntail; he hade saide thir wordes, he
rase vp, & satt & wrate a lettre vn-till Alexander, sayande on this
wyese.  <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT><BODY><P>'Ti&llbar; his lorde
Alexander, kyng of Macedoyne, Darius, kyng of Perse, gretyng & Joy.
We hafe wele vndirstanden by &thorn;at that we hafe herde of &yogh;owe
and sene, &thorn;at &yogh;e hafe in &yogh;ow grete wysedo&mtail; & a
hye witt: so &thorn;at no&yogh;te allanly &yogh;e knawe thynges
&thorn;at are present or passede, bot also thynge&yogh; &thorn;at ere
for to come, and &thorn;are-fore a&llbar; thynge&yogh;, &thorn;at
&yogh;e doo: &yogh;e do it wit-owte&ntail; any lakke or repreue.
Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse hafe&yogh; in mynde &thorn;at ri&yogh;te as wee
ware, so ware &yogh;e gete&ntail; & borne of a fleschly
woma&ntail;. And &thorn;are fore rayse no&yogh;te &yogh;our herte to
hye bi-cause of &yogh;our prowesche & &yogh;our doghty dedis, so
&thorn;at &yogh;e forgete &yogh;our laste ende.  For ofte tymes we see
&thorn;at &thorn;e lattere end of a ma&ntail; discordes wit &thorn;e
firste.  It suffice&yogh; ti&llbar; a werryoure for to gete &thorn;e
victorye of his enemys, &thorn;ofe a&llbar; he schewe no&yogh;te
a&llbar;e &thorn;e malice &thorn;at he may. Remembre &yogh;ow of
&thorn;e wirchipfu&llbar; kyng &yogh;erses oure progenytour, &thorn;at
many victoryes gatt & schane in a&llbar;e prosperiteez, Be-fore he
rayse&dtail; his hert in pride passande mesure.  A&llbar;e &thorn;e
wirchippe &thorn;at he hadd: won&ntail; be-fore, he loste in Ellada,
&thorn;are-fore remembre &yogh;ow, &thorn;at a&llbar; &thorn;e
wirchipes & &thorn;e victoryes &thorn;at &yogh;e hafe gete&ntail; by
&thorn;e forluke of god&dtail; </P><P><ADD>ye got this victory.  To us
then who beseech grant your mercy.  Yield us our mother, our sons, and
wife, and we will render unto you the treasures we have in Aydem and
Susa and Batram, the which our fathers hoarded and hid in earthen
cellars. And we will give you the kingsbip of the Medes and Persians,
that thus ye may have and keep what victory Jove the all-mighty hath
granted you.'</ADD> </P></BODY></TEXT></Q></P> </DIV1><PB N="51">
<DIV1 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>HOW THE MESSENGERS OF DARIUS GAVE ALEXANDER THE LETTER, AND HIS
ANSWER.</HEAD> <P><ADD>The messengers of Darius coming then to
Alexander gave him the letter, which Alexander read soon before them
all.  Then one of his chieftains, called Parmerion, said to Alexander:
'Most mighty emperor, take all the wealth which Darius covenants unto
thee, and give back to him his wife and sons.'  And, hearing this,
Alexander called to him the messengers of Darius, and before all spoke
thus, saying: 'Tell ye to your emperor we wonder first that he
misdeemed his mother, wife, and sons to be betrayed by our hands.  If
he be overcome, bid him not promise us a reward.  If he bow himself to
our yoke, all his honours and the majesty of God shall be laid bare to
our sway.  If he be not overcome, let him do us battle once again.'
This said, he gave them rich gifts and sent them forth away.  Then he
bade the soldiers take up and gather the bodies of the dead and bury
them in graves: and he bade them heal those that were
wounded.</ADD></P></DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>HOW ALEXANDER ENCAMPED BY THE STREAM GRANCUS.</HEAD>
<P><ADD>Then he encamped with his host by the stream of Grancus, and
wintered there some days.  And there he offered up victims to the
gods. And about the river there were palaces, and they were the
fairest, raised up with greatest skill, and Xerxes the King of the
Persians had built them.  Alexander, seeing them, bade them be burned.
And soon after this, stirred by ruth, he gave word none should dare
touch them.  And there too was a most fair and very wide field in
which the Kings and Deemsters of Persia were of old buried.  And
digging into this field the Macedonians found in the graves gemmed
vases.  And there they found the grave of Ninus the King of Assyria
and Persia, which was hollowed out of a single amethyst, and engraven
on the outside with palm-leaves and sundry kinds of birds.  And so
bright was the amethyst that even from the outside the man's body
appeared whole.  And in this place was a narrow and evil tower on
which stood many men, some with cut legs, some with broken thighs,
some with torn hands, and some blinded. They hearing
<PB N="52">
the noise of the armed men cried out to Alexander, who bearing their
cries, bade them be taken thence.  And seeing them was struck with
ruth and wept, and bade each one be given ten thousand drachmas, and
be restored every one to his own. For Darius kept them in prison,
since they were of noble birth, and awarded all their possessions to
his thralls.  In the meantime the messengers from Alexander to Darius
told all that Alexander had said.  And Darius hearing this began to
get ready for the fight. And he wrote another letter to Porus King of
India, which runneth as follows:</ADD><TEXT>
<BODY>
<HEAD>THE LETTER SENT BY DARIUS TO PORUS KING OF INDIA.</HEAD>
<P><ADD>'Darius King of the Persians to Porus King of Our Indians joy.
We asked but lately of you, and again we ask you to come and help
against those who strive to overthrow our palace.  We know well also
that the like harm will light on you.  For this Alexander, who
fighteth thus, hath an unquenchable and wild soul, which like a lion
ceaseth not, and is like the sea when stirred by mighty winds.
Furthermore, unwillingly though it be, we have gathered numberless
races, and we have taken our counsel to fight with him to the very
death.</ADD>
<MILESTONE N="20" UNIT="leaf">better vs es for to dy manly in &thorn;e felde &thorn;an
for to see &thorn;e mescheffe of oure pople & &thorn;e
dissolacio&ntail; of oure rewme. Whare-fore, hafan&dtail; rewar&dtail;
and compassio&ntail; of oure disesse, we be-seke &yogh;ow, &thorn;at
&yogh;e late oure prayeres satte&llbar; in &yogh;our hert, & helpe for
to succour vs now at oure nede, hafan&dtail; in &yogh;oure mynde
&thorn;e grete noblaye of oure progenytours.  And I seure &yogh;ow
&thorn;at [I sall] giffe ilke a fote-ma&ntail; &thorn;at come&yogh;
wit &yogh;ow, thre pece&yogh; of golde, And ilke a horse-ma&ntail;,
fyve pece&yogh; of golde, And also mete & drynke ynoghe to &yogh;ow &
a&llbar; &yogh;our me&ntail;.  And whare so &yogh;e lugge &yogh;ow, we
scha&llbar;e fynde &yogh;ow a hundreth & fourscore tentes curyously
wrogbte.  And also we scha&llbar; gyffe &yogh;ow Alexander horse
Buktyphalas, and a&llbar;e appairai&llbar;, & &thorn;e araye &thorn;at
langes ti&llbar; Alexander hallely scha&llbar; be &yogh;ours and also
a&llbar; &thorn;e spoylle of his folke sa&llbar; be dalte amange&yogh;
&yogh;oure folke.  Where-fore we beseke &yogh;ow &thorn;at also
so&ntail; als this
<PB N="53">
lettre comme&yogh; to &yogh;ow, &yogh;e haste &yogh;ow ti&llbar; vs in
a&llbar; &thorn;at &yogh;e may.  For wite &yogh;e wele for certayne,
that ri&yogh;te als he done ti&llbar; vs, so he purpose hym in tyme
commynge for to do to &yogh;owe.'</P> </BODY></TEXT> </P><P>In the men
tyme, certane me&ntail; of Darius went fra hym & come ti&llbar;
Alexander, & talde hym, &thorn;at Darius purposede hym for to feghte
wit hym eftesones, and had sent ti&llbar; Porus, kyng of Inde, for to
come in grete haste, for to helpe hym.  Whe&ntail; Alexander herd
&thorn;is, be-lyfe he remowe&dtail; his Oste to war&dtail; Darius,
thynkand in his herte &thorn;at he wolde on na wyse take apo&ntail;
hym &thorn;e name of Emperour be-fore he had&dtail; won&ntail; Darius
and his rewme one werre.  And when Darius herde of &thorn;e commyng of
Alexander, he dred&dtail; hym gretly & &thorn;e percyenes also.  Bot
&thorn;are was two prynce&yogh; of Darius, of &thorn;e whilke &thorn;e
tane highte Bisso & &thorn;e to&thorn;er Ariobarsantes, thir twa
whe&ntail; &thorn;air her&dtail; of &thorn;e comyng of Alexander,
conspyre&dtail; togedir for to slaa &thorn;aire lor&dtail; Darius,
supposyng for ti&llbar; hafe a grete thanke of Alexander, and a gret
rewar&dtail; for &thorn;aire dede.  And ayther of &thorn;a&mtail; ware
sworne ti&llbar; o&thorn;er.  And tha&ntail; thay went to &thorn;e
kynges palace, and come inti&llbar; his chamber wit drawe&ntail;
swerdes in &thorn;aire hande&yogh;, and fand Darius bi hym ane.  And
whe&ntail; Darius saw that, he trowe&dtail; wele &thorn;at &thorn;ay
wolde sla hy&mtail;, And said vn-to &thorn;a&mtail;: 'Dere
frende&yogh;, hedir to warde&yogh; hafe I called &yogh;ow my
seruaunde&yogh;, bot now I call &yogh;ow my lordes.  What ayles
&yogh;ow at me &thorn;at &yogh;e wi&llbar; sla me ?  Haes Alexander
cheriste &thorn;e macedoynes mare &thorn;a&ntail; I hafe done
&yogh;ow?  Hafe I no&yogh;te sorow & disese ynoghe of enemyse
wit-owtte&ntail; ?  Bot if &yogh;e conspire agaynes me for to sla me
wit owtte&ntail; gilt, I say for sothe, & &yogh;e sla me<MILESTONE
N="20 bk." UNIT="leaf"> thus preuelye, And Alexander may gete &yogh;ow, he wi&llbar; take mare
crue&llbar; vengeance one &yogh;ow, the&ntail; on any theues.  For
sothely it es na comforthe ne lykyng ti&llbar; ane Emperour to fynd an
o&thorn;er Emperour murthere&dtail; wit his awe&ntail; me&ntail;.' Bot
&thorn;ay were na-thynge stirrede to petee, ne tendernesse, ne mercy,
thurg&hbar; his worde&yogh;, Bot went ti&llbar; &hbar;ym and wit grete
cruelnesse smate hym, & al-to magle hym, and went faste &thorn;aire
waye, & lefte hym for dede.
</P>
<P>And whe&ntail; Alexander her&dtail; te&llbar; &thorn;at Darius was
slayne he
<PB N="54">
went ouer &thorn;e water of Graunt, and a&llbar; his Oste wit hym, and
come to &thorn;e cetee of Susis.  And alsone als &thorn;e percyenes
saw hym, Thay Opened &thorn;e &yogh;ates of &thorn;e citee, &
rescheyue&dtail; hy&mtail; wit grete wirchipe.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;e prynce&yogh; &thorn;at slewe Darius wiste &thorn;at Alexander
was come&ntail; i&ntail;-to &thorn;e citee &thorn;ay went & helde
&thorn;a&mtail; in hidils ay ti&llbar; &thorn;ay my&yogh;te gete
knaweynge of Alexander wi&llbar;, as towchan&dtail; &thorn;at that
&thorn;ay had&dtail; done to Darius.  Alexander &thorn;a&ntail; went
in-to &thorn;e kynges Palace, and as he went &thorn;are-in he
merueyled hym gretly of &thorn;e biggyng &thorn;are-off.  For Cirus
&thorn;e kyng of Perse gert bigg it ryally.  And the pament
&thorn;areoffe was made of stanes of dyuerse colours, & &thorn;e
walles a&llbar; enueround wit fyne golde & precyous stanes & sternes
lyke to &thorn;e firmament, and pelers of golde &thorn;at bare vp
&thorn;e werke.  Whe&ntail; Alexander saw a&llbar; this curious werke,
he meruaile&dtail; hym gretly.  And tha&ntail; he went to &thorn;e
chambre &thorn;are Darius laye halfe dede.  And alsone als he saw
hy&mtail; he had&dtail;grete rewthe & compassio&ntail; of hym, and he
tuke off his awen&ntail; manti&llbar; & couer&dtail; [hym] &thorn;are-wit,
& went and grape&dtail; his wondes and wepi&dtail; for hym ri&yogh;t
tenderly, & sai&dtail; un-til hym.  'Rise vp, sir Darius,' quo&thorn;
he, '& be of gude comforthe.  And als frely as euer &thorn;ou
reioysede thy&ntail; Empire, so mot &thorn;ou &yogh;itt do, And be als
myghty, & als gloryouse als euer &thorn;ou was.  I swere the here by
oure my&yogh;ty goddes & by &thorn;e faythe in my body, &thorn;at here
I resigne vn-to the a&llbar; thy&ntail; empyre, desyran&dtail;
souerayngly for to hafe &thorn;e lyfe of the, as &thorn;e so&ntail; of
&thorn;e Fader, For sekerly it es vnfittan&dtail; & unsemly ti&llbar;
ane emperour for to be reioysede of an o&thorn;er emperours mescheffe
& disesse, whe&ntail; fortune hase forsake&ntail; hym.  Te&llbar;e me,
sir, what &thorn;ay are &thorn;at hase thus fare&ntail; wit the, and I
sewre &thorn;e als I am trew ma&ntail; I sa&llbar; venge the to
&thorn;e uttereste.'  And<MILESTONE N="21" UNIT="leaf"> whe&ntail; Alexander had sai&dtail; this & meki&llbar; mare, Sare wepan&dtail; Darius putt furthe his hande, and layde his arme abowte Alexander nekke, and kyssed his breste, his
nekke, & his hande, & saide thir worde&yogh;, thare that here folowes.
'A, dere so&ntail; Alexander,' quo&thorn; he, 'als thi heghe witt knawes
wele, a&llbar; this werlde es corupt and sett in malice.  For &thorn;e
souerayne forluke of god&dtail;, a&llbar; thynge&yogh; knawande fra
&thorn;e begynnyng, and hafan&dtail; felyng of &thorn;e wirkynge&yogh;
for to come, made ma&ntail; in that wyse, at &thorn;e <PB N="55">begynnynge, &thorn;at nathyng es in hym stable ne faste.  So
&thorn;at a&llbar; thynge&yogh; &thorn;at ere passande & werldely, fra
&thorn;at he faile of gouernance, tournes also&ntail; ti&llbar; hym in
contrarye.  For if god&dtail; had&dtail; ordeyne&dtail; a&llbar;
thynge&yogh; esy to ma&ntail; and alwaye wit-owtte&ntail; chaungynge
sent hym prosperitee, ma&ntail; schulde be lyftede vp so hie in pryde
& in vayne glorye, &thorn;at he solde no&yogh;te arett a&llbar;e his
wele-fare & his welthe vn-to godd, bot ti&llbar; his awen&ntail;
desert & his awen&ntail; vertu.  And so schulde me&ntail; gaa fra
&thorn;aire makare.  On &thorn;e to&thorn;er syde if &thorn;e heghe
wyssedo&mtail; of god&dtail; had&dtail; made &thorn;e werlde o&ntail;
&thorn;at wyse &thorn;at a&llbar; illes and infelicytes fe&llbar;
apo&ntail; ma&ntail; wit-owtten any maner of gudenesse, so many
freletese sulde folow &thorn;e kynde of ma&ntail;, &thorn;at we
schulde a&llbar; be drawe&ntail; in-to &thorn;e gilder of
disparacio&ntail;, so &thorn;at we solde hafe na triste in &thorn;e
gudnes of god&dtail;.  And &thorn;arefore grete god&dtail; wolde so
wisely skifte a&llbar; thynges, &thorn;at, whe&ntail; a ma&ntail;
fu&llbar; of felicitee, thurgh his heghe pride wi&llbar; no&yogh;te
knawe his makere, Fra &thorn;e heghte of pride in-to &thorn;e pitte of
mekenes & lawnes he mo&ntail; be plungede.  So &thorn;at he &thorn;at
thurgh pride & felicite forgatt his god&dtail;, thurgh fallynge in
wrechidnesse & disesse hafe mynde of his god&dtail;.  Reghte als
&thorn;ou may see bi me, my dere so&ntail; Alexander, &thorn;at was
raysede vp so hye in- pride & vayne glorye, thurgh reches &
prosperitee &thorn;at fe&llbar;e vn-to me, &thorn;at I trowed
no&yogh;te &thorn;at I was goddes creature bot goddes Felawe.  And
&thorn;a&ntail;, thurg&hbar; blyndeness of pride, I couthe no&yogh;te
see that, &thorn;at now, thurgh scharpenesse of mekenes and mescheffe,
I see clerely & knawes.  Bot if it happe&ntail; &thorn;at any
ma&ntail; be vmbilappede wit grete infilicitee, so &thorn;at he,
despairan&dtail; of &thorn;e grace of godd, supposse na remedy, ne
nane lukes eftere;<MILESTONE N="21 bk." UNIT="leaf"> &thorn;a&ntail; oure lorde god&dtail; rayse&yogh;
hym vp to &thorn;e heghte of prosperitee, so &thorn;at &thorn;a&ntail;
he, &thorn;at bi-cause of wrechidnes & infelicitee, my&yogh;te
no&yogh;te see god&dtail; ne knawe hym, thurgh felicite & prosperitee
knawes &thorn;at he, &thorn;at may bryng a ma&ntail; to lawe state,
may rayse a ma&ntail; ti&llbar; heghe degree.  And he &thorn;at may
rayse a ma&ntail; ti&llbar; heghe degree, may putt hym to lawnesse
agayne, whe&ntail; hym lyst, and &thorn;are-fore, so&ntail;, late
no&yogh;te thy hert ryse to hye in pride, for &thorn;e victoryes
&thorn;at god&dtail; hase sent the, if a&llbar; &thorn;ou may do now
whate &thorn;e listri&yogh;t as [ &thorn;ou] were a god&dtail;.  Bot
alway thynke on thy laste ende.  For &thorn;ou ert a dedly ma&ntail;,
and ilk a day if &thorn;ou be-halde graythely &thorn;ou may see thy
ded&dtail; bi-fore thy&ntail; eghne.  Consedirs
<PB N="56">
&thorn;ou no&yogh;te how oure lyffe may be lykkene&dtail; to &thorn;e
werke of Eranes, &thorn;at so sotelly makes &thorn;aire webbes?  Bot
also&ntail; als a little blaste of wynde puffes apo&ntail;
&thorn;a&mtail;, &thorn;ay breke, & falles to grownde.  Behalde & see
how glorius I was &yogh;isterday & how wrechede I a&mtail; to-day, &
how law I am broghte.  I was lorde nerehande of all &thorn;e werlde, &
now I hafe na power of my&ntail; awe&ntail; selfe.  Now I be-seke the,
so&ntail;, &thorn;at &thorn;ou will bery me wit thy benynge
handes. And suffre for to come to my&ntail; exequise bathe &thorn;e
Macedoynes and &thorn;e persyenes. And fra this tyme forwarde&yogh;,
&thorn;e empire of Macedoyne & &thorn;e empire of perse be bathe ane.
Haffe recomen&dtail; vn-to the my Moder Rodogo&ntail;, & trete hir
wirchipfuily as thy&ntail; awen&ntail; Moder.  And I be-seke &thorn;e
also, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be Mercyable to my wyfe.  And if it be
lykynge to &thorn;e, take Rosa&ntail; my dogheter to thi wyfe.  For
semely it es, &thorn;at &yogh;e be ioynede to-geder &thorn;at er
come&ntail; of so wirchipfu&llbar; progenitours, For &thorn;ou of kyng
Philippe, and scho of kyng Darius, And of &yogh;ow twa may a
wirchipfu&llbar; & a noble fruyte sprynge.'  And ri&yogh;te as he had
saide thir worde&yogh; he swelt in Alexander armes.  Kyng Alexander,
&thorn;a&ntail;, after &thorn;e custo&mtail; was for to bery
emperours, gert araye Darius body als ryally as he couthe.  And wit
a&llbar; &thorn;e solempnyte and wirchipe &thorn;at myghte be done, he
helped hym selfe for to bere &thorn;e bere, sare wepande, and gert
&thorn;e Macedoynes & &thorn;e Percyenes gaa bi-fore &thorn;e bere.
The persyenes also wepe&dtail; wonder faste, no&yogh;te allanly for
&thorn;e dede of Darius, bot for petee of &thorn;aire hertis,
&thorn;at &thorn;ay saw Alexander wepe so enterely.  And whe&ntail;
Darius was berie&dtail; Alexander went agayne to &thorn;e palace.</P>
<P>And one &thorn;e morne Alexander went and sett hym in a trone
a&llbar; of golde & precyous stanes, the whilke Cyrus sumtyme gert<MILESTONE
N="22" UNIT="leaf">
make &thorn;at was kynge of Perse.  And the Macedoynes and &thorn;e
Persyenes sett apo&ntail; his hede a coroune &thorn;at was Darius,
&thorn;e whilke was so precious, &thorn;at me&ntail; knewe nane like
it in na lande.  For a&llbar; &thorn;e palace schane thurg&hbar;
bryghtness of &thorn;e precyous stanes, &thorn;at were sett
&thorn;are-in.  And &thorn;e trone was a&llbar; of golde, & of
precious stanes, & of&thorn;e sege &thorn;are-offe was vii seue&ntail;
cubete&yogh; heghe fra &thorn;e grounde, and a grece of seue&ntail;
gree&yogh; was made
<PB N="57">
&thorn;are-to, whare-by kynges ascended &thorn;are-to.  And thir
gree&yogh; were mede wonder craftyly & curyously.  The firste gree was
of ane amatist.  The seconde gree was of a Smarag&dtail;.  The
thred&dtail; gree was of a Topa&yogh;.  The ferthe gree was of a
granat.  The fifte was of ane adaman&dtail;.  The sext was of
fy&ntail; golde.  And the seuennt was of clay.  And thay ware
no&yogh;t [wit-o]wtte&ntail; grete cause&yogh; ordeyne&dtail; one
&thorn;is wyse.
</P>
<P>For &thorn;e first gree w[as a]ne amatist, for amange a&llbar;
o&thorn;er stanes it hase this vertu, that it represses & halde&yogh;
donne &thorn;e fumositee of wyne & &thorn;e myghte &thorn;are-offe, &
suffers no&yogh;te a ma&ntail; &thorn;at bere it o&ntail; hym be
troubble&dtail; in his witt ne in his mynde thurgh drownkeness.  And,
on &thorn;e same wise, solde ilke a kyng be of perfite witt & mynde, &
thurg&hbar; nane occasio&ntail; do na mysse.  The secun&dtail; gree
was of a Smarag&dtail;, &thorn;e whilke clarifye&yogh; & kepe&yogh;
&thorn;e sighte of hym &thorn;at beres [it] apo&ntail; hym, and so
schulde a kynge hafe clere sighte of his hert, wysely for to see &
discerne that &thorn;at es spedfull & profitable bathe for hym selfe &
for &thorn;e como&ntail; profit. The third&dtail; gree was of a
Topa&yogh;, &thorn;e whilke es so clere, &thorn;at & a ma&ntail;
bi-halde hym selfe &thorn;are-in, it sa&llbar; seme ti&llbar; hym, as
his hede ware tournede downwarde&yogh;, and his fete vpwarde&yogh;;
And it be-takenes &thorn;at a kyng schulde alway take hede ti&llbar;
his laste ende. The ferthe gree was of a Granat whilk passe&yogh;
a&llbar; manere of precious stanes in reedness: & betakens &thorn;at a
kyng suld be schamfu&llbar; for ti&llbar; consent ti&llbar; any thynge
&thorn;at es vnlefu&llbar;.  The fifte was of ane Adamande.  &THORN;e
Adamande es so harde &thorn;at it may no&yogh;te be broke&ntail;
now&thorn;er with yre&ntail; ne wit stane, bot if it firste be
enoynte&dtail; wit gayte blode.  On &thorn;e same wyse a kyng suld be
of so grete constance & sadnesse &thorn;at, for na prayere, ne for na
worldely gude, he solde no&yogh;te bewg&hbar; fra &thorn;e way of
ryght-wisnesse.  The sexte gree was of fyne gold: for ri&yogh;te as
gol&dtail; passe&yogh; all maner of meta&llbar;e in bewtee, & in
precioustee; ri&yogh;te so a kyng awe to be preferre&dtail; before
o&thorn;er me&ntail; & gouernours of &thorn;a&mtail;.<MILESTONE
N="22 bk." UNIT="leaf">  &THORN;e seuent was of Clay, ti&llbar; &thorn;at entent &thorn;at a ma&ntail;
&thorn;at es raysed vp to &thorn;e dingnyte of a kyng sulde alway
vmbythynk hym &thorn;at he was made of erthe, & at &thorn;e laste
<PB N="58">
to &thorn;e erthe he sa&llbar; agayne.  Whe&ntail; Alexander was sett
apo&ntail; this trone, coronnde wit his diademe, & &thorn;e Macedoynes
& &thorn;e persenes standyng abowte hym: be-fore &thorn;a&mtail;
a&llbar;e he gert write a lettre ti&llbar; a&llbar; cuntree&yogh;,
&thorn;at was of this tenour.  <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P>'Alexander the so&ntail; of god&dtail; Amo&ntail; & qwene Olympias
kyng of kynges & lorde of lordes, ti&llbar; a&llbar;e Dukes,
Prynce&yogh;, Erles, Baronns, maisters, & ti&llbar; a&llbar; &thorn;e
folke&yogh; of Perse: ioy & grace. Se&ntail; it es plesynge to godd,
&thorn;at I sitt one &thorn;e trone of Darius, & be lorde of &thorn;e
persyenes, grete cause I hafe for to be reioyist gretely
&thorn;are-offe, ne were it for &thorn;e gret multitude of folke
&thorn;at ere slayne.  Bot se&ntail; it so es &thorn;at god&dtail;
hase ordeynede me to be &yogh;our lorde, and &yogh;our gouernour,
&thorn;are-fore we commande &yogh;ow &thorn;at in ilke a citee,
thurghowte &thorn;e lordchipe of Perse, &yogh;e ordeyne prynce&yogh;
and gouernours as &thorn;are was in Darius tyme, to &thorn;e whilke we
commande &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e be obeyande as &yogh;e
before-tymes hafe bene, and that &thorn;ay do ri&yogh;te ti&llbar;
ilke a ma&ntail; at &thorn;aire powere.  Also it es oure wi&llbar; and
oure commandement, &thorn;at ilke a ma&ntail; welde & reioyse
paysabily his landes and his possessiouns. We commande alsoo,
&thorn;at fra this lande of perse vn-ti&llbar; Ellada, & fra
thethy&ntail; to Macedoyne, be redy way & ope&ntail; so &thorn;at ilke
a ma&ntail; &thorn;at wi&llbar; may passe bathe in and owte, wit
merchandyse or any o&thorn;er erandes &thorn;at &thorn;ay hafe at do,
and Joy & pese be vn-to &yogh;owe.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>
</P>
<P>&THORN;an gert Alexander a&llbar; me&ntail; be sti&llbar;, and said
one this wyse: 'Whilke of &yogh;ow so slew my&ntail; enemy Darius;
come&yogh; forthe be-for me, and I sha&llbar; giffe &yogh;ow worthy
mede, & conable wirchipe do &thorn;a&mtail;, I swere bi oure
godde&yogh; &thorn;at ere Almy&yogh;ty, & bi my moste bilove&dtail;
moder Olympias, &thorn;at I sa&llbar; gyffe &thorn;a&mtail; worthy
mede.'  Whe&ntail; Alexander had saide thir wordes &thorn;e persyenes
wepede wonderly sare.  And tha&ntail; &thorn;e twa
ma&ntail;-morthireres Bisso and Aryobar&yogh;antes come bi-fore
Alexander, and sayde vn-ti&llbar; hym: 'Wirchipfu&llbar; emperour,'
quo&thorn; &thorn;ay, 'we ere thase &thorn;at slew Darius thyne enemy
wit oure Awen&ntail; hende.'  And whe&ntail; Alexander saw
&thorn;a&mtail;, he bade his knyghtes belyfe ga & take
&thorn;a&mtail;, & bynde<MILESTONE N="23" UNIT="leaf"> &thorn;am, & lede &thorn;a&mtail; to Darius
grafe, & &thorn;are smyte of &thorn;aire heuedes, And tha&ntail;
&thorn;ay ansuer&dtail;, & saide vn-ti&llbar; Alexander: 'A, A,
wirchipfu&llbar; emperour,' quo&thorn; &thorn;ay,
<PB N="59">
'swore &thorn;ou no&yogh;te ti&llbar; vs, bi oure godde&yogh;
&thorn;at ere Almy&yogh;ty, & bi &thorn;e hele of thi moder Olympias,
&thorn;at &thorn;ou solde gerre do vs na harme, bot &thorn;at
&thorn;ou solde giff vs a worthi rewar&dtail;.'  And Alexander saide
agayne vn-to &thorn;a&mtail;: 'So aughte me wele for to swere, for to
gette knawyng of &thorn;e slaers of Darius.  For I solde neuer hafe
gety&ntail; knawyng &thorn;are-offe had I no&yogh;te sworne so. And
&yogh;itt I sa&llbar; safe my&ntail; athe wele ynoghe.  For it was
al-way my&ntail; entent, &thorn;at if I my&yogh;te wete what &thorn;ay
ware, &thorn;ay solde hafe swilke a rewarde.  For &thorn;ay &thorn;at
slaes &thorn;aire awen&ntail; lorde it es a take&ntail; &thorn;at
&thorn;ay wi&llbar; hafe na conscience to sla ano&thorn;er ma&ntail;.'
And when &thorn;e perseyenes herde this &thorn;ay by-ga&ntail; to
prayse Alexander & to commende hym and blysse hym as he had bene a
god&dtail;.  &THORN;a&ntail; kyng Alexander gert hede tha twa
homycydes.  And a&llbar; &thorn;e rewme he sett in gouernance of
certayne lordes.  Amanges o&thorn;er &thorn;are was ane alde lorde was
eme to Darius, &thorn;e whilke highte Climitus, &thorn;at was gretly
luffede wit &thorn;e persyenes; And Alexander at &thorn;e request of
a&llbar; the persyenes ordeyned hym for to be chefe goueruour vnder
hym of a&llbar; perse.  And one &thorn;e morne Alexander sett hym in
his trone, wit his corou&ntail; on his hede, and efter &thorn;e
biddynng of Darius he commande to brynge bi-fore hym Rosa&ntail;,
Darius doghter, wit a corou&ntail; o&ntail; hir hede, sett fu&llbar;
of precious stanes.  And &thorn;are, as &thorn;e maner was of &thorn;e
persyenes, he tuke hir to his wyfe, and made hir to sitt wit hym in
his trone & command a&llbar; me&ntail; to wirchipe hir als quene.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e persyenes were wonderly glade, & onane
&thorn;ay bro&yogh;te &thorn;aire godde&yogh; bi-fore Alexander, and
bi-ga&ntail; to wirchipe hym, & loue hym ri&yogh;te als he hade bene a
god&dtail;, and sai&dtail; vn-till hym, hallely wit a voyce,
'&thorn;ou thi selfe es a god&dtail;, For that &thorn;at es plesande
ti&llbar; oure goddes alway &thorn;ou dose.'  And whe&ntail; Alexander
saw this, he was gretly troubled & ri&yogh;te ferde & sai&dtail; vn-to
&thorn;am 'Wirchipfu&llbar; sirs,' quo&thorn; he, 'I pray &yogh;ow
&thorn;at &yogh;e wirchipe me no&yogh;te as a god&dtail;, for sothely I
am as &yogh;e are, a corupteble & a dedly ma&ntail;, and in me
&thorn;are es na parce&llbar; of the godhede.  And &thorn;arefore, I
beseke &yogh;ow, cesse&yogh; of this wirchipe &thorn;at &yogh;e do me'
</P>
<P>&THORN;an gert Alexander write a lettre ti&llbar; Olympias his
moder & ti&llbar; Arestotle his maister, makand mencyo&ntail; of
a&llbar; &thorn;e batay&llbar;s & &thorn;e disesse&yogh; &thorn;at he
had&dtail; suffred in Perse, and of &thorn;e grete reches
<PB N="60">
&thorn;at he fande &thorn;are, of &thorn;e whilke he & a&llbar; his
me&ntail; ware made riche.  And also he wrate vn-to &thorn;a&mtail;,<MILESTONE
N="23 bk." UNIT="leaf">
&thorn;at &thorn;ay scholde make grete solempnytee lastyng aghte dayes
be-cause of &thorn;e weddynge of Alexander & Rosa&ntail; Darius
doghter.  And so di&dtail; Alexander, in Perse, wit &thorn;e
maceydoynes & &thorn;e persyenes, many a daye.
</P>
<P>Affter this kyng Alexander semble&dtail; a grete Oste, bathe of
macedoyns & of persyenes, and went towarde Inde for to werre
apo&ntail; Porus, kyng of Inde, &thorn;e whilke ordeynede hym for to
come & helpe kyng Darius.  And, when Alexander was entered
in-ti&llbar; Inde, he went thurg&hbar; wildernes & waste cuntree,
whare in ware grete reuers and many grete caues & cauernes.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; Alexander & his me&ntail; wex wery, & irkede
ri&yogh;te sare.  And &thorn;e prynces Of macedoyne & of grece
murmourede amange&yogh; &thorn;a&mtail; gretly, & saide ilka&ntail;
ti&llbar; o&thorn;er: 'It my&yogh;te hafe suffice&dtail; ti&llbar;
vs, &thorn;at we hafe ouer-sett kyng Darius, & conqerre&dtail;
&thorn;e kyngdo&mtail; of Perse.  Where-be seke we forthire
in-ti&llbar; Inde, &thorn;e whilke es fu&llbar; of wilde beste&yogh;,
and leues oure awen&ntail; lande&yogh;.  Ne &thorn;is Alexander nane
o&thorn;er thynge&yogh; desyre&yogh;, bot for to wende abowte and
thurgh werre to brynge a&llbar; &thorn;e worlde vndere his subieccion.
For werre & debate unresche&yogh; his body so fer furth &thorn;at, and
he ristede any lange tyme witowte&ntail; werre, ri&yogh;te als it were
for defaute of mete he schulde faile & dye.  Leue we hym
&thorn;arefore, and turne we agayne vn-ti&llbar; oure awen&ntail;
cuntree, and late hym wende furthe wit the persyenes, if he
wi&llbar;.'  When Alexander herde &thorn;is, he garte a&llbar;
&thorn;e Oste habide, and he went and stodde in ane heghe place
amange&yogh; &thorn;a&mtail;, & sayde one this wise: 'Departis
&yogh;ow in twaa, so &thorn;at &thorn;e persyenes be by
&thorn;a&mtail;-selfe and &thorn;e Macedoynes and &thorn;e grekes bi
&thorn;a&mtail;-selfe.'  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ay had&dtail; so done,
Alexander saide to &thorn;e Macedoynes and &thorn;e grekes: 'A A, myne
owen&ntail; dere knyghtis,' quo&thorn; he, 'wele [&yogh;e] knawe
&thorn;at thir persyenes, vn-to &thorn;is day, hase bene contrary &
rebe&llbar;es vn-to &yogh;ow & to me, and &yogh;e wi&llbar; now lefe
me here wit &thorn;a&mtail;, and tourne agayne to &yogh;our
awen&ntail; cuntree.  Wele &yogh;e wate, &thorn;at when &yogh;our
hertes were troubblede, & fered, for &thorn;e wordes &thorn;at ware
contene&dtail; in Darius lettres, I thrug&hbar; my speche & my
conse&llbar; comforthe&dtail; &yogh;our hertis.  And afterwarde, when
we come in-to &thorn;e felde agaynes oure enemys, I went bi-fore
&yogh;ow a&llbar;.
<PB N="61">
And I by my&ntail; ane was &thorn;e firste ma&ntail; &thorn;at entrede
&thorn;e batay&lbar;e.  And &yogh;itt more-ouer, as &yogh;e wele wate, I
tuke apo&ntail; me for to be &yogh;oure allere messangere vn-to kynge
Darius.  And &thorn;are, for &yogh;ow, I putt my selfe in many grete<MILESTONE
N="24" UNIT="leaf">
peri&llbar;s.  And &thorn;arefore, witte&yogh; wele for certayne,
&thorn;at, ri&yogh;te as hedirtowarde&yogh;, we hafe ouercome&ntail;
oure enemys and hade &thorn;e better of &thorn;a&mtail;, ri&yogh;te so
fro he&thorn;ein-forwarde&yogh;, thurgh &thorn;e helpe of oure
godde&yogh; we sa&llbar; ouercome oure enemys, & hafe &thorn;e
victorye of &thorn;a&mtail;. And &thorn;are-fore I say &yogh;ow
forsothe, &thorn;at, a&llbar; if &yogh;e will tourne agayne to grece &
macedoyne, I sa&llbar; no&yogh;te tourne agayne o&ntail; na wyse,
&thorn;at &yogh;e may knawe &thorn;at, wit-owtte&ntail; gouernance of
a kynge, nane Oste may wynne na wirchipe.'  Whe&ntail; Alexander had
sai&dtail; &thorn;us, a&llbar; &thorn;e prynce&yogh; of Macedoyne and
of &thorn;e grekes schamede gretely, and askede mercy & forgifnesse,
sayande one this wyse: 'Moste wirchipfu&llbar; emperour, oure lyfe
lyes hallely in &yogh;our hande.  Whedir so euer &yogh;e wi&llbar; goo
we wi&llbar; gladly felowe &yogh;our hye maiestee; &thorn;ofe we
schulde a&llbar; dye for &yogh;ow o&ntail; a daye, we sa&llbar; folow
&yogh;ow & neuer lefe &yogh;ow.'  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ay
remowe&dtail; fra &thorn;einne and come in-ti&llbar; a cuntree of Inde
&thorn;at es calle&dtail; Phisiace&ntail;, in &thorn;e laste ende of
July.  And &thorn;are mette hym &thorn;e embassatours of Porus kyng of
Inde, and broghte hym lettres fra Porus, &thorn;at said o&ntail; this
wyse.  <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P>' Porus kyng of Inde: vn-to &thorn;e theeffe Alexander, &thorn;at
thurg&hbar; thifte & robbery many citee&yogh; wynne&yogh;, biddyng we
sen&dtail;.  Se&ntail; &thorn;ou ert dedely: wharto wene&yogh;
&thorn;ou &thorn;at &thorn;ou ert of powere to agaynstande god&dtail;
&thorn;at es vn-dedely.  A grete fole, me thynke, &thorn;ou ert
&thorn;at hase eghne, and cane nott see. Trowes &thorn;ou we be lyke
vn-to &thorn;e percyenes &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase made subiecte&yogh;
vn-to the ?  &THORN;ou hase foughte&ntail; hedir-towarde wit softe
me&ntail; & cowarde&yogh;, & for &thorn;ou hase ouercome&ntail;
&thorn;a&mtail;, &thorn;ou wene&yogh;, &thorn;at thi littillness
sa&llbar; brynge oure hye maiestee vnder thi subieccion; &thorn;e
whilke es vnpossyble for to bee, bot if godde&yogh; submytt
&thorn;a&mtail; vn-to me&ntail;, and &thorn;e erthe be euen lyke to
&thorn;e heue&ntail;.  I late the wiete, &thorn;at I may no&yogh;te be
ouercomme&ntail; for no&yogh;te allanly me&ntail; bot also godde&yogh;
doee&yogh; seruyce to my name.  Wate &thorn;ou no&yogh;te wele,
&thorn;at ane Dynise, &thorn;e fader of Bachus, come in-ti&llbar;
Inde, wit a grete Oste for to feghte, bot onane he tournede &thorn;e
bakke & fledd, for he
<PB N="62">
was no&yogh;te of powere to agaynstande &thorn;e vertu of me&ntail; of
Inde.  And &thorn;arefore, or any schame or mischeffe co&mtail; to
&thorn;e; we con-se&llbar; the & commande&yogh; the, &thorn;at in
a&llbar; &thorn;e haste &thorn;at &thorn;ou may, &thorn;ou tourne hame
agayne to thyne awe&ntail; lande.  Fore wele &thorn;ou knawes,
&thorn;at, bi-fore &yogh;erses was kynge of Perse, &thorn;e macedoynes
gaffe tribute ti&llbar; Inde.  Bot, by-cause &thorn;at &thorn;aire
lande es barayne & vnprofitable, & na thynge&yogh; &thorn;er-in
plesande ti&llbar; a kynge: &thorn;e me&ntail; of Inde sett no&yogh;te
&thorn;are-by.  For ilke a ma&ntail;, desyres mare a large lande & a
plenteuous: &thorn;an<MILESTONE N="24 bk." UNIT="leaf"> a strayte lande & a barayne.  And
&thorn;arefore, &yogh;itt the thirde tourne, I comaunde the that
&thorn;ou tourne hame to thyne awen&ntail; lande. And neuer, in thi
lyfe, couette to hafe Lordschipe &thorn;are &thorn;ou may nane
gete.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q></P> <P>Whe&ntail; &thorn;is lettre was
come&ntail; ti&llbar; Alexander, he gerte rede it be-fore a&llbar;
me&ntail;.  And whe&ntail; his knyghtis had&dtail; herde &thorn;e
tenour of &thorn;is lettre, &thorn;ay were trublede.  And Alexander
sayde vn-to &thorn;a&mtail;: 'My wirchippfull knyghtis,' quo&thorn;
he, 'late no&yogh;te &yogh;our hertis be trublede ne fere&dtail; for
Porus lettre.  Hafe &yogh;e no&yogh;te in mynde, wit how grete pride
Darius wrate vn-ti&llbar; vs dyuerse tymes ?  I say &yogh;ow sotheley
&thorn;at all &thorn;e folke of thyse Este parties hase &thorn;aire
hertis & &thorn;aire wittis lyke vn-to &thorn;e bestes &thorn;at
&thorn;ay due&llbar;e wit-a&llbar;, &thorn;at es at say, Tygres,
Pardes, & o&thorn;er wilde bestis, whilke fu&llbar; selde&ntail; ere
slaen&ntail; of me&ntail;, and &thorn;are-fore &thorn;ay triste
a&llbar; in &thorn;aire strengthe.'  And whe&ntail; Alexander hade
said thir wordes, he garte writte a lettre vn-to Porus kynge of Inde
whare-of this was the tenour.  <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P>'Kyng of kynges and lorde of lordes, Alexander &thorn;e so&ntail;
of god&dtail; Amo&ntail; & &thorn;e quene Olympias, vn-to Porus we
sende.  &THORN;ou hase scharpede oure wittes, & gyffe&ntail; vs
hardynesse for to feghte agaynes &thorn;e, whare &thorn;ou says
&thorn;at macedoyne es bot a litti&llbar; lande & barayne of a&llbar;
thyng &thorn;at gude es.  And Inde, &thorn;ou says, es large, &
plenteuous of a&llbar; gude&yogh; & reches.  And &thorn;are-fore we
sa&llbar; enforce vs to feghte wit the at a&llbar; oure myghte, for to
con-quere thi lande&yogh; &thorn;at, &thorn;ou sais, es so fu&llbar;
of reches.  And, for &thorn;ou halde&yogh; vs pouer, & of na
reputacio&ntail;, &thorn;are-fore we desire for to ascende to &thorn;e
heghte of thi majestie.  And also &thorn;are &thorn;ou says, &thorn;at
no&yogh;te allanly vn-to me&ntail;, bot also vn-to godde&yogh;
&thorn;ou erte emperour, I sa&llbar; come to the, for to feght wit
&thorn;e, as wit a&ntail;
<PB N="63">
haythe&ntail; ma&ntail; fu&llbar; of Pompe & pride and vayne glory, &
no&yogh;te as wit a god&dtail; For a&llbar; &thorn;e werlde may
no&yogh;te agaynstan&dtail; &thorn;e wrethe of a god&dtail;.
&THORN;er-fore, se&ntail; &thorn;e elementis of this aere, &thorn;at
es at say Thunners, leuenynge&yogh; and water, may no&yogh;te bere
&thorn;e indygnacion of godde&yogh;, how schulde &thorn;a&ntail;
dedely me&ntail; mowe agaynstande &thorn;aire wrethe?  And
&thorn;are-fore I late the<MILESTONE N="25" UNIT="leaf"> wele witte &thorn;at &thorn;i founde
proudde speche trubble&yogh; me no&yogh;te ne moue&yogh; me neuer a
dele.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>
</P>
<P>Whe&ntail; Porus had&dtail; this lettre, he was wondere wrathe &
assemblede a grete Oste of me&ntail;, and a grete multitude of
Olyphanntes wit &thorn;e whilke &thorn;e me&ntail; of Inde ere wount
for to feghte, and went agaynes Alexander.  This Oste of Porus was
ri&yogh;te grete & strange, for &thorn;are ware &thorn;er in
xiiij. cartes of were and viij<HI REND="sup">c</HI> Oliphannte&yogh;, and ilk an
Olyphanthad&dtail; a toure of tree apo&ntail; his bakke, & in ilke a
toure xxx me&ntail;.  &THORN;are ware also o&thorn;er feghting
me&ntail; on horse and on fote wit-owten nowmer.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;e Macedoynes and &thorn;e persyenes sawe &thorn;e grete
multitude bathe of me&ntail; & of Olyphaunte&yogh;, &thorn;ay were
fere&dtail;, & gretely stonayde.  Neuer &thorn;e lesse, bathe &thorn;e
partyes ordayne&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; to bate&llbar;, and
araye&dtail; &thorn;aire bate&llbar;s, Alexander on his syde, and
Porus on his syde.  And Alexander lepe vp-o&ntail; his horse
Buktiphalas & prikkede bi-fore a&llbar; his me&ntail;, and
comande&dtail;, &thorn;at &thorn;e Medoynes & &thorn;e persyenes sulde
firste begyn&ntail; to feghte.  And so &thorn;ay di&dtail;; & hym
selfe wit &thorn;e grekes, and &thorn;e macedoynes stode on &thorn;e
to&thorn;er syde, redy to succour &thorn;a&mtail; whe&ntail; myster
ware.  And for &thorn;e Olyphaunte&yogh; also, Alexander gert make
suylke a&ntail; ordynance.  He gert make xxiiij ymage&yogh; of brasse,
and gert fi&llbar; &thorn;a&mtail; fa&llbar; of dry wodde. And he
gerte make also cartes of yre&ntail;, for to bere thir ymage&yogh;
before &thorn;e Olyphaunte&yogh; and whe&ntail; &thorn;e Oste&yogh;
came nere to-gedir he gert sett fyre in &thorn;e wod&dtail; &thorn;at
was in &thorn;e ymages.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e Olyphaunte&yogh; saw
&thorn;ir ymages, &thorn;ay wende &thorn;at &thorn;ay had&dtail; bene
me&ntail; and schott owte &thorn;aire groynes, as &thorn;ay were wount
for to do for ti&llbar; hafe weryed &thorn;a&mtail;.  And alsone
thurgh &thorn;e grete hete, &thorn;ay were brynne&dtail; and
tha&ntail; thay gaffe bakke, & fled&dtail; for drede to brynne
&thorn;ayre groynes.  And &thorn;are-fore &thorn;e me&ntail; &thorn;at
were abow&ntail; in &thorn;e toures myghte no&yogh;te wy&ntail; to for
to feghte.  And whe&ntail; Porus saw that he was reghte
<PB N="64">
sary.  &THORN;a&ntail; &thorn;e Medoynes & &thorn;e persyenes, wit
arowes and speres & o&thorn;er dyuerse wapynes of werre, slewe
thykfalde of &thorn;e me&ntail; of Inde.  And thus &thorn;ay faghte
contenuelly xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> days, & meki&llbar; pople of bathe &thorn;e parties
ware dede.  And at &thorn;e laste &thorn;e Medoynes, & &thorn;e
persyenes, bega&ntail; faste for to fayle.  And whe&ntail; Alexander
saw that, he was wondere wrathe, and entrede in-to &thorn;e
bate&llbar;e, sittan&dtail; on his horse Buctiphalas,<MILESTONE
N="25 bk." UNIT="leaf"> and faghte mannfully, & &thorn;e grekes & &thorn;e macedoynes wit hym.  And his horse
also helpe&dtail; hy&mtail; gretely.  And tha&ntail; belyfe &thorn;e
Indyenes bega&ntail; gretely for to fayle.  And whe&ntail; Porus saw
that he turne&dtail; &thorn;e bakke & fled&dtail; And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;e Indyenes &thorn;at ware lefte o&ntail; lyfe fled&dtail; also.
And Alexander luge&dtail; hym thare wit his Oste and made Sacrafice
ti&llbar; his godde&yogh; and commaunde&dtail; for to bery &thorn;e
ded&dtail; bodys, bathe of Indyenes & of &thorn;e persyenes & &thorn;e
Macedoynes.
</P>
<P>Sone after, apo&ntail; a day, Alexander enseged&dtail; Porus citee
& wan&ntail; it, and went in-ti&llbar; Porus Palace, whare-I&ntail; he
fande mare reches &thorn;a&ntail; any ma&ntail; wi&llbar; trowe.  For
he fande &thorn;are-in x&lbar; pelers of Massy golde, ilka&ntail; of a
grete thikness & a grete lenthe, wit &thorn;aire chapytra&llbar;es.
And bitwene &thorn;e pelers of golde, ware hyngande venette&yogh; of
golde & syluere, wit leues of golde.  And &thorn;e brawnche&yogh; of
this venett ware su&mtail; of crista&llbar;e, su&mtail; of
Margarite&yogh;, su&mtail; of Smaragdes, & su&mtail; of Onyches, and
&thorn;ay seme&dtail; as &thorn;ay hade bene verray vynes.  &THORN;e
walles also of &thorn;e palace ware couerde a&llbar; ouer wit plates
of golde, &thorn;e whilke whe&ntail; &thorn;e Macedoynes cutte in
soundre & brakke, &thorn;ay fande &thorn;at &thorn;ay ware a gret
ynche thikke.  And &thorn;ir walles ware sett fu&llbar; of diuerse
precious stanes, &thorn;at es at say, of charebuncles, Smaragdes,
Margarites & Amatistes.  And &thorn;e &yogh;ates of &thorn;e Palace
ware of Euour wonder whitt, & &thorn;e bande&yogh; of &thorn;a&mtail;,
& &thorn;e legges of Ebene.  &THORN;e chambirs, also, of &thorn;is
Palace, were a&llbar; of Cipresse, and &thorn;e bedde&yogh; in
&thorn;a&mtail; ware sett fu&llbar; of Margarite&yogh;,
Smaragde&yogh;, & charebuncles.  &THORN;e hau&llbar;, also, of
&thorn;is Palace, was sett fu&llbar; of ymages of golde, & bi-twix
&thorn;a&mtail; stode perlatanes of golde, in &thorn;e branches of
whilke &thorn;are were many manners of fewles & ilke a fewle was
colourede, & paynte&dtail; after his kynde aske&dtail;, &thorn;e bekes
of &thorn;a&mtail;, & &thorn;e clowes ware a&llbar; of fyne golde.
And ay,
<PB N="65">
whe&ntail; Porus liste, thir fewles thurg&hbar; crafte of music walde
synge after &thorn;aire kynde askede & was.  He fande also in
&thorn;at Palace veselles wit-owte&ntail; nowmer, su&mtail; of golde,
su&mtail; of Crista&llbar;e, Su&mtail; of o&thorn;er maneres of
precyouse stanes, su&mtail; of Suluere, and &thorn;at a&llbar; maner
of vese&llbar; &thorn;at me&ntail; sulde be serue&dtail; offe.  Bot
&thorn;are were bot fewe of &thorn;a&mtail; of Siluere.
</P>
<P>Fra thethy&ntail;, Alexander remowede his Oste & come to &thorn;e
&yogh;ates of Caspee, and &thorn;are he luge&dtail; hy&mtail;.  It was
a noble lande & a gude.  Bot &thorn;are ware &thorn;are-In many maners<MILESTONE
N="26" UNIT="leaf">
of nedders and of wilde beste&yogh;.  Fra &thorn;eine Alexander sent a
lettre ti&llbar; Talifride quene of Ama&yogh;o&ntail;, of &thorn;is
tenour.  <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P>' Kyng of kynges, and lorde of lordes, Alexander, &thorn;e
so&ntail; of god&dtail; Amo&ntail;, & &thorn;e quene Olympias, vn-to
Talifride &thorn;e quene of Ama&yogh;o&ntail;, ioy.  The grete
Batay&llbar;es &thorn;at we hafe had&dtail; wit kyng Darius, & how we
hafe conquere&dtail; a&llbar; his rewme, and his lordchipes, we trowe
he noghte unknawe&ntail; vn-to &yogh;ow.  And also how we hafe
foghte&ntail; with Porus &thorn;e kyng of Inde & his cheeffe citee
wonne&ntail;.  And also wit many o&thorn;er folkes, & &thorn;ay ware
neuer of powere to agaynestande vs, &thorn;e whilke we suppose be
no&yogh;te vnknawe&ntail; vn-to &yogh;owe.  Whare-fore we sende
&yogh;ow worde, & commande&yogh; &yogh;ow, &thorn;at &yogh;e sende vs
tribute, if &yogh;e wi&llbar; &thorn;at wee co&mtail; no&yogh;te to
&yogh;ow to do &yogh;ow disesse.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>
</P>
<P>And vn-to this lettre Talifride made ansuere by lettre one this
wyse.  <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P>' Talyfride quene of Amazo&ntail; wit o&thorn;er grete ladys of
oure rewme, vn-ti&llbar; Alexander, kynge of Macedoyne, joy.  We hafe
wele herde te&llbar;e of &thorn;e bye witt &thorn;at es in the,
thurg&hbar; whilke &thorn;ou hase in mynde thynge&yogh; &thorn;at ere
passede, and dispose&yogh; thynges &thorn;at ere present, and
knawe&yogh; thynge&yogh; &thorn;at ere to come. Avyse the wele
&thorn;arefore are &thorn;ou come ti&llbar; vs, what
trebulacionne&yogh; & disesse may fa&llbar;e the in thi commynge.  For
&thorn;are was neuer nane &yogh;it &thorn;at werreyed agayne&yogh; vs
&thorn;at ne he ha&dtail; schame &thorn;are-offe at &thorn;e ende.
And &thorn;are-fore take hede to thi last ende. For grete schame it es
ti&llbar; a wyse ma&ntail; thurg&hbar; indiscrecio&ntail; to
fa&llbar;e in mescheffe.  Bot if it be lykynge to &thorn;e, to knawe
our conuersacyo&ntail;, and oure habitacio&ntail;, we declare it
vn-to &thorn;e be oure
<PB N="66">
present lettres, &thorn;at oure habitacio&ntail; es in ane Ile,
&thorn;at es closede abowte wit a grete reuer &thorn;at no&thorn;er
hase bygynnynge nor endynnge.  Bot on a syde we hafe a strayte entree.
And the nowmer of wome&ntail; &thorn;at duelle&yogh; &thorn;er-in es
ccxiiii<HI REND="sup">m</HI> &thorn;at ere no&yogh;te filed wit me&ntail;.  For oure
husbande&yogh; duelle&yogh; no&yogh;te amange&yogh; vs ne no
no&thorn;er ma&ntail;, Bot on &thorn;e to&thorn;er syde of &thorn;e
reuer.  And ilke a &yogh;ere we make a solempne feste in the wirchipe
of Iubiter xxx days.  And &thorn;a&ntail; we go till oure husbandes,
and duelle&yogh; wit &thorn;a&mtail; o&thorn;er xxx dayes & hase oure
luste and oure disporte<MILESTONE N="26 bk." UNIT="leaf"> to-gedir as kynde askes.  And if any of vs
consayfe & bere a childe if it be a male &thorn;e modere kepis it
seue&ntail; &yogh;ere and tha&ntail; sende&yogh; it to &thorn;e
fadere.  And if scho bere a mayde&ntail; childe &thorn;e moder
halde&yogh; it wit hir & teche&yogh; it oure maners.  Whe&ntail; we
goo to werre agayne &yogh;oure enemys we ere c<HI REND="sup">m</HI> rydan&dtail; one horse
wele armede. And su&mtail; of vs hase bowes & arowes, and su&mtail;
speres, and o&thorn;er diuerse wapyne.  And &thorn;e remanent
kepe&yogh; oure Ile.  And whe&ntail; we come wit the victorye oure
husbande&yogh; does vs grete wirchipe.  And &thorn;are-fore if
&thorn;ou come agaynes vs we late the witt &thorn;at we wi&llbar;
feghte wit the at a&llbar; oure my&yogh;te.  And if it happe&ntail;
&thorn;at &thorn;ou hafe &thorn;e victory of vs, wirchipe sa&llbar; it
nane be to the bi-cause &thorn;ou hase discomfit wome&ntail;. And if
we discomfit the, it sa&llbar; be an heghe wirchippe ti&llbar; vs,
&thorn;at we may discomfit so wirchipfu&llbar; an emperour; and to the
it sa&llbar; be a hye reproue.  Where-fore we sygnifie vn-to &thorn;e
by oure lettres &thorn;at &thorn;ou come no&yogh;te agaynes vs for
sekerly &thorn;are may grete dysese come &thorn;are-offe, &thorn;at
perauenture &thorn;ou knawe&yogh; no&yogh;te now offe at &thorn;is
tymme.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>
</P>
<P>Whe&ntail; Alexander had&dtail; red&dtail; &thorn;is lettre, he
bega&ntail; to lawghe.  And onane he garte writte ano&thorn;er lettre,
and sent it to Talyfride, whare-offe &thorn;e tenour was this.  <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P>'Alexander kyng of kynges and of lorde&yogh;, the so&ntail; of
god&dtail; Amo&ntail; & &thorn;e qwene Olympias, to Talyfride quene of
Ama&yogh;o&ntail; and &thorn;e o&thorn;er ladys of &thorn;e same
rewme: ioy.  We late &yogh;ow weite &thorn;at thre parties of &thorn;e
werlde, &thorn;at es to say, Asye, Affric, & Europe we hafe
conquere&dtail; and made subiects vn-ti&llbar; vs, & &thorn;are was
neuer nane of &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at my&yogh;te agaynstande oure
powere.  And if we now suld no&yogh;te be of powere, to feghte with
&yogh;owe it ware ane heghe schame ti&llbar; us.  Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse
for als meki&llbar;
<PB N="67">
als we lufe &yogh;our conuersacio&ntail; we conse&llbar; &thorn;at
&yogh;e come forthe of &yogh;our Ile & &yogh;our husbonde&yogh; wit
&yogh;ow, and appere in oure presence.  For we swere &yogh;ow bi
go&dtail; Amo&ntail; oure Fader, & by a&llbar; oure godde&yogh;
&thorn;at &yogh;e sa&llbar; hafe na disesse of vs.  Bot gyffe&yogh; vs
sumwhat in name of tribute and we scha&llbar; fynd &yogh;ow and
&yogh;oure Ama&yogh;onns &thorn;at come<MILESTONE N="27" UNIT="leaf"> wit &yogh;ow horse ynowe.  And
whe&ntail; &yogh;ou listees for to wende hame agayne, &yogh;e
scha&llbar; hafe gude leue.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q> And whe&ntail;
&thorn;e Ama&yogh;ons had&dtail; red&dtail; &thorn;is lettre,
&thorn;ay went to conse&llbar;, and thoghte it was beste for to ascent
vn-ti&llbar; hym.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ay sent hym x stedes
&thorn;e beste &thorn;at my&yogh;te be funde&ntail; in any cuntree,
and x o&thorn;er horse &thorn;e beste &thorn;at my&yogh;te be
gete&ntail;, and a grete su&mtail; of golde.  And Talifride hir selfe
and o&thorn;er ladys wit hir went un-ti&llbar; hy&mtail;, and
accorde&dtail; wit hym, and went hame agayne, wonder glade and blythe.
</P>
<P>In &thorn;e mene tyme it was talde Alexander, &thorn;at Porus,
&thorn;e kyng of Inde, was in Bactrice&ntail;, and assemble&dtail; a
grete Oste for to feghte eftsonns wit hym.  And whe&ntail; Alexander
herde this, he remowede his Oste, and chese owte c.l of duyercs
&thorn;at knewe &thorn;e cuntree, for to hafe &thorn;e gouernance of
his Oste, and to lede &thorn;a&mtail; seurly thurgh &thorn;at strange
cuntree.  In &thorn;e Monethe of Auguste, whe&ntail; &thorn;e
so&ntail; es maste hate, &thorn;ay biga&ntail; for to take &thorn;aire
iournee.  And thay went thurg&hbar; a dry cuntree, sandye, &
wit-owtte&ntail; water.  And nedlynge&yogh; &thorn;a&mtail;
byhoue&dtail; wende armede, &thorn;are was so grete plentee of
neddirs, and crue&llbar; wylde bestes.  For thies forsaid gyde&yogh;
ware mare fauorable to Porus, &thorn;a&ntail; ti&llbar; Alexander &
his Oste, and &thorn;are-fore &thorn;ay led&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail;
thurgh swilke barrayne and perilous cuntree&yogh;.  And whe&ntail;
Alexander saw it schope thus, and that his conse&llbar; byfore had
sayd &thorn;e sothe, &thorn;at es at say, bathe his awn&ntail;
frende&yogh; and me&ntail; of Caspy, &thorn;at consel&dtail; hym
&thorn;at he suld no&yogh;te hye hym ouerfaste, ne triste to
meki&llbar; to stran&yogh;gers; &thorn;au he commande&dtail; &thorn;at
a&llbar; me&ntail; schulde wende arme&dtail;: & so &thorn;ay
di&dtail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;e Oste schane
ri&yogh;te as it ha&dtail; bene sternes, for sum of &thorn;aire
armours ware of golde, su&mtail; of siluer, and su&mtail; of precious
stanes. And whe&ntail; Alexander saw &thorn;e araye of his Oste, and
&thorn;aire baners bi-fore &thorn;a&mtail; Schynande so faire, he was
ri&yogh;te gladde.  Neuer-&thorn;e-les grete disese he had&dtail;,
&thorn;at now&thorn;er he, ne his me&ntail;, my&yogh;te fynde na
water.
<PB N="68">
</P>
<P>So it fe&llbar;e &thorn;at a knyghte of Macedoyne &thorn;at
hy&yogh;te &yogh;ephilus fan&dtail; water standynge in an holle stane,
&thorn;at was gadir&dtail; &thorn;are of &thorn;e dewe of &thorn;e
heue&ntail;, the whilke &thorn;is forsaide knyghte putt in his
Bacenett, & bro&yogh;the it till Alexander for to drynke.  And
Alexander saide un-ti&llbar; hym, 'I suppose,' quo&thorn; he,
'&thorn;at I drynke &thorn;is water, sa&llbar; &thorn;e Macedoynes &
&thorn;e persyenes be any thynge refreschede &thorn;areby, or I
sa&llbar; hafe a&llbar; &thorn;e refreschyng be my selfe.'  And he
ansuerd, & saide, '&THORN;ou a&llbar; ane lorde,' quo&thorn; he,
'sa&llbar; be comforthed &thorn;areby.' Quo&thorn; Alexander
&thorn;a&ntail;, 'An&dtail; if &yogh;e<MILESTONE N="27 bk." UNIT="leaf"> sa&llbar; a&llbar; perische
trowes &thorn;ou &thorn;at it solde be lykan&dtail; to mee, for to
lyfe in sorowe & disese seynge &thorn;e ded&dtail; of &thorn;e
Macedoynes & &thorn;e persyenes ?' And be-lyue he garte he&llbar;e
down&ntail; &thorn;e water on &thorn;e erthe be-fore a&llbar; his
me&ntail;.  And whe&ntail; his knyghtis saw that, &thorn;ay were
hugely comforthede &thorn;are-by ri&yogh;te als Ilka&ntail; of
&thorn;a&mtail; had&dtail; dronke&ntail; a grete draughte of water,
and &thorn;a&ntail; went furthe &thorn;aire waye.  And o&ntail;
&thorn;e morne, &thorn;ay come ti&llbar; a reuere whase bankes was
growan&dtail; fu&llbar; of grete redys & &thorn;ay ware als hye as
pyne-treese; &yogh;a, for &thorn;e maste partie of x&lbar; fote lange.
Than bad&dtail; [he] that &thorn;ay drawe of &thorn;e water and brynge
to &thorn;e Oste.  Bot a&llbar; &thorn;at dranke &thorn;are-offe it
keste &thorn;a&mtail; in-ti&llbar; a flux, and slewe a grete hepe of
&thorn;am.  For &thorn;at water was wonder scharpe, and als bittire
als any meki&llbar; gyrse.  Bot &thorn;a&ntail; was Alexander gretly
disessed&dtail; & a&llbar; his Oste no&yogh;te allanly of
&thorn;a&mtail;-selfe, bot also for &thorn;aire horse&yogh; &
&thorn;aire beste&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;ay led&dtail; wit
&thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;e whilke bi-ga&ntail; for to faile for thryste.
Alexander had&dtail; wit hym a thowsande Olyp&hbar;ante&yogh;
&thorn;at bare his golde, And foure hundreth cartes of werre and j<HI REND="sup">m</HI> &
cc wayne&yogh;.  He had&dtail; also in his Oste ccc<HI REND="sup">m</HI> horse me&ntail;
and muyles & camelles witowte&ntail; nowmer, &thorn;at bare
&thorn;aire vetails, and o&thorn;er thynge&yogh; &thorn;at was
necessarye to &thorn;e Oste; also oxe&ntail; and kye, schepe and
swyne, wit-owte&ntail; nowmer, &thorn;e whilke perischt for defaute of
drynke.  Su&mtail; of Alexander knyghtes lykke&dtail; Ire&ntail;,
Su&mtail; dranke oyle, & sum ware at so grete meschefe &thorn;at
&thorn;ay dranke &thorn;aire awe&ntail; stalynge.  And thare was so
grete habundance of nedders & o&thorn;er venymous bestee&yogh;,
&thorn;at &thorn;am byhoue&dtail; nede&yogh; traue&llbar;e armed, and
&thorn;at was a grete nuy to &thorn;am & a&ntail; heghe disese.
&THORN;a&ntail; was Alexander wonder sorye & namely for &thorn;e
disese &thorn;at his Oste suffrede.
<PB N="69">
</P>
<P>An&dtail; as &thorn;ay went endlande &thorn;is reuere, abowte
&thorn;e viii houre of &thorn;e day, &thorn;ay come ti&llbar; a
caste&llbar; &thorn;at stode in a litti&llbar; Ile in &thorn;is
forsai&dtail; ryuere; Aud this caste&llbar; was made of &thorn;e
forsai&dtail; rede&yogh;.  &THORN;e brede of this ryuer was foure
furlange lent&hbar;.  And in &thorn;at caste&llbar; &thorn;ay sawe a
few me&ntail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Alexander bad his me&ntail; spirre
&thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at ware in &thorn;e caste&llbar; in &thorn;e
langage of Inde whare &thorn;ay myghte fynde any swete watir able for
to drynke.  And also so&ntail; als &thorn;ay spake to &thorn;a&mtail;
&thorn;ay with-drewe &thorn;a&mtail; & hid&dtail;.  And Alexander
gerte schotte arowes in-to &thorn;e caste&llbar; and &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;ay hid&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; wele &thorn;e mare. And when
Alexander saw<MILESTONE N="28" UNIT="leaf"> that &thorn;ay walde one na wyse speke wit hym, he
had&dtail; a certane of his knyghtes nakne &thorn;am & swyme ouer
&thorn;e water to &thorn;e caste&llbar;. And &thorn;a&ntail; xxxvii
balde knyghtis & hardy of Macedoyne nakne&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail;, and
tuke ilka&ntail; of &thorn;a&mtail; a swerde in his hande & went in-to
&thorn;e water & swame it to &thorn;ay were passede &thorn;e fertbe
parte &thorn;are-offe.  And sodeynly thare rase oute of &thorn;e water
a grete multitude of beste&yogh;, &thorn;at ere calle&dtail;
ypotaynes, grettere of body tha&ntail; a&ntail; olyp&hbar;ant, and
deuore&dtail; thir knyghtis euer-ilkanne.  And &thorn;a&ntail; was
Alexander ri&yogh;te sare greuede, and be-lyfe garte take &thorn;e
forsai&dtail; guyde&yogh; cl & caste &thorn;a&mtail; in-to &thorn;e
water.  And onane &thorn;e ypotaynes deuore&dtail; &thorn;em.
</P>
<P>And Alexander thoghte it was no&yogh;te spedfu&llbar; langare to
stryffe wit thase monstres, and garte tromppe vp and remowe&dtail; his
Oste fra &thorn;eine, and went so a&llbar; &thorn;at day wondere wery
for thriste.  And also &thorn;ay had&dtail; grete disese & nuye of
wilde Beste &thorn;at come apo&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail;, &thorn;at es to
say, of lyones, beres, vnycornes, tygres, and parde&yogh;, wit
&thorn;e whilke &thorn;ay faughte & grete traue&llbar; hade.
</P>
<P>And as &thorn;ay went o&ntail; &thorn;is wyse wit grete angere &
disese aboute &thorn;e elleue&dtail; houre &thorn;ay saw a
litti&llbar; bate in &thorn;e riuere made of rede and me&ntail;
rowande &thorn;are-in.  And Alexander gert spirre &thorn;a&mtail; in
&thorn;e langage of Inde, whare &thorn;ay my&yogh;te fynde any fresche
water.  And &thorn;ay talde whare & schewe&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; a
place a litti&llbar; &thorn;eine whare-in &thorn;ay saide &thorn;ay
scholde fynde a grete staunke of swete water and gude.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; Alexander & hys Oste went a&llbar; aboute &thorn;at
ryuere, & come ti&llbar; &thorn;is forsai&dtail; stanke and
luge&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; aboute it.  And Alexander comande&dtail;
&thorn;at &thorn;ay sulde fe&llbar;e
<PB N="70">
a wod&dtail; &thorn;at growe&dtail; faste &thorn;are-by three myle on
lenthe, & a&llbar;s meki&llbar; on brede.  &THORN;at wodde was
a&llbar; of &thorn;e rede&yogh; &thorn;at I spak of bi-fore, and
&thorn;e stanke was a myle o&ntail; lent&hbar;.  &THORN;a&ntail;
Alexander comande&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;ay sulde make many fires in
&thorn;e Oste, and gerte trompe to &thorn;e mete.  Ald also&ntail;
&thorn;e mone be-ga&ntail; to schynne &thorn;are come a grete
multitude of scorpyons to-warde &thorn;e stanke for to take
&thorn;a&mtail; a drynke.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;are come
o&thorn;er manere of nedders, and dragones wonder grete of dyuerse
colours.  And a&llbar; &thorn;at cuntree resounne&dtail; of &thorn;e
noyse & &thorn;e hiss&yogh;inge&yogh; &thorn;at &thorn;ay made.
&THORN;ir dragones come dounne fra &thorn;e hye mountaynes for to
drynke of &thorn;e stanke, and &thorn;ay had&dtail; crestis one
&thorn;aire hedde&yogh; & &thorn;aire breste&yogh; ware bryghte lyk
golde, & &thorn;aire mowthes ope&ntail;.  &THORN;aire aande slewe any
qwikk thynge &thorn;at it smate apo&ntail;, and oute of &thorn;aire
eghne &thorn;are come flammes of fyre.  And whe&ntail; Alexander & his
Oste saw &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;ay ware ri&yogh;t<MILESTONE
N="28 bk." UNIT="leaf"> fere&dtail; for &thorn;a&mtail;.  For &thorn;ay wende &thorn;ay schulde hafe
werie&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; ilka&ntail;.  And &thorn;a&ntail;
Alexander comforthe&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; and saide vn-to
&thorn;a&mtail;: 'Mi wirchipfu&llbar; knyghtes,' quo&thorn; he, 'bees
no&yogh;te agaste of &thorn;a&mtail;, bot does ilkane as &yogh;e see
me do.'  And &thorn;a&ntail; he tuk a nett & sett it bi-twixe hym &
&thorn;a&mtail; and tuke his schelde & his spere & faughte wit
&thorn;a&mtail; manfully.  And whe&ntail; his knyghtes saw &thorn;at
&thorn;ay ware gretly comforthe&dtail; & be-lyfe tuke &thorn;aire
wapynne&yogh; & did&dtail; als &thorn;ay sawe Alexander doo, and slewe
of &thorn;a&mtail; a grete multitude, whatt thurg&hbar; dyuerse
wapynne&yogh;, what in &thorn;aire fyres.  And of Alexander knyghtes
&thorn;e dragones slewe xx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> & xxx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> foteme&ntail;.  After
&thorn;a&mtail;, &thorn;are come owte of &thorn;e forsaide wodde of
rede&yogh;, Crabbes of a wonderfu&llbar; greteness; and &thorn;aire
bakkes ware harder &thorn;a&ntail; cocadrille&yogh;.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;e knyghtis smate &thorn;a&mtail; one &thorn;e bakkes wit
&thorn;aire speres, &thorn;ay my&yogh;te no&yogh;te perche
&thorn;a&mtail;, ne na harme do &thorn;a&mtail;.  Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse
&thorn;ay slewe many of &thorn;a&mtail; in &thorn;aire Fires and
&thorn;e remenant of &thorn;a&mtail; gatt in-to &thorn;e staunke. And
aboute &thorn;e sexte houre of &thorn;e nyghte &thorn;are come
apo&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail; whytt lyones grettere &thorn;a&ntail;
Bulles, and &thorn;ay schoke &thorn;aire heuede&yogh; at
&thorn;a&mtail; & grete manace made in &thorn;aire manere.
&THORN;a&ntail; &thorn;e knyghtes kepe&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; in
&thorn;aire nettis and slew &thorn;am.  After this &thorn;are
co&mtail; apo&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;a&ntail; a grete multitude
of swynne &thorn;at ware a&llbar; of a wonderfu&llbar; mekilness, wit
tuskes of a cubett lenthe.  And wit &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;are come
wilde me&ntail; & wome&ntail; of &thorn;e whilke ilka&ntail;
had&dtail; sex hende.  Bot Alexander & his knyghtes keped
&thorn;a&mtail; in &thorn;aire
<PB N="71">
nettis & slewe many of &thorn;a&mtail;. And on &thorn;is wyse
Alexander & his Oste was gretly disesed.  &THORN;a&ntail;
comande&dtail; Alexander &thorn;at &thorn;ay schul&dtail; make many
fyres wit-owtte&ntail; &thorn;e Oste abonte &thorn;e stanke.  After
this &thorn;are come apo&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail; a wondere grete beste,
grettere & strangere &thorn;a&ntail; a&ntail; Olyphaunt, and he hadde
in his frunte three lange hornes.  And he was schape&ntail; lyke a
horse & he was a&llbar; blakke.  And &thorn;is beste was calle&dtail;
in &thorn;e langage of Inde 'Anddontrucio&ntail;'.  And or he went to
&thorn;e water at drynke, he assaille&dtail; &thorn;e Oste. Bot
Alexander went here & &thorn;are amange&yogh; &thorn;e oste &
comforthe&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail;.  This ilke beste slewe of his
knyghtes xxviij and bare donne lij and at &thorn;e laste it fe&llbar;e
in &thorn;e nettis and was slayne. After &thorn;is &thorn;are come
oute of &thorn;e rede&yogh; a grete multi-tude of mys&yogh; als grete
als foxes, and ete up &thorn;e dede bodys.  &THORN;are was na qwike
thynge&yogh;, &thorn;at &thorn;ay bate &thorn;at ne also so&ntail; it
dye&dtail;.  Bot harme di&dtail; &thorn;ay nane<MILESTONE N="29" UNIT="leaf"> to &thorn;e oste.
&THORN;a&ntail; come &thorn;are flyande amange&yogh; &thorn;a&mtail;
bakkes, grettere &thorn;a&mtail; wilde dowfes, and &thorn;aire tethe
ware lyke me&ntail;-tethe.  And &thorn;ay did&dtail; me&ntail;
meki&llbar; disese and hurte many me&ntail;.  Of su&mtail; &thorn;ay
bate offe &thorn;e nese; of sum &thorn;e eres.  In &thorn;e mornenynge
arely &thorn;are come many fewlis als grete as wlturs, ree&dtail; of
colour, and &thorn;aire fete & &thorn;aire bekes a&llbar; blakke.  Bot
&thorn;ay did&dtail; na disese to &thorn;e oste, bot went to &thorn;e
stanke-syde & drewe fisches & ele&yogh; oute of &thorn;e water, & ete
&thorn;a&mtail;.
</P>
<P> &THORN;ha&ntail; lefte Alexander &thorn;ir perilous place&yogh;,
and come wit his Oste, in-to &thorn;e cuntree of Bactrice&ntail;,
&thorn;e whilke was fu&llbar; of golde & o&thorn;er reches.  And
&thorn;e me&ntail; of &thorn;e cuntree resayfe&dtail; hym benyngly &
wirchipfully and gaffe hym and his Oste grete giftes.  And &thorn;are
he habade xx<HI REND="sup">ti</HI> dayes.  In &thorn;at cuntree &thorn;ay sawe trees
&thorn;at, in-stedde of leues, bare wo&llbar;e; &thorn;e whilke
folke&yogh; of &thorn;e cuntree gader&dtail; & made clathe
&thorn;are-offe.  &THORN;e knyghtes of Alexander wex wonder balde &
strange of hert because of &thorn;e victoryes &thorn;ay had&dtail;
wonne&ntail; of &thorn;e wilde beste&yogh; before neuenned.
</P>
<P>Fra thethyn, Alexander remowe&dtail; his Oste and come to &thorn;e
place whare Porus lay wit &thorn;e folke &thorn;at he had&dtail;
assemble&dtail;.  And one &thorn;e morne bathe Alexander and Porus
tuke &thorn;aire grounde & araye&dtail; &thorn;aire bate&llbar;s for
to feghte.  And tha&ntail;
<PB N="72">
Alexander lepped apo&ntail; his horse Buktiphalas and went bifore his
Oste & &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ay trumpede up & &thorn;e bate&llbar;s
joyne&dtail; same&ntail;, & faghte to-gedir ri&yogh;te sare.  Bot
&thorn;e Indienes fe&llbar; thikfalde in &thorn;e bate&llbar; as corne
dose in &thorn;e felde be-fore &thorn;e sythe.  And whe&ntail; Porus
saw that, he went and stode bi-fore a&llbar; his me&ntail;, and
crye&dtail; vn-ti&llbar; Alexander, & saide on this wyse: 'It
sitte&yogh; no&yogh;te ti&llbar; an emperour,' quo&thorn; he, 'to lose
his me&ntail; &thorn;us in vayne.  Bot it sitte&yogh; ti&llbar; hym
for to determyne his cause with his awen&ntail; hande&yogh;.  And
&thorn;arefore late thi folke stand sti&llbar; on &thorn;e ta syde, &
my&ntail; on &thorn;e to&thorn;er & late the & me feghte to gedir
han&dtail; for han&dtail;.  And if it happe&ntail; &thorn;at &thorn;ou
ouer-come me, my folke & I sa&llbar; be subiecte&yogh; vn-to &thorn;e.
And if I ouer come the, tha&ntail; thou & thi folke&yogh; be
subiecte&yogh; vn-to me.'  Thir worde&yogh; said Porus dispysan&dtail;
Alexander, bi-cause &thorn;at he was a ma&ntail; of litti&llbar;
stature.  For he was bot three cubites hye, & Porus was fyfe cubetes
hye & mare. And &thorn;arefore he trayste&dtail; hym a&llbar; in
strenghe of his body, no&yogh;te knawande &thorn;e vertu & &thorn;e
hardnes &thorn;at was hid&dtail; in Alexander.<MILESTONE N="29 bk." UNIT="leaf">  And than bathe &thorn;e ostes stode sti&llbar; ant lete &thorn;e twa kynge&yogh;
feghte same&ntail;, Porus gaffe Alexander a grete str[a]ke o&ntail;
&thorn;e hede, & was in poynte to hafe felle&dtail; hy&mtail;.  And
the&ntail; Porus knyghtes sett vp a grete Schowte.  And Porus
tourne&dtail; hym to &thorn;a&mtail;-warde for to reproue
&thorn;a&mtail; for &thorn;aire schowttyng.  And Alexandsr went
ti&llbar; hym manfully & tuke his swer&dtail; in bathe his hande&yogh;
& lete flye at hym & hitt hym fullbott one &thorn;e heue&dtail; & slew
hym.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e Indienes saw that &thorn;ay bi-gan
scharply for to fighte wit Alexander & his oste. Vnto whayme
Alexander spake & sayde: 'Wrechis,' quo&thorn; he, 'wharto feghte
&yogh;e se&ntail; &yogh;our kynge es dede.  Wate &yogh;e no&yogh;te
wele that thare na gouernour es &thorn;e folke are sparple&dtail;
be-lyfe als schepe &thorn;at ere wit-owtte&ntail; ane hirde.'
&THORN;e Indienes ansuer&dtail; & saide: 'Vs es leuer,' quo&thorn;
&thorn;ay, 'fighte manfully, and dye in the felde, &thorn;a&ntail; for
to see &thorn;e dissolacio&ntail; of oure folke, and oure lande be
distroye&dtail; & waste&dtail;.' 'Leues &yogh;our feghtynge,'
quo&thorn; Alexander, '& wende&yogh; hame to &yogh;our howse&yogh;
pesaybly & seurely.  For I swere &yogh;ow bi oure godde&yogh;, if
&yogh;ee wi&llbar; do so, &yogh;e sa&llbar; hafe no harme, ne
&yogh;our lande sa&llbar; no&yogh;te be distroye&dtail; ne
spoyle&dtail;, bicause &thorn;at &yogh;e hafe foghten so manfully for
&yogh;our kynge.'  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e Indienes
<PB N="73">
herde thir wordes &thorn;ay keste fra &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;aire
wapyne&yogh; & thanke&dtail; Alexander and wirchipe&dtail; him ri&yogh;te
als he had&dtail; bene a god&dtail;.  Than kyng Alexander luge&dtail;
hym &thorn;are & his Oste wit hym, & he comman&dtail; to bery &thorn;e
dede corse&yogh; &thorn;at ware slayne in &thorn;e Bate&llbar;, and
offre&dtail; sacrafice ti&llbar; his godde&yogh;.  Also he garte
Entere Porus &thorn;e kynge of Inde wirchipfully.
</P>
<P>Fra thethy&ntail; Alexander remowe&dtail; his Oste & come ti&llbar;
a cuntree &thorn;at was calle&dtail; Oxidraces. The folkes of
&thorn;at cuntree are wonder Symple me&ntail;, and no&yogh;te prowde,
& &thorn;ay are calle&dtail; Gumnosophiste.  &THORN;ay feghte neuer
mare ne stryfes.  &THORN;ay ga alway nake&dtail; & citez ne townnez
hafe &thorn;ay nane, Bot duellez in luge&yogh; & in caues.  Whe&ntail;
&thorn;e kyng of &thorn;is folke her&dtail; te&llbar; of &thorn;e
commyng of Alexander he wrate a lettre, & sent vn-ti&llbar; hym whare-
offe this was the tenour.  <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P><MILESTONE N="30" UNIT="leaf">'The coruptible Gumnosophist vn-ti&llbar; Alexander a ma&ntail; wee
wryte.  We here te&llbar; &thorn;at &thorn;ou comme&yogh; to werre
apo&ntail; vs, whare of we merueylle vs gretly.  For wit vs sa&llbar;
&thorn;ou fynd nathyng &thorn;at &thorn;ou may spoyle vs offe.  For we
hafe na thyng elles amange&yogh; vs, bot allanly whare with we may
sustene oure wafu&llbar; bodys.  What may &thorn;ou &thorn;a&ntail;
take fra vs.  Bot if &thorn;ou come for to feght wit vs, feghte
o&ntail;.  For I late the wele witt, &thorn;at oure symplenes
wi&llbar; we on na wyse lefe.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>Whe&ntail;
Alexander had rad&dtail; this lettre he sent ane ansuere agayne
o&ntail; this wyse.  'Paisably,' quo&thorn; he, 'wi&llbar; we
co&mtail; to &yogh;ow and no violence do &yogh;ow.'  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he wente in-to &thorn;e cuntree whare &thorn;ay
duelle&dtail;.  And he saw &thorn;a&mtail; ga nake&dtail; & duelle in
luges & in caues, & &thorn;aire wyfes & &thorn;aire childre away fra
&thorn;a&mtail;, walkan&dtail; wit wilde beste&yogh;.  And he
had&dtail; grete maruey&llbar;e, & aske&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; if
&thorn;ay had&dtail; any o&thorn;er howse&yogh;.  And &thorn;ay
ansuerde & sai&dtail;, 'Nay.  Bot in thir holette&yogh; due&llbar;e we
alwaye & in &thorn;ir caues.'  And Alexander commendi&dtail; gretely
&thorn;aire symplenesse, and bad &thorn;a&mtail; aske hy&mtail;
whate-so &thorn;ay walde.  And &thorn;ay ansuer&dtail; & sayde, 'Gyffe
vs,' quo&thorn; &thorn;ay, 'vndedlynesse, so &thorn;at we mow
no&yogh;te dye; for o&thorn;er reches couet we nane.'  Quo&thorn;
Alexander, 'I am dedely my selfe, how &thorn;a&ntail; may I giffe
&yogh;ou vndedlyness ?'  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ay her&dtail; hym say
soo &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ay ansuer&dtail; & sayde o&ntail; this
wyse.  'A, A, wreche&dtail; ma&ntail;,' quo&thorn; &thorn;ay, 'whare
to wende&yogh; &thorn;ou &thorn;us
<PB N="74">
aboute, & quelle&yogh; so many me&ntail;, & soo many ilke dedi&yogh;
dooes sen &thorn;ou wate wele &thorn;at &thorn;ou sa&llbar; dye.'
'For sothe,' quo&thorn; he, '&thorn;e cause whi I do it es of &thorn;e
prouydence of god&dtail;.  For hys mynystre I a&mtail;, doan&dtail;
&thorn;e commandement of hym.  &yogh;ee wate wele &thorn;at &thorn;e
see es no&yogh;te trubble&dtail; of hym selfe.  Bot whe&ntail;
&thorn;e wynde entres in-ti&llbar; hym, &thorn;a&ntail; it
stirre&yogh; hym & truble&yogh; hym.  I walde hafe risted&dtail; and
lefte a&llbar; werre.  Bot &thorn;are es ano&thorn;er spyryte &
suffres it no&yogh;te be in reste.'  And whe&ntail; Alexander hadde
sai&dtail; thir worde&yogh; he lefte &thorn;a&mtail; & went ti&llbar;
ano&thorn;er cuntree.
</P>
<P>Ano&thorn;er day, he come wit his Oste ti&llbar; a place wharee twa
ymage&yogh; ware, &thorn;e whilke Ercules gart make & sett in
&thorn;at place.  And &thorn;e tane of &thorn;a&mtail; was of fyne
golde and &thorn;e to&thorn;er of fyne Siluere, & the lenthe of aythir
of &thorn;a&mtail; was twa cubettis.  Whe&ntail; Alexander saw
&thorn;ir ymage&yogh;,<MILESTONE N="30 bk." UNIT="leaf"> he gert perche &thorn;a&mtail; for to witt,
whe&thorn;er &thorn;ay ware holle or massy.  And he fan&dtail;
&thorn;at &thorn;ay were a party ho&llbar;e.  And he garte stoppe
&thorn;e hole agayne and putt in &thorn;a&mtail; a thowsande nobles, &
fyve hundreth.  And fra &thorn;eine he remowed his Oste, and entrede
in-ti&llbar; a wildirnesse calde & myrk, so &thorn;at &thorn;ay myghte
vnnethes a&ntail; knawe ano&thorn;er or see ano&thorn;er. And fra
thythi&ntail; &thorn;ay went seue&ntail; daye iournee and entre&dtail;
in-ti&llbar; a wildirnesse, and come ti&llbar; a grete reuere.  And
bi-&yogh;onde &thorn;at riuere &thorn;ay saw wonder faire & wele
vesage&dtail; wome&ntail; cled&dtail; in foule clethyng & horrible;
and &thorn;ay had&dtail; in &thorn;aire hande&yogh; wapne made
a&llbar; of siluere, bicause &thorn;ay had&dtail; no&thorn;er
Ire&ntail; ne stele.  And &thorn;ay rade one horse.  And men saw
&thorn;ay nane amange&yogh; &thorn;a&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e
Oste walde hafe passede ouer this ryuere, &thorn;ay my&yogh;te
no&yogh;te be cause it was ri&yogh;te brade and fu&llbar; of dragones
and o&thorn;er monstres.
</P>
<P>Fra thethin &thorn;ay went aboute towarde&yogh; &thorn;e lefte
party of Inde and come till a dry Marras fu&llbar; of gret rede&yogh;.
And as &thorn;ay passed thurgh &thorn;at Marras, be-lyue &thorn;are
come owte of &thorn;e rede&yogh; a beste lyke ane ypotayne, whase
breste was lyke to &thorn;e cocadri&llbar;e, and his bakke lyk a sawe,
and his tethe wonder grete, & als scharpe as a suerde; bot in his
gangyng he was
<PB N="75">
als slaw als a snyle.  And, in his oute - come, he slew twa knyghtis
of Alexander.  This ilke beste my&yogh;te &thorn;ay on na wyse perche
wit &thorn;aire speres.  Bot wit mellis of yre&ntail; &thorn;ay slew
it.
</P>
<P>And fra &thorn;eine &thorn;ay trauelde thritty day iourne&yogh; and
come to &thorn;e vttermaste iles of Inde, & &thorn;are &thorn;ay
luge&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; beside&yogh; a ryuere &thorn;at es callede
in &thorn;at langage of Inde Hemmahurer.  And aboute &thorn;e
Eleuen&dtail; houre &thorn;ar come owte of &thorn;e wodde&yogh; a
grete multitude of Olyphante&yogh; & come apo&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail;
wit a gret birre & &thorn;aire groynes opy&ntail;.  And onane
Alexander lepe apo&ntail; his horse Buktiphalas and buske&dtail; hym
agaynes &thorn;a&mtail; and bad&dtail; &thorn;e macedoynes &thorn;at
&thorn;ay solde tak &thorn;aire horse and ilk a ma&ntail; a swyne in a
bande, & wende agaynes &thorn;e olyphantis.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e
oliphantes saw &thorn;a&mtail;, &thorn;ay come gapande wit
&thorn;aire groyne&yogh; redy te tak &thorn;a&mtail;.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;e Macedoynes saw &thorn;at &thorn;ay ware fere&dtail; and
durste no&yogh;te go to &thorn;a&mtail;.  And Alexander saide vn-to
&thorn;am, 'My wirchipfu&llbar; knyghtes,' quo&thorn; he, 'bese of gud
comforthe and drede&yogh; &yogh;ow na-thynge.  For, and &yogh;e
wi&llbar; gare &yogh;oure swyne crye faste<MILESTONE N="31" UNIT="leaf"> &yogh;e schall see a&llbar;
&thorn;ir Olyphantes flee ano&ntail;.'  And alsone als &thorn;e
Olyphantes herde &thorn;e crye of &thorn;e swyne, and &thorn;e noyse
of &thorn;aire trompes, &thorn;ay fled&dtail; and durste no&yogh;te
habyde.  And Alexander & his me&ntail; pursue&dtail; tha&mtail;, and
what wit nettis, whatt wit swerdes & speres, &thorn;ay slewe of
&thorn;a&mtail; a grete multitude, and come agayne to thaire tentis.
</P>
<P>Ano&thorn;er day &thorn;ay remove&dtail; &thorn;eine, and trauelde
thurg&hbar; the same wodde&yogh; of Inde.  And &thorn;ay fande
&thorn;are wome&ntail; with berdis rechande down&ntail; to &thorn;aire
pappes, & &thorn;aire heuede&yogh; playne abownne, and &thorn;ay ware
cled&dtail; a&llbar; in skynnes.  &THORN;ay chasede thir wome&ntail;
and sum of &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;ay tuke & broghte &thorn;a&mtail;
ti&llbar; Alexander.  And he gart spirre &thorn;am in the langage of
Inde, how &thorn;ay liffed in thase woddes, whare na duellyng was of
me&ntail;.  And &thorn;ay ansuere&dtail; & said, 'We lyffe a&llbar;,'
quo&thorn; &thorn;ay, 'wit venyso&ntail; &thorn;at we take in thir
woddes thurg&hbar; huntynge.'
</P>
<P>Whe&ntail; &thorn;ay ware passe&dtail; oute of thir wodde&yogh;
&thorn;ay come in-ti&llbar; a faire felde vn-ti&llbar; a place whare
this forsai&dtail; riuere ra&ntail;.  And &thorn;are &thorn;ay fande
bath me&ntail; & wome&ntail; a&llbar; naked.  And &thorn;ay ware
 
<PB N="76">
als rug&hbar;e of hare as &thorn;ay hade bene bestes.  Whase kynde &
custo&mtail; it was als wele to be in &thorn;e water, als o&ntail;
&thorn;e lande.  And als sone als &thorn;ay saw Alexander Oste onane
&thorn;ay fled&dtail; to &thorn;e water, and dowked in-till it.  Fra
&thorn;eine &thorn;ay trauel&dtail; xv day iournee, and entre&dtail;
in-ti&llbar; woddes &thorn;at ware fu&llbar; of cynocephals, &thorn;e
whilke als so&ntail; als &thorn;ay saw Alexander & his oste onane
&thorn;ay assaillede &thorn;am.  Bot Alexander & his me&ntail;, what
wit arowes whate wit speres & nettes slew a grete multitude of
&thorn;a&mtail;, and &thorn;e remenaunt of &thorn;a&mtail; fled&dtail;
here and thare in &thorn;e wodde&yogh;.
</P>
<P>Fra thethy&ntail; &thorn;ay went fourty dayes & come in-ti&llbar; a
champaynne cuntree, &thorn;at was a&llbar; Barayne, and na hye place
ne na hilles myghte be sene on na syde.  And as it ware aboute
&thorn;e xj houre of &thorn;e day, &thorn;are biga&ntail; so grete a
wynde to blawe oute of &thorn;e Este &thorn;at it blew doune to
&thorn;e erthe a&llbar; thaire tentis & &thorn;aire luges.  And
&thorn;are was grete disese ymang &thorn;e oste.  For &thorn;e wynde
tuk fire-brandes oute of fyres &thorn;at &thorn;ay had&dtail; made,
and smate dyuerse me&ntail; & brynte &thorn;a&mtail;.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; Alexander knyghtes mournurede gretly & said
amange&yogh; &thorn;am, '&THORN;e wrethe & &thorn;e wreke of oure
godde&yogh;,' quo&thorn; &thorn;ay, 'falle&yogh; apo&ntail; vs,
Bicause we seke to ferre towarde &thorn;e so&ntail; rysynge.'  'My
wirchipfu&llbar; knyghte&yogh;,' quo&thorn; Alexander, 'bese<MILESTONE
N="31 bk." UNIT="leaf"> of gud
comforthe and no thyng ferde for this tempeste es no&yogh;tee
falle&ntail; thurg&hbar; wrethe of oure goddes bot be-cause of equinox
of heruest.'  Whe&ntail; &thorn;e wynde was cesse&dtail; &thorn;ay
gadirde te-gedir &thorn;at &thorn;e wyn&dtail; had&dtail;
sparple&dtail;.
</P>
<P>Fra &thorn;eine &thorn;ay went xxv days and come in-ti&llbar; a
grene valay, and &thorn;are &thorn;ay luge&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail;.
Than commande&dtail; Alexander &thorn;at &thorn;ay schuld make many
fyres. For it bega&ntail; for to be vnsufferable calde. And thare
be-gan for to falle grete flawghtis of snawe, as &thorn;ay had bene
grete lokkes of wo&llbar;e.  Whe&ntail; Alexander saw that, he was
ferde &thorn;at it schul&dtail; no&yogh;te hafe cesse&dtail; sone, aud
bad his me&ntail; &thorn;at &thorn;ay suld tred dou&ntail; &thorn;e
snawe & fu&llbar; it wit &thorn;aire fete. And &thorn;aire fyres also
helpe &thorn;a&mtail; gretly. Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse &thorn;are ware
fyve hundrethe of &thorn;e Oste ded&dtail; thurgh&thorn;at snawe,
&thorn;e whilk Alexander gart bery.  &THORN;a&ntail; &thorn;are felle
a passan&dtail; grete rayne, and &thorn;e snaw cessed.  Wit &thorn;e
rayne, also, &thorn;are come so thikke a myste, &thorn;at contenually
three days to gedir &thorn;ay
<PB N="77">
saw na son&ntail;. And oute of &thorn;e clude &thorn;at hange
abow&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;er fe&llbar; as it had&dtail; bene
grete fyrebrande&yogh; &thorn;e whilk brynt many of thaire tenttis and
of &thorn;aire luges.  And onane Alexander offre&dtail; sacrafice
ti&llbar; his godde&yogh; and bad his knyghtis put alde ryue&ntail;
clathe&yogh; wate bi-fore &thorn;e fire, and he made his prayere. And
also so&ntail; the whedir wexe clere & faire.
</P>
<P>Fra thethin, &thorn;ay remowe&dtail; and come ti&llbar; a grete
ryuere &thorn;at es calle&dtail; Ganges & &thorn;are &thorn;ay luged
&thorn;a&mtail;.  And as &thorn;ay luke&dtail; ouer on the to&thorn;er
syde, &thorn;ay saw twa or thre me&ntail; walke up & down&ntail;
&thorn;are.  And Alexander bad&dtail; his me&ntail; spirre
&thorn;a&mtail; in &thorn;e langage of Inde what &thorn;ey ware.  And
&thorn;ay ansuere&dtail; & sai&dtail;.  'We are Bragmayns,' quo&thorn;
&thorn;ay.  Alexander had&dtail; grete desyre to speke wit &thorn;e
Bragmayns.  Bot he my&yogh;te no&yogh;te wyn&ntail; ouer &thorn;e
water; it was so depe & so brade Bot if it had bene in &thorn;e
monethe of July and Auguste. And also it was fu&llbar; of ypotaynes &
scorpyones and cocadrilles, out take&ntail; in &thorn;e forsai&dtail;
monethes And whe&ntail; he saw &thorn;at he myghte on na wyse
wyn&ntail; ouer he was re&yogh;te heuy.  And belyfe he garte make a
lytti&llbar; bate of redis, & couerde it wit nowtte hydis & gerte pykk
it wele bathe wit-in & wit-owtte&ntail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e bate
was made, he gert a knyght of his gang in-to it, and gaffe hym a
lettre wit hym for to bere<MILESTONE N="32" UNIT="leaf"> to Dindimus, &thorn;at was kyng of &thorn;e
Bragmayns, of whilk lettre &thorn;is was &thorn;e tenour.  <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P>' Kyng of kynges and lorde of lorde&yogh;, Alexander &thorn;e
so&ntail; of god&dtail; Amo&ntail; & of &thorn;e quene Olympias, vn-to
Dindimus kyng of Bragmayns, ioy.  Euer se&ntail; we were come&ntail;
to &thorn;at age &thorn;at we couthe discerne by-twix gud & i&llbar;
we hafe desyre&dtail; soueraynly for to hafe wysdomme & konnyng, & for
to putt away fra vs ignorance & vnconnynge.  For as &thorn;e wise
techynge of oure philosop&hbar;res declares opynly, Eloquence wit
owtte&ntail; witt & wisdo&mtail; dose ofte-sythes mare skathe
&thorn;a&ntail; gude.  &THORN;arefore we hafe wele vnderstande&ntail;
by relacio&ntail; of dyuerse me&ntail;, &thorn;at &yogh;our lyfe &
&yogh;our maners are diuise&dtail; and diuerse fra a&llbar; o&thorn;er
me&ntail;; so &thorn;at no&thorn;er o&ntail; &thorn;e See ne on
&thorn;e lande &yogh;e seke na helpe and &thorn;at &yogh;e &yogh;eme
ano&thorn;er manere of doctryne &thorn;a&ntail; we hafe lerende of
oure doctours.  Whare-fore we pray &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e
wi&llbar; certyfye vs bi &yogh;our lettres of &yogh;our lyffe and
&yogh;our maners and &yogh;our doctryne. For
<PB N="78">
perauenture we may take &thorn;are of su&mtail; gud Ensample, and
&yogh;our wysdome & &yogh;our gudnesse neuer be &thorn;e lesse. For it
es na harme ti&llbar; a ma&ntail; thurg&hbar; his gudnes to make
ano&thorn;er ma&ntail; gude as he es.  The whilk I may proue bi this
simylitu&dtail;ÑI supposse a ma&ntail; had&dtail; in his han&dtail; a
lyght candi&llbar;, many o&thorn;er candi&llbar;s may be lyghte&dtail;
&thorn;are at, it lose na-thynge of his lyghte. And ri&yogh;te so it
es of &thorn;e gudnesse of a ma&ntail;.  For many me&ntail; may take
gude ensample of hym & his gudnesse be na thynge enmenuste
&thorn;areby.  Where-fore &yogh;itt eft-sons we pray &yogh;ow
&thorn;at wit-owtte&ntail; any taryinge or delay, &yogh;e schowe vs
&thorn;e maners of &yogh;our lyffyng.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>Than kyng
Dindimus resaffe&dtail; &thorn;is lettre wirchipfully and wrate
ano&thorn;er agayne of this tenour.  <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P>' Dyndimus maister of &thorn;e Bragmayns vn-to kyng Alexander ioy &
gretynge.  We hafe wele vndirstande&ntail; by &thorn;e tenour of thi
lettres, &thorn;at &thorn;ou desyres gretly for to hafe verray
connynge and perfitt wysdo&mtail;; &thorn;e whilke are meki&llbar;
better &thorn;a&ntail; any kyngdo&mtail;; for &thorn;ay may neuer be
boghte wit na pryce, whare-fore I comen&dtail; &thorn;e gretly,
knawyng &thorn;at &thorn;ou arte a wyse ma&ntail;.  For ane Emperour
wit-owtte&ntail;<MILESTONE N="32 bk." UNIT="leaf"> wisdo&mtail;, es noghte lorde of his subiectis, Bot
his sugettis ere lordes of hym.  &yogh;e wrate vnti&llbar; vs, praying
vs for to schewe &yogh;owe oure maners of lyffynge, ilke a poynte
efter o&thorn;er, &thorn;e whilke we halde inpossible for to doo.  For
oure maner of lyffynge es fu&llbar; ferre dyuerse fra &yogh;ours.  For
no&thorn;er we wirchipe &thorn;e goddes &thorn;at &yogh;e wirchipe, ne
ledis &thorn;e lyfe &thorn;at &yogh;e lede.  And if I writte &yogh;owe
oughte of oure maner of lyffyng, &yogh;e may hafe na sauoure
&thorn;are in, be-cause &yogh;e are besily ocupie&dtail; wit dedis of
armes.  Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse &thorn;at &yogh;e say no&yogh;te
&thorn;at I layne oure lyfe fra &yogh;ow for envy, Als meki&llbar; as
come&yogh; to my mynde at &thorn;is tyme I sa&llbar; writt vnto
&yogh;ow of oure maners.
</P>
<P>' We Bragmayns lede&yogh; a symple lyfe & a clene and &thorn;e
wirchipyng of many goddes we eschu.  We do na synnes ne we wi&llbar;
hafe na mare &thorn;a&ntail; reso&ntail; of kynde asches.  A&llbar;
thynge&yogh; we suffer & &thorn;at, say we, es necessary &
ynog&hbar;e, &thorn;at es no&yogh;te ouermeki&llbar;. We ti&llbar;e na
lande, ne eryes, ne sawes, ne &yogh;okes no&thorn;er ox ne horse in
plughe ne in carte.  Ne nett caste we nane in &thorn;e see, for to
take fysche; Ne hunttynge ne fewlynge vse we
<PB N="79">
nanne.  Mete & drynke hafe we ynoghe, and o&thorn;er mete seke we
nane, bot &thorn;at &thorn;e erthe oure allere moder wit-owtte&ntail;
mannes labour brynges furthe.  Wit swilke metis we fi&llbar; oure
wambes, whilke nu&yogh;es vs no&yogh;te, ne na harme dose.  And
&yogh;it of swilke metis we fi&llbar; no&yogh;te oure bodis to
fu&llbar;.  For amange&yogh; vs it es an vn-semely thynge & an
vn-leefu&llbar; to see a grete-belye&dtail; ma&ntail;.  And
&thorn;are-for ere we a&llbar; oure lyfe ty&mtail; wit-owtte&ntail;
sekenesse & lyffe&yogh; lang & alwaye are in gude hele ti&llbar; oure
lyffes ende.  We vse neuer-mare na medcyns ne sekes na helpe for
&thorn;e hele of oure bodys.  At a terme of deede endes oure lyfes,
for ane of vs leues na langere &thorn;a&ntail; a&ntail;-o&thorn;er,
Bot efter &thorn;e order of &thorn;e birthe of ma&ntail;, &thorn;e
terme of deede comes ti&llbar; ilke a ma&ntail;.  Thare come&yogh;
nane of vs at na fire for na calde, ne clathe&yogh; come&yogh;
&thorn;are nane apo&ntail; vs, Bot alway we ga nake&dtail;.  We
fulfi&llbar; neuer &thorn;e desyres of oure bodys.  Thurg&hbar;
pacyence we suffree a&llbar; thynge&yogh;.  A&llbar; oure inwarde
enemys we slaa, So &thorn;at we drede nane enemys wit-owtte&ntail;.
For lightlyer es a citee or a caste&llbar;e take&ntail; &thorn;at es
ensegge&dtail; bathe wit inwarde enemys & wit-owtte&ntail;,
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;at &thorn;at es ensegge&dtail; allanly wit
owtwarde enemys.  Bot &thorn;ou, emperour, feghtes agaynes
owtwarde&yogh; enemys for [to] foster & nuresche thy&ntail;
inwarde&yogh; enemys, &thorn;e whilke ere fendes of he&llbar;e.  We
Bragmayns has slayne a&llbar; oure inwarde&yogh; enemys and
&thorn;arefore we drede nane owtwarde enemys ne nane helpe sekes for
to hafe agayne&yogh; &thorn;a&mtail;<MILESTONE N="33" UNIT="leaf"> no&thorn;er be see ne be lan&dtail;.  Bot we ere always sewre ynoghe, and lyffe&yogh;
wit-owtte&ntail; any drede.  Oure bodys we hi&llbar; wit &thorn;e
leues of trees and &thorn;e fruyte of &thorn;a&mtail; we ete.  We ete
mylke also and drynkes water of a gude ryuere or of swete welles.  We
wirchippe a god&dtail;, and ti&llbar; hym alwaye we &yogh;elde
lonynge&yogh;.  We desire &thorn;e life of &thorn;e werlde &thorn;at
es to come, and vs liste no&yogh;te here &thorn;e &thorn;yng &thorn;at
turne&yogh; to na profett.  We spekke no&yogh;te meki&llbar;, Bot
whe&ntail; we ere artede for to speke we say no&yogh;te bot &thorn;e
sothe, and onane we halde vs sti&llbar;.  Reches luffe we no&yogh;te.
Couetise es a thynge &thorn;at may no&yogh;te be fille&dtail;,
&thorn;e whilke oftesythe&yogh; brynge&yogh; a ma&ntail; ti&llbar; a
mescheuous ende.  Wrethe ne envie es &thorn;are nane amange&yogh; vs,
ne nane of vs es strangere &thorn;a&ntail; ano&thorn;er.  Of the
pouert &thorn;at we hafe we ere riche, for we hafe it in como&ntail;.
We strife neuer mare, ne beres neuer wape&ntail;.  We bere peesse
ilka&ntail; ti&llbar; o&thorn;er of custo&mtail;, no&yogh;te
thurg&hbar; vertu.  Domes hafe we nane amanges vs, for we do nane
i&llbar;, whare-fore
 
<PB N="80">
we schulde be calle&dtail; vn-to dome.  A law &thorn;are es &thorn;at
es contrary til oure kynde.  For we do na mercy, bi-cause we do no
thyng whare-fore we sulde aske mercy. We do na labour &thorn;at
pertene&yogh; to couetise or auarice.  We giffe no&yogh;te oure bodyse
to lechorye, we do nane advowtrye, ne we do na syn&ntail; whare-fore
vs sulde nede to do penance.  We fynde na fawte in na thynge, For we
a&llbar; does that &thorn;at righte es.  We dye na sodeyne dede, For
thurg&hbar; foule dedis we corupte no&yogh;te &thorn;e ayere.  We vse
na clathes &thorn;at are littede of dyuerse coloures.  Oure wiffes ne
are no&yogh;te gayly araye&dtail; for to plese vs. Ne wit
&thorn;a&mtail; we como&ntail; no&yogh;te bi-cause of luste of
lecherye, bot bi-cause of childre getynge.  Our wyffes sekes na
no&thorn;er clethynge, &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e forluke of god&dtail;
hase grante&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail;.  And whaa dare take apo&ntail; hym
for to chaunge his wirkynge, an heghe sy&ntail; vs thynke it ware till
any ma&ntail; for to presume to do it.  Baththis vse we nane, ne warme
water to wasche oure bodys wit a&llbar;.  &THORN;e So&ntail; mynistres
vs hete, and &thorn;e dewe of &thorn;e ayer ministre&yogh; vs moyster
& wete.  We hafe na thoghte of na thynge, ne we schewe na lordechipe
abown&ntail; o&thorn;er me&ntail; &thorn;at ere lyke vn-ti&llbar; us.
For a grete crueltee we halde it to constreyne a ma&ntail; to serue
vs, whayme kynde & &thorn;e forluke of god&dtail; hase made oure
bro&thorn;er als fre als we are.  We brynne na stanes for to make lyme
off and &thorn;are-wit to make vs howses at due&llbar;e in, and
curiouse palase&yogh;: ne vessell make we nane. In caues or
creuyce&yogh; of cragges we duelle, whare thare come&yogh; na noyse of
wyndes<MILESTONE N="33 bk." UNIT="leaf"> ne whare vs thare drede na rayne.  On &thorn;e erthe we slepe
wit-owtte&ntail; any besynesse.  Swilk howses we hafe; in &thorn;e
whilke, whils we lyffe, we due&llbar;e, and whe&ntail; we dye,
&thorn;ay ere oure graues.  We sayle no&yogh;te in &thorn;e see aboute
na merchandyse, in &thorn;e whilke &thorn;ay suffre many perills
&thorn;at sayles &thorn;arein & many meruaylles ca&ntail; te&llbar;
offe.  The crafte of Eloquence & faire speche, lere we no&yogh;te for
to polishe oure wordes; Bot thurgh &thorn;e sympilnesse &thorn;at we
hafe &thorn;at suffres vs no&yogh;te to lye, a&llbar; oure speche we
speke.  Scoles of philosophres haunt wee no&yogh;te, whase
techechynge&yogh; es alway discordand & na thynge certayne, ne
stabi&llbar; diffines, bot for &thorn;e mare partye lyes.  Bot
&thorn;a scoles we haunte in &thorn;e whilke we lere to lyffe
vertuosly and also thynges &thorn;at teches vs for to do no wrange to
no ma&ntail;.  Bot after verray rightwisnesse to helpe ilk ma&ntail;
at oure powere.  Plays lufe we nane.
<PB N="81">
Bot if vs liste hafe any disporte we take & rede&yogh; &thorn;e lyfes
& &thorn;e dedis of oure Auncestres, and oure predicessours.  And if
we fynde any thynge in &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at es cause of laughtre
&thorn;ar-at we wepe & makes dole.  Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse we behalde
o&thorn;er thynges of &thorn;e whilke oure hertis ere gladdide and
grete lykyng has, &thorn;at es at say, heue&ntail;-schyne wit sternes
wit-owt nowmer; &thorn;e so&ntail; faire & bryghte, of whase
bryghtnesse a&llbar; &thorn;e werlde takes lyghte and hete.  The see
we se alwaye of purpour coloure, and whe&ntail; tempeste&yogh;
ryse&yogh; &thorn;are-i&ntail; it distruyes no&yogh;te &thorn;e
lan&dtail; &thorn;at es nere it, as it does in &yogh;oure partes. Bot
he embrace&yogh; it as his sister and gase abuoute it.  And in
&thorn;e se we see many dyuerse kynde&yogh; of Fisches, Delphines &
porpase&yogh; layke &thorn;a&mtail;.  We hafe lykyng also for to
bihalde faire feldes alouer floresche&dtail; wit flores of &thorn;e
whilke a swete reflaire enters in-ti&llbar; oure nose&yogh;, in
&thorn;e whilke a sensible saule hase maste delite. Also we delit vs
in faire place&yogh; of wodde&yogh; & of swete welles whare we here
swete sange&yogh; of fewles.  This customs hafe we al-way, &thorn;e
whilke, & &thorn;ou walde halde no&yogh;te bot a while, we trowe
&thorn;ou suld thynke &thorn;a&mtail; ri&yogh;te har&dtail;.  Blame
no&yogh;te me, for a&llbar; &thorn;at &thorn;ou requerede me be
&thorn;i lettres I send &thorn;e wrety&ntail;.  Neuer-&thorn;e-less,
and it sulde no&yogh;t displese the, I walde te&llbar; &thorn;e a
litti&llbar; of oure doctryne &thorn;e whilke makes oure lyfe to seme
harde vn-to &thorn;e.  &YOGH;ee hafe wit-in a schorte while
conquere&dtail; & made sugete vn-to &yogh;our empire a&llbar; Asy,
Europe, & Affryke.  As &yogh;our selfe hase sayde<MILESTONE N="34" UNIT="leaf"> &yogh;e make &thorn;e lighte of &thorn;e so&ntail; to faile, whe&ntail; &yogh;e
seke &thorn;e termes of his course thurg&hbar; werre.  &YOGH;e ete
a&llbar; manere of thynges &thorn;at corne&yogh; ti&llbar; hande, And
&yogh;our vesages seme&yogh; as &yogh;e ware fastande & hungry.
&YOGH;e slaa &yogh;our childre makande sacrafice of &thorn;a&mtail; to
Mawmetes.  &YOGH;e sawe discorde bi-twix kynges and thase &thorn;at
schulde be meke &yogh;e stirre for to be prowde.  &YOGH;e make
me&ntail; to thynke &thorn;at grete space of landes sufice&yogh;
&thorn;a&mtail; no&yogh;te And so &thorn;ay seke duellynge place&yogh;
of heue&ntail;.
</P>
<P>'Also thurg&hbar; &yogh;our goddes &yogh;e do many i&llbar; dedis,
as &thorn;ay did&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; selfe, Ensample of Iubiter
&yogh;our god&dtail; & of Proserpyna &thorn;at &yogh;e wirchipe as a
goddesse.  For Iubiter defoule&dtail; many mens
<PB N="82">
wyfes, and Proserpyna made many me&ntail; to do advowtry wit hir.
Fu&llbar; wreche&dtail; & fu&llbar; hye fules &thorn;ay ere, &thorn;at
swilke goddes wirchipes.  &YOGH;ee wi&llbar; no&yogh;te suffer
me&ntail; lyfe in &thorn;aire awen&ntail; libertee bot makes
&thorn;a&mtail; &yogh;our thralles & &yogh;our sugetes.  &YOGH;e deme
no&yogh;te ri&yogh;twisly, &yogh;e gerre &yogh;our iuge&yogh; change
&yogh;our lawes as &yogh;ow liste.  &YOGH;e say many thynge&yogh;
&thorn;at sulde be donne, bot &yogh;e do &thorn;a&mtail; no&yogh;te.
&YOGH;e halde na ma&ntail; wysse bot hym &thorn;at hase Eloquence of
speche.  &YOGH;e hafe a&llbar; &yogh;our witt in &yogh;our
tunge&yogh;, and a&llbar; &yogh;our wysdome es in &yogh;our mouthe.
&yogh;e lufe golde & siluer & gaders &thorn;am to-gedir and
desyre&yogh; to hafe grete howse&yogh; & hye, and grete multitude of
seruande&yogh;.  &YOGH;e ete & drynk to meki&llbar;, so &thorn;at
oftymes &yogh;our stomake thurgh grete repleccio&ntail; es
greue&dtail; & many sekenesse &thorn;are-thurg&hbar; &yogh;e fa&llbar;
in, & so ofte sythes dyes before &yogh;our tyme.  &YOGH;e wolde
euer-mare halde &yogh;our reches and a&llbar; thynge&yogh; &thorn;at
&yogh;e may gete.  Bot a&llbar; thynge&yogh; at &thorn;e laste leues
&yogh;ow.  &THORN;e wysdo&mtail; allanly of &thorn;e Bragmayns
passe&yogh; as &yogh;our witt & &yogh;our wysdo&mtail;.  For, & we
wele consedere, &thorn;e me moder &thorn;at broghte forthe stanes &
trees, of &thorn;e same was bathe oure bygynnyng & &yogh;ours.
&YOGH;e honowre &yogh;our Sepultours curyousely wit golde & syluer,
and in vesse&llbar;e made of precyouse stanes &yogh;e putt &thorn;e
asse of &yogh;our bodys, whe&ntail; &thorn;ay ere brynne&dtail;.  And
what may be werre &thorn;a&ntail; for ti&llbar; take &thorn;e banes,
&thorn;at &thorn;e erthe sulde hafe, for to ga bry&ntail;
&thorn;a&mtail;, and no&yogh;te suffere &thorn;e erthe resayffe his
element &thorn;e whilke he broghte forthe.
</P>
<P>'We sla na beste&yogh; in &thorn;e wirchipe of godde&yogh;.  Nee
temples make we nane, for to sett in ymage&yogh; of golde or of
siluere in &thorn;e name of false godde&yogh;, as &yogh;e do; ne
awters of golde and of precious stanes.  &YOGH;e hafe swilke a lawe
for to honoure &yogh;our godde&yogh; wit &yogh;our gudes for &thorn;at
&thorn;ay sa&llbar; here &yogh;our prayers.  Bot we vndirstande & wate
wele &thorn;at no&thorn;er for golde ne siluer; ne for &thorn;e blode
of calues nor gayte ne schepe God&dtail; heres any ma&ntail;.  Bot for
gude werkes &thorn;e whilke God&dtail; lufes, and thurg&hbar; &thorn;e
wordes of deuote prayere.  God&dtail; wi&llbar; here a ma&ntail; for
&thorn;e worde.  For thurg&hbar; worde we ere lyke to God&dtail;.  For
God&dtail; es worde,<MILESTONE N="34 bk." UNIT="leaf"> and &thorn;at worde made a&llbar; &thorn;e werlde
aud thurg&hbar; &thorn;at worde a&llbar; thynge&yogh; hase beyng,
Mouyng & lyfe.  That worde wirchipe wee and luffes & honowres.
God&dtail; es a spirite.  And he lufes na-thyng bot &thorn;at that es
clene.  Whare-fore we halde &yogh;ow fu&llbar; grete foles, that
wene&yogh; &yogh;our kynde be heuenly, and &thorn;at &yogh;e hafe
<PB N="83">
communicacio&ntail; with God&dtail;, And neuer-&thorn;e-less files
&yogh;our kynde wit advowtries & fornicacions & seruyce of Mawmettis &
false goddis, and many o&thorn;er wikkede dedis: ilke a day &thorn;is
&yogh;e do.  &THORN;is &yogh;e luffe, and &thorn;arefore whe&ntail;
&yogh;e ere dede ye sa&llbar; suffere tourmentis wit-owtte&ntail;
nowmer. &YOGH;e wene &thorn;at God&dtail; wi&llbar; be mercyable vn-to
&yogh;ow bi-cause &thorn;at &yogh;e offre hym blode & flesse of
dyuerse beste&yogh;.  Bot we on &thorn;e contrarye wyse luffe&yogh;
clennesse bathe of Body & of saule, so &thorn;at we mowe &hbar;afe
after &thorn;is lyfe ioy &thorn;at neuer sa&llbar; &hbar;afe ende.
</P>
<P>'&YOGH;ee serue no&yogh;te a God&dtail; &thorn;at regne&yogh; in
heue&ntail;, Bot &yogh;e do seruyce to many false goddis.  For als so
many membris, als &yogh;e &hbar;afe o&ntail; &yogh;our bodys, als many
goddis &yogh;e wirc&hbar;ipe & serues.  For &yogh;e ca&llbar;e a
ma&ntail; &thorn;e lesse werlde, and ri&yogh;te as a ma&ntail;
here hase many lymmes, so &yogh;e say &thorn;are are many
goddes in heue&ntail;.  &YOGH;e say Iuno es god&dtail; of &thorn;e
hert, bi-cause he was wonder angry; and Mars &yogh;e say es god&dtail;
of &thorn;e breste, bi-cause he was prynce of Bate&llbar;s.  Mercury
&yogh;e ca&llbar;e god&dtail; of &thorn;e tung, bicause he was wonder
euloquent in spekyng. Hercules &yogh;e trowe be god&dtail; of &thorn;e
armes, Bi-cause he di&dtail; twelfe passande dedes of armes.  &YOGH;ee
trowe Bacus be god&dtail; of &thorn;e t&hbar;rotte, for he fande
firste drounkynnesse.  Couetise, &yogh;e sauy, es god&dtail; of
&thorn;e lyuer, for he was &thorn;e firste lechoure &thorn;at euer
was.  And &yogh;e say &thorn;at he &hbar;ase in his hande a byrnand
fyrebrande whare-wit he styrres &thorn;e luste of lechery.  Cereris
&yogh;e ca&llbar;e god&dtail; of &thorn;e wambe, bi-cause sc&hbar;o
was &thorn;e firste Fynder of wheete.  And Venus, be-cause scho was
moder of lec&hbar;ery, &yogh;e say scho es god&dtail; of &thorn;e
preuee membres of ma&ntail; & woma&ntail;.  Mynerua, bi-cause scho was
fynder of many werkes, &yogh;e say wisdome riste&yogh; in her, and
&thorn;are-fore &yogh;e ca&llbar; hir god&dtail; of &thorn;e
heue&dtail;.  And o&ntail; &thorn;is wyse a&llbar; &thorn;e body of
ma&ntail; &yogh;e deuyde in goddes, & na party &thorn;areoffe &yogh;e
lefe in &yogh;our awe&ntail; powere.  Ne &yogh;e trowe no&yogh;te that
a god&dtail; &thorn;at es in heue&ntail; made &yogh;our bodys of
noghte.  False goddes &yogh;e wirchipe &thorn;at sa&llbar; brynge
&yogh;ow to thralledome & schame & schenchipe, and to thay&mtail;
&yogh;e make sacrafice & tribute payes.  Vn-to Mars &yogh;e offere a
Bare.  To Bacus &yogh;e offere a gayte ; To Iune a pacoke; To Iubiter
a Bulle; To Appollo<MILESTONE N="35" UNIT="leaf"> a swane; To Venus a doufe; To Mynerua ane owle; To
Cereris floure; To Mercury hony.  And Hercules &yogh;e onowre&ntail;
wit floures & grene braunches of treesse&yogh;.  &THORN;e temple
<PB N="84">
of Couetyse &yogh;e enourne wit rose&yogh;.  A&llbar;e &yogh;our
myghte & &yogh;oure triste &yogh;e putt in &thorn;am &thorn;at may
&yogh;ow na-thyng helpe at nede.  Now sothely &yogh;e pray
&thorn;a&mtail; no&yogh;te to be &yogh;our helpers, Bot &yogh;oure
tourmentours.  For it byhoues nedis be &thorn;at, als many goddes als
&yogh;e wirchipe & gyffe&yogh; &thorn;a&mtail; powere of &yogh;our
lymmes, als many tourmente&yogh; &yogh;e suffere.  Ane of &yogh;our
goddes stirres &yogh;ow to fornycacion.  Ane o&thorn;er to ete &
drynke to meki&llbar;, and ano&thorn;er to feghte & stryffe.  A&llbar;
ere &thorn;ay &yogh;our lordes, and to &thorn;a&mtail; &yogh;e obey &
serues and wirchippes.  So &thorn;at wonder it es &thorn;at &yogh;our
wrechi&dtail; bodys fayles no&yogh;te for &thorn;e many seruyce&yogh;
&thorn;at &yogh;e do to so many goddes.  And gud ri&yogh;te it es
&thorn;at &yogh;e serue swilke goddes bi-cause of &thorn;e many
wikkede dedis &thorn;at &yogh;e do.  And for &yogh;e wi&llbar;
no&yogh;te cesse of &yogh;our i&llbar; dedis, &thorn;arefore &yogh;e
serue swilke goddes ti&llbar; &yogh;our awen&ntail; harme, For
euermare &thorn;ay desyre &thorn;at &yogh;e do i&llbar;.  If &yogh;our
goddes here &yogh;ow whe&ntail; &yogh;e pray to &thorn;am, &thorn;ay
do &yogh;ow harme in &yogh;our conscience.  For &thorn;at that &yogh;e
pray fore es i&llbar;. And if &thorn;ay here &yogh;ow noghte,
&thorn;a&ntail; ere &thorn;ay contrarye to &yogh;our desyres.
Whare-fore whethir &thorn;ay here &yogh;ow, or &thorn;ay here &yogh;ow
noghte, euer-mare &thorn;ay do &yogh;ow disesse.  &THORN;ise ere
&thorn;a tourmente&yogh; &thorn;at oure doctours talde vs offe,
&thorn;at here in this werlde tourmente&yogh; &yogh;ow as &yogh;e ware
dede.  For, and &yogh;e consyder wele, &thorn;are may no man suffere
wers tourment &thorn;a&ntail; &yogh;e doo.  For a&llbar; &thorn;e
takens &thorn;at oure doctours telle&yogh; vs ere in he&llbar;e, and
we see &thorn;a&mtail; in &yogh;owe.  &THORN;are are many paynes in
he&llbar;e, &yogh;e suffre paynes when &yogh;e wake for to do
advowtres, fornycacions, & thiftes, ma&ntail;-slawghters.  And
namely, &thorn;at &yogh;e bee fille&dtail; of werldly reches &yogh;a,
& of worldly rechesse.  For oure doctours says, &thorn;are es in helle
so meki&llbar; thriste, &thorn;at it may neuer be sloken&dtail;; and
&yogh;e haue so grete Couetyse of worldely reches &thorn;at &yogh;e
may neuer be fu&llbar;.  &THORN;ay say also &thorn;at in helle
&thorn;are es a hunde &thorn;at es callede Cerberus &thorn;e whilke
hase thre heuedes; And if &yogh;ee conseder ry&yogh;te, &yogh;our
wambes are lyke Cerberus.  For meki&llbar; etyng & drynkkynge,
&thorn;ay say also, &thorn;are es in he&llbar;e a maner of nedder
&thorn;at es calle&dtail; Idra.  And &yogh;e for &thorn;e many
vice&yogh;, &thorn;at &yogh;e hafe bicause of &yogh;our fu&llbar;
wambe&yogh; may be callede Idra.  Whare-fore & we bi-helde wele
a&llbar; &thorn;e illes &thorn;at
<PB N="85">
are in he&llbar;e, &thorn;ay due&llbar;e in &yogh;ow.<MILESTONE
N="35 bk." UNIT="leaf">  Waa es
&yogh;ow, wreches, &thorn;at swilke a mysbileue haldes; whare-fore
after &thorn;is lyfe, &yogh;e mo&ntail; suffere paynes
wit-owtte&ntail; nowmer.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>Whe&ntail; Alexander
had&dtail; red&dtail; &thorn;is lettre, he was wonder wrathe, be-cause
of iniury of his godde&yogh;.  Neuer-&thorn;e-less, be-lyfe he gart
write ano&thorn;er agayne of this tenour.  <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P>'Kyng of kynges, and lorde of lorde&yogh;, Alexander &thorn;e
so&ntail; of god&dtail; Amo&ntail; and of &thorn;e quene Olympias, to
Dindimus, kyng of &thorn;e Bragmayns, gretyng.  If a&llbar; be
fu&ntail; trew amanges &yogh;ow &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase sent
wrety&ntail; in thy lettres, &thorn;a&ntail; allanly &yogh;e are gude
me&ntail; in &thorn;is werlde; for as &thorn;ou says &yogh;e do
na&ntail; i&llbar;.  Bot wit &thorn;ou wele for certayne, &thorn;at
&thorn;is maner of lyffyng comme&yogh; no&yogh;te of vertu bot of
custo&mtail;.  A&llbar; thynge&yogh; &thorn;at we do, &yogh;e saye es
syn&ntail;.  And a&llbar; &thorn;e crafte&yogh;, &thorn;at ere
amange&yogh; vs on &thorn;e same wyse, &yogh;e say, &thorn;ay ere
synnes.  &YOGH;e wi&llbar; distroye a&llbar; &thorn;e customs
&thorn;at ma&ntail;-kynde hedir-towarde hase had&dtail; & vse&dtail;.
Owther &yogh;e schew bi &yogh;our worde&yogh;, &thorn;at &yogh;e are
godde&yogh;, or e&llbar;s ti&llbar; goddes &yogh;e hafe envy. And
&thorn;are-fore &yogh;e say, as &yogh;e say, I may no&yogh;t write to
&yogh;ow a&llbar; &thorn;e order of &yogh;our lyffyng. Bot als
meki&llbar; &thorn;are-offe als I may vnderstande at this tyme, I
sa&llbar; writte vn-to &yogh;ow.  &YOGH;ee say &yogh;e vse no&yogh;te
for to ti&llbar; &thorn;e erthe, ne sawe na corne, ne plante na vynes,
ne sett na trees, na to make na faire howse&yogh;.  And &thorn;e cause
here-of as it wele semes es for &yogh;e hafe na Ire&ntail;, whare-of
&yogh;e myghte make &yogh;ow tuyles for to wirke with-a&llbar;e.  And
&thorn;are-fore &yogh;ow by-houes nedes ett herbes & lede an harde
lyfe, ry&yogh;te as beste&yogh;.  For &yogh;e may now&thorn;er gette
brede ne flesche ne fysche.  Does no&yogh;t wolfes o&ntail; &thorn;e
same wyse, &thorn;e whilke, whe&ntail; &thorn;ay may no&yogh;te gete
&thorn;aire fi&llbar; of flesche, &thorn;ay fi&llbar; &thorn;aire
belys of &thorn;e erthe ?  And it ware lefu&llbar; or lykande to
&yogh;ow to come ti&llbar; oure cuntree, we sulde lere na wisdo&mtail;
of &yogh;oure nede.  And &thorn;are-fore late &yogh;our hunger habyde
at hame in &yogh;our awen&ntail; cuntree.  &THORN;at ma&ntail; es
no&yogh;te mekills at commen&dtail; &thorn;at alwayes lyffes in
disesse.  Bot he es gretly to commen&dtail;, &thorn;at in reches
lyffe&yogh; attemperally.  Bot and me&ntail; schulde be
commendi&dtail; &thorn;at are oppresse&dtail; wit disesse,
&thorn;a&ntail; sulde blynd me&ntail;, leprouse me&ntail;, &
o&thorn;er swilke ouer a&llbar; o&thorn;er be commendi&dtail;; &thorn;e
blynde, for he sees no&yogh;t at desyre; &thorn;e pouer, for he hase
no&yogh;te at do.  And we walde make oure duellynge in &yogh;our
cuntree we sulde suffere
<PB N="86">
pouert & wrechidnes ri&yogh;te as &yogh;e do.  &YOGH;e say also
&thorn;at &yogh;our wyfes vse&yogh; na prowde aray for to plese
&thorn;aire husbande&yogh;, and &thorn;e cause es for &thorn;ay hafe
na no&thorn;er<MILESTONE N="36" UNIT="leaf"> thyng for ti&llbar; araye &thorn;a&mtail; wit. Also
&yogh;e say &yogh;e do nane advowtries ne fornycacions.  And &thorn;at
es na meruaile!  For-whi, how sulde &thorn;ay hafe luste to lechery
&thorn;at etes no&yogh;te.  Luste of lechery es no&yogh;te comonly,
bot yf it come of hete of &thorn;e leuer or e&llbar;s of habudance of
mete & drynke.  Bot &yogh;e ete na-thynge hot herbes & rote&yogh;, as
&yogh;e ware swyne, & drynkes water & vnnethes may &yogh;e
sloke&ntail; &yogh;our hunger and &thorn;arefore &yogh;e hafe
na&ntail; appitite to wome&ntail;.
</P>
<P>'&YOGH;e hafe na liste to studie aboute lerynge, ne &yogh;e seke na
mercy ne dees nane ti&llbar; o&thorn;er.  And a&llbar; this &yogh;e
hafe in como&ntail; wit beste&yogh;. For ri&yogh;te as beste&yogh;
hase now&thorn;er reso&ntail; ne discrecio&ntail;, ne hase na felynge
of gude, ri&yogh;te so &thorn;ay hafe na delite in gode.  Bot
ti&llbar; vs resonable me&ntail; &thorn;at has free wi&llbar; of kynde
ere many lykynges & blandeschynge&yogh; grante&dtail;.  For it es
im-possible &thorn;at &thorn;is werlde wyde & brade sulde no&yogh;te
hafe su&mtail; chaungynge of gouernance; So &thorn;at ne after
heuyness & sorowe, Ioy & myrthe sulde no&yogh;te folowe. For-why manes
wi&llbar; es variable & chaungeable &thorn;at chaunge&yogh; wit
&thorn;e heue&ntail; abown&ntail;.  On &thorn;e same wyse manes hert
es dyuerse.  For whe&ntail; &thorn;e day es clere, manes hert es
gladde & blythe.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e day es derke, manes wittis
are derke & du&llbar;e & heuy. Also me&ntail; chaunge&yogh;
thurg&hbar; dyuerse ages.  For barnehe&dtail; reioyse it in
sympilnesse, &yogh;outhede in presumptuosnes, And grete elde in
stabilnes.  For wha wi&llbar; luke efter wysdome in a childe, In a
&yogh;unge ma&ntail; stabi&llbar;nes, or in an alde ma&ntail; wildenes
?  Many delitable thynges come&yogh; ti&llbar; oure mynde.  For
su&mtail; we See wit oure eghne; Su&mtail; we hafe thurgh herynge;
Su&mtail; we fele thurg&hbar; smellyng; Su&mtail; thurg&hbar;
tastynge; and Su&mtail; thurgh towchynge.  Sumtyme we hafe delite in
salutacions & swete sange&yogh; & melodys of dyuerse
Instrumente&yogh;.  Of &thorn;e erthe we hafe al maner of gud
fruyte&yogh;; of &thorn;e see we hafe habundance of fysche, and of
&thorn;e ayere delyte of fewles of dyuerse kyndis.  If &thorn;ou
abstene &thorn;e fra a&llbar; thies owthir it es for pride or for
envy.  For pride, &thorn;at &thorn;ou dispyse&yogh; swilke precyouse
gifte&yogh;. For envy bi-cause &thorn;ay ere no&yogh;te gyffe&ntail;
&yogh;ow, as &thorn;at &thorn;ay ere to vs.  Bot efter my&ntail;
opynyo&ntail; I deme &thorn;at
<PB N="87">
&yogh;our lyffyng and &yogh;our maners commes mare of foundnesse
&thorn;a&ntail; of wysdo&mtail;.  For se&ntail; &yogh;e are me&ntail;
&yogh;e schulde hafe &thorn;e vertu&yogh; of a resonable creature, and
&thorn;at hafe &yogh;e no&yogh;hte.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>When
Dindimus had&dtail; red&dtail; &thorn;is lettre, onane he wrate
ano&thorn;er to kyng Alexander of &thorn;is tenour.  <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P>'Dyndimus, &thorn;e mayster of &thorn;e Bragmayns, vn-ti&llbar;
Alexander, gretyng.  We hafe vndirstand &thorn;e tenour of &thorn;i
lettres & &thorn;us we ansuere. We er no&yogh;te<MILESTONE
N="36 bk." UNIT="leaf"> lorde&yogh; of this werlde, as we sulde euermare lyffe &thorn;are in.  But we ere
pilgrymes in &thorn;is werlde, and whe&ntail; dede comme&yogh; we
wende ti&llbar; o&thorn;er habytacions.  Oure Synne&yogh; greue&yogh;
vs no&yogh;te, ne we duelle no&yogh;te in &thorn;e tabernacles of
synners.  We do na thyfte.  And for &thorn;e conscyence &thorn;at we
haue, we gaa no&yogh;te furthe in ope&ntail;.  We say no&yogh;te
&thorn;at we ere goddes, ne nane envy hase vn-to &thorn;a&mtail;.
God&dtail; &thorn;at made a&llbar; &thorn;at es in &thorn;is werlde,
he ordeyne&dtail; many diuerse thynge&yogh;.  For warne dyuersitees
ware of thynge&yogh; &thorn;e werld my&yogh;te noghte stande.
God&dtail; gaffe ma&ntail; fre wi&llbar;, for to discerne of a&llbar;
thynge&yogh; &thorn;at ere in &thorn;e werl&dtail;, and chese whilke
hym lyste.  Whare-fore he &thorn;at leues &thorn;e i&llbar; &
chese&yogh; &thorn;e gude, no&yogh;te god&dtail;, but goddes frende he
may be calle&dtail;.  Be-cause &thorn;at we lyffe contenently, and in
quiete & reste, &yogh;e say &thorn;at we ere godde&yogh;, or elles
&thorn;at we hafe envy to godde&yogh;.  But this suspeccio&ntail;
&thorn;at &yogh;e hafe of vs, pertene&yogh; to &yogh;ow.  For &yogh;e
&thorn;at ere blawe&ntail; fu&llbar; of &thorn;e wynde of pride
&yogh;e aray &yogh;our bodys wit gloryous clethyng, and on &yogh;our
fyngers, &yogh;e putt iowe&llbar;s of golde & precyous stanes.
</P>
<P>'Bot I pray &yogh;ow, what profit does &thorn;is &yogh;ow: Golde
and siluer saues no&yogh;te a manes saule, ne sustene&yogh; no&yogh;te
mens bodys.  Bot we &thorn;at knawes &thorn;e verray profitt of golde,
and &thorn;e kyn&dtail; &thorn;areoffe, when vs thriste&yogh;, & gase
to &thorn;e ryuere for to take vs a drynke, if we fynde golde in
&thorn;e way, we trede apo&ntail; it wit oure fete.  For golde
no&thorn;er fille&yogh; vs whe&ntail; we hunger, ne slokens oure
thriste, ne it hele&yogh; no&yogh;te a ma&ntail; &thorn;at es seke.
If a ma&ntail; thriste & drynke water, it putte&yogh; away his
thriste.  Also if a ma&ntail; hunger & ete mete, it does away his
hunger.  Bot and golde ware of &thorn;e same kynde, als so&ntail; als
a ma&ntail; had&dtail; it, &thorn;e vice of Couetyse suld be slokynde
in hym.  Be &thorn;is cause es golde i&llbar;.
 
<PB N="88">
For ay &thorn;e mare &thorn;at a ma&ntail; hase &thorn;are-offe,
&thorn;e mare he couetes.  Wikkede me&ntail; are wyrchippede
amange&yogh; &yogh;ow.  For comonly a ma&ntail; luffes hym &thorn;at
es lyke ti&llbar; hym selfe&ntail;.  &YOGH;e say &thorn;at god&dtail;
takes nane hede ti&llbar; dedly thynges. And neuer-&thorn;e-lesse
&yogh;e bygge temples, and makes autres in &thorn;a&mtail;, and settis
vp mawmettes abown&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail;, and grete delyte hase
whe&ntail; bestes ere offerde, & in &thorn;am, and at &yogh;our name
es noysede, &thorn;is was done to &thorn;i fader, to thy&ntail;
Eldfader, & ti&llbar; a&llbar; thi progenytours.  And &thorn;e same
also es highte on-to &thorn;e.  Wit swilke wirchipes &thorn;ay ere
rewarde&dtail;, &thorn;at knawes no&yogh;te &thorn;a&mtail; selfe
dedly.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>When Alexander had&dtail; red&dtail;
&thorn;is lettre onane he sente ano&thorn;er agayne and that was of
this tenour &thorn;e whilk &thorn;at folowes.  <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P><MILESTONE N="37" UNIT="leaf">' Alexander, &thorn;e so&ntail; of god&dtail; Amo&ntail; & of
&thorn;e quene Olympias, kyng of kynge&yogh; & lorde of lorde&yogh;,
vn-to Dyndymus kynge of &thorn;e Bragmayns we sende.  For als
meki&llbar; als &yogh;our duellynge es in &thorn;at partye of &thorn;e
werlde fra &thorn;e begynynge, whare na strangers may co&mtail; to
&yogh;ow, bot if it be ri&yogh;te fewe, ne &yogh;e may no&yogh;te
passe forthe of &yogh;our cuntree, but als swa say &yogh;e, are
parre&dtail; in, and na ferrere may passe; &thorn;arefore &yogh;e
magnyfye &yogh;our manere of lyffynge and suppose&yogh; &thorn;at
&yogh;e are blysse&dtail; be-cause &thorn;at &yogh;e er so
spere&dtail; in, &thorn;at if &yogh;e walde neuer so gladly passe
furthe for to lere &thorn;e customes &thorn;at o&thorn;er me&ntail;
vse&yogh;, &yogh;e may no&yogh;te; and ny&llbar;-&yogh;e
wi&llbar;-&yogh;e, &yogh;ow by-houe&yogh; nedis suffere &thorn;at
caytefftee &thorn;at &yogh;e lyffe in. Whare-fore it seme&yogh; bi
&yogh;our techynge, that &thorn;ay &thorn;at ligge&yogh; in
preson&ntail;, are als meki&llbar; at comen&dtail; als &yogh;e,
&thorn;e whilke vn-to &thorn;aire lyues ende suffres sorowe and
nede. And as me thynke, &thorn;e gudnesse &thorn;at &yogh;e ruse
&yogh;ow offe, may wele be lykkene&dtail; to &thorn;e paynes of
&thorn;aim &thorn;at ere in preson&ntail;. And so &thorn;at that oure
lawe demes to be done t[i]ll wikke&dtail; me&ntail;, &yogh;e suffere
kyndely.  And &thorn;are-fore hym &thorn;at we halde wyse, &yogh;e
halde an Ebbere fule .  Sothely me thynk &yogh;our lyffynge es
no&yogh;te blysse&dtail; bot wrechi&dtail; and as it ware a chastying
to &yogh;owe.  I swere &yogh;ow by oure godde&yogh; of myghte,
&thorn;at, & I myghte come to &yogh;ow with an oste, I sulde gare
&yogh;ow leue &yogh;our wrechi&dtail; lyfe, and by-come me&ntail; of
armes, als many of &yogh;ow als ware able.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>

When Alexander ha&dtail; sent this lettre ti&llbar; Dyndimus he gart
<PB N="89">
rayse vp a pelare of Marble a wonder grete, & an heghe, and gart writt
&thorn;are-apon this title wit lettres of grewe, of latyne, and of
&thorn;e langage of Inde.  'I Alexander, Philip&ptail; son of
Macedoyne, after &thorn;e discomfytour & &thorn;e ded&dtail; of Darius
& Porus come on werre vn-to this place.'</P> <P>Fra &thorn;eine kyng Alexander & his Oste remowe&dtail; & come in-ti&llbar; a felde,
&thorn;at was calle&dtail; Actea & &thorn;are &thorn;ay luge&dtail;.
Abowte &thorn;at felde was a thikke wod&dtail; of treesse beran&dtail;
fruyte; of &thorn;e whilke wilde me&ntail; &thorn;at duelt in &thorn;e
Same wod&dtail; vsede for ti&llbar; hafe &thorn;aire fude, whase
bodyes ware grete as geaunte&yogh;, and &thorn;aire clethynge ware
made of skynnes of dyuerse beste&yogh;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ay saw
Alexander Oste luge &thorn;are, onane &thorn;are come oute of &thorn;e
wod&dtail;, a grete multitude of &thorn;a&mtail; wit lange roddes in
&thorn;aire hand&yogh; & bi-ga&ntail; for to feghte wit &thorn;e
oste. And &thorn;an Alexander commande&dtail; &thorn;at a&llbar;
[&thorn;e] oste schulde sette vp a schowte at anes.  And also sone als
&thorn;e wylde me&ntail; herde &thorn;at<MILESTONE N="37 bk." UNIT="leaf"> noyse, &thorn;ay were wondere fere&dtail; be-cause &thorn;ay had neuer be-fore herde swilke a noyse. And tha&ntail; &thorn;ay be-ga&ntail; to flee hedir & thedir in
&thorn;e wod&dtail;. And Alexander & his me&ntail; persue&dtail;
&thorn;a&mtail; and slewe of &thorn;a&mtail; vi<HI>c</HI> xxx iiij.
And &thorn;ay slew of Alexander knyghtes xxvij.  In &thorn;at felde
Alexander & his oste leuge&dtail; iij dayes and vetaile&dtail;
&thorn;am of &thorn;at fruyte &thorn;at growe&dtail; in &thorn;e
wod&dtail;.
</P>
<P>Fra &thorn;eine pay remowe&dtail; and come ti&llbar; a grete ryuer,
& luge&dtail; &thorn;am &thorn;are.  And as it ware abowte none,
&thorn;are come apo&ntail; &thorn;am a wilde ma&ntail;, als
meki&llbar; als a geaunte.  And he was rughe of hare a&llbar; ouer,
and his hede was lyke ti&llbar; a swyne, An&dtail; his voyce also.
And whe&ntail; Alexander saw hym, he bad his knyghtis tak hy&mtail; &
bryng hym bi-for hy&mtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ay come abowte hym,
he was na thynge fered, ne fled&dtail; no&yogh;te, bot stod&dtail;
baldly bi-fore &thorn;a&mtail;.  And when Alexander saw that, he
comande&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;ay sulde take a &yogh;onge
damese&llbar; & nakke&ntail; hir & sett hir bi-fore hym.  And
&thorn;ay di&dtail; soo.  And onane, he ranne apo&ntail; &hbar;ir
romyand&dtail; as he had&dtail; bene wod&dtail;. Bot &thorn;e knyghtes
wit grete deficcultee refte hyr fra hym.  And ay he romye&dtail; &
made grete mane.  And efte &thorn;ay broghte hym ti&llbar; Alexander
and sett hym bi-fore hym.  And Alexander wonder&dtail; gretly of his
figure.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he

<PB N="90">
gerte byn&dtail; hym ti&llbar; a tree & make a fyre abowte hym &
brynne hym.  And so &thorn;ay did&dtail;.  Fra &thorn;eine &thorn;ay
remowe&dtail; & come ti&llbar; ano&thorn;er felde in &thorn;e whilke
&thorn;are ware growan&dtail; treesse, of a wonderfu&llbar; heghte,
and &thorn;ay biga&ntail; for to sprynge vp at &thorn;e so&ntail;
rysynge; An&dtail; bi &thorn;e so&ntail; settynge &thorn;ay
wyte&dtail; a-way in-to &thorn;e erthe agayne.  At &thorn;e firste
houre of &thorn;e day &thorn;ay bi-ga&ntail; to sprynge oute of
&thorn;e erthe, & so &thorn;ay wex ay to myddaye, and &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;ay bi-ga&ntail; to decresse.  And by &thorn;e so&ntail;
settynge &thorn;ay ware in &thorn;e erthe agayne, And was na thyng of
&thorn;a&mtail; sene bi-fore o&ntail; &thorn;e morne. &THORN;ir
treesse bare a fruyte wonder swete of reflayre bot &thorn;ay [ware]
bitter of taste.  When Alexander saw &thorn;at fruyte he bade a
knyghte bryng hym &thorn;areoffe.  And he went & tuk &thorn;are-offe,
and onane a wikke&dtail; spirit smate hym, and be-lyfe he was
dede. And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ay her&dtail; a voyce in &thorn;e
ayer &thorn;at sai&dtail; on &thorn;is wyse: 'What ma&ntail; so neghes
&thorn;ir treesse he sa&llbar; dye onane.'  &THORN;are was also in
&thorn;at felde fewles wonder meke & tame.  Bot what ma&ntail; so
layde nande on any of &thorn;am, onane &thorn;are come fire oute of
&thorn;a&mtail;, & brynt hym ri&yogh;te greuosly.
</P>
<P> <MILESTONE N="38" UNIT="leaf">Than &thorn;ay remowe&dtail; fra &thorn;eine, And come ti&llbar; a
Mountayne, &thorn;at was so hye, &thorn;at &thorn;ay ware viij dayes
in gangyng ar &thorn;ay my&yogh;te wyne to &thorn;e heghte
&thorn;are-offe.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ay come to &thorn;e heghte of
it, &thorn;are come agaynes &thorn;a&mtail; a grete multitude of
dragones, Serpentes, and lyones &thorn;e whilke turmenti&dtail;
Alexander & his me&ntail; reghte gretely.  And at &thorn;e laste,
&thorn;ay askape&dtail; &thorn;aire daungere, and went doune of
&thorn;e mountayne and come in-ti&llbar; a vaylay &thorn;at was so
myrke &thorn;at vnnethes myghte ane of &thorn;a&mtail; See
ano&thorn;er.  In &thorn;at depe valay ware treesse growan&dtail; of
whilke &thorn;e fruyte & &thorn;e lefes ware wonder sauory in &thorn;e
tastynge, and reue&llbar;s of water faire & clere.  Aghte dayes
contenuelly &thorn;ay saw na so&ntail;.  And at &thorn;e viij days
en&dtail; &thorn;ay come to &thorn;e fote of a mountayne whare
a&llbar; &thorn;e Oste thurg&hbar; a wikked thikk ayer ware so gretley
disesse&dtail; &thorn;at &thorn;ay ware in poynte to hafe bene
choke&dtail; &thorn;are-offe.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ay come
a-bow&ntail; on &thorn;e mountayne, &thorn;ay fande &thorn;e ayer mare
sote&llbar;, and &thorn;e lighte of &thorn;e day mare clere.  And
&thorn;us &thorn;ay ware wendan&dtail; vpwarde, o&ntail; &thorn;is
Mountayne Elleue&ntail;, xj, days wit grete trauaile. And whe&ntail;
&thorn;ay come to &thorn;e
<PB N="91">
hegheste of &thorn;is Mountayne, &thorn;ay saw on &thorn;e to&thorn;er
syde faire weder & bryghte.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ay went
dow&ntail; of &thorn;is Mountayne, and come in ti&llbar; a grete
playne of whilke &thorn;e erthe was wonder rede.  And in &thorn;is
playne &thorn;are ware growande treesse wit-owtte&ntail; nowmer; and
&thorn;ay passed no&yogh;te a cubit in heghte, & &thorn;aire fruyte &
&thorn;aire lefes ware passandly swete as &thorn;ay had bene
fyges. And &thorn;ay fande &thorn;are reue&llbar;s ri&yogh;te many, of
clere water as crista&llbar;e.  And it was als nureschan&dtail; to
manes body, as it had&dtail; bene mylke wit-oute&ntail; eny o&thorn;er
mete.  Thurgh &thorn;at ilk playne &thorn;ay went fourty .xl. days and
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ay com ti&llbar; wonder heghe Mountaynes; and it
semed as &thorn;e toppes had towched &thorn;e firmament.  And
&thorn;ir Mountaynes ware als brant vp-ri&yogh;te as &thorn;ay had
bene walles. So &thorn;at &thorn;are was na clymbyng vpo&ntail;
&thorn;am.  And at &thorn;e laste &thorn;ay fande twa passage&yogh;
be-twix &thorn;ase Mountaynes, of whilke, &thorn;e tane streche&dtail;
to-warde &thorn;e west, and &thorn;e to&thorn;er towarde &thorn;e
Este. Than Alexander deme&dtail; &thorn;at that dyuyso&ntail; be-twix
&thorn;ase Mountaynes was made thurg&hbar; Noye flode.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ay went by &thorn;at passage &thorn;at streched
to warde &thorn;e Este Seue&ntail; days.  And o&ntail; &thorn;e
heghte&ntail; .viij. day &thorn;ay fande a Basilisc &thorn;at
me&ntail; calle&yogh; a Cocatrys, a grete & ane horrible.  And bicause
of his grete elde he was fou&llbar; stynkan&dtail;.<MILESTONE
N="38 bk." UNIT="leaf">  &THORN;is ilke Basilisc was so venymous, &thorn;at no&yogh;te a&llbar; anely
thurg&hbar; his stynke, bot also thurg&hbar; his sighte allane,
whay&mtail; so he luke&dtail; o&ntail;, he sulde dy onane; &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e Macedoynes and &thorn;e persyenes, as &thorn;ay passede thurg&hbar; &thorn;e strayt way dye&dtail; thikk-falde thurgh &thorn;e sighte of &thorn;at Basilisc. And
whe&ntail; Alexander knyghtis saw that peri&llbar;, &thorn;ay durste
passe na forther bot sai&dtail; amange&yogh; &thorn;a&mtail;:
'&THORN;e vertue of oure goddes,' quoth &thorn;ay, 'es bifore vs,
&thorn;at schewes vs &thorn;at we schulde ga na forthir.'  Bot
Alexander went bi hym ane vppo&ntail; an heghe cragge, where he myghte
see on ferrome fra hym.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he saw this pestellencius
beste &thorn;e Basilisc lygg slepande in myddes of &thorn;e passage.
&THORN;e kynde of hym was &thorn;at, als so sone als he feli&dtail; a
ma&ntail; or a beste co&mtail; nere hym, for to ope&ntail; his eghne &
stare appo&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail;, and als many als he luked o&ntail;,
solde sudaynly fa&llbar;e dou&ntail; & dye.  When Alexander had sen
hym, Be lyfe he went dounne of &thorn;e cragge, and gart sett a merke
&thorn;at na ma&ntail; sulde passe.  And
 
<PB N="92">
&thorn;a&ntail; he gart a pavysse be made seue&ntail; cubites of
lenghte & foure o&ntail; brede; and o&ntail; &thorn;e vtter syde
&thorn;are-offe he gart sett a grete Mirroure, And a large.  And at
&thorn;e nethir ende of &thorn;e pavisse he gart nayle a burde
&thorn;e lenthe of a cubit for to couere wit his legges, and his fete,
so &thorn;at na party of hym my&yogh;te be sene.  And &thorn;an
Alexander tuk &thorn;is pavisse in his handis, and went towarde this
Basilisc, and warned his me&ntail; &thorn;at na&ntail; of
&thorn;a&mtail; sulde passe his termes.  And whe&ntail; he come nere
&thorn;e basillsc, &thorn;e basilisc opynde his eghne.  And wit a
grete ire he bi-belde &thorn;e Mirroure and saw hym-selfe
&thorn;are-in.  And of &thorn;e refleccio&ntail; of &thorn;e bemes of
his sighte strykande appo&ntail; hym-selfe Sudanly he was dede.  And
whe&ntail; Alexander knewe wele &thorn;at he was dede, he calle&dtail;
ti&llbar; his knyghtis; And bad &thorn;a&mtail; come see hy&mtail;
&thorn;at slewe &thorn;aire felawes.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ay come
ti&llbar; hy&mtail;, &thorn;ay saw &thorn;e Basilisc dede.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ay comende&dtail; & praysse&dtail; gretly his
hardynesse and his hye witt, And went & brynede &thorn;e Basilisc at
&thorn;e commandement of Alexander.
</P>
<P>Fra &thorn;eine &thorn;ay went ti&llbar; &thorn;ey come to &thorn;e
ferreste of &thorn;at waye ; and ferrere my&yogh;te &thorn;ay
no&yogh;te wyn&ntail;.  For &thorn;are ware so hye Mountaynes agaynes
&thorn;a&mtail; and cragges like walles &thorn;at &thorn;ay my&yogh;te
passe no for&thorn;er.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ay turne&dtail;
agayne, and come to &thorn;e forsaide playne; and went by &thorn;at
way &thorn;at streche&dtail; to-warde &thorn;e weste fyvftene
.xv. days.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ay lefte &thorn;at way, And
turnede o&ntail; &thorn;e lefte hande.  And so &thorn;ay went foure
score iiij <NOTE ID="n4">In printed text, "xx" inserted superscript above "iiij"</NOTE> days, and at &thorn;e laste &thorn;ay come ti&llbar; a
Mountayne of adamande; and at &thorn;e fute &thorn;are-offe &thorn;are
hange chynes of golde.  &THORN;is Mountayne had&dtail; made<MILESTONE
N="39" UNIT="leaf"> of saphyres twa thowsande gree&yogh; & a halfe, by &thorn;e whilke
me&ntail; ascendi&dtail; to &thorn;e summit of &thorn;e Mountayne.
And &thorn;are Alexander & his Oste luged &thorn;a&mtail;.
</P>
<P>And on &thorn;e morne Alexander Offer&dtail; sacrafice ti&llbar;
his goddes, And &thorn;a&ntail; he tuk with hym xij twelue
prynce&yogh; of &thorn;e wyrchip-fulleste &thorn;at he hade, and went
vp bi &thorn;e forsai&dtail; gree&yogh; till he come abou&ntail;
o&ntail; &thorn;e Mountayne.  And &thorn;are he fande a palace wonder
faire and curiously wroghte; and it hade twelve &yogh;ates and thre
score & te&ntail; wyndows.  And &thorn;e lynta&llbar;s bathe of
&thorn;e durs and of &thorn;e wyndows ware of fy&ntail; golde, wele
burnescht, and &thorn;at Palace was calle&dtail; &thorn;e howse of
&thorn;e so&ntail;.  &THORN;are was also
<PB N="93">
a temple a&llbar; of golde & of precious stanes, And bi-fore &thorn;e
dores &thorn;are-offe &thorn;are was a vyne of golde, berande grapes
of charbuncles, of Rubyes, Dyamande&yogh;, and many o&thorn;er maneres
of precyous stanes.  &THORN;a&ntail; kyng Alexander & his prince&yogh;
went in-to &thorn;e palace; and fande &thorn;are a ma&ntail;
liggan&dtail; in a bed&dtail; of golde, and couer&dtail; wit a riche
clathe of golde.  And he was ri&yogh;te a meki&llbar; ma&ntail; and a
faire, And his berde & his heue&dtail; ware als whitt als any
wo&llbar;e; and hym seme&dtail; lyke a Bischoppe.  Als so&ntail; als
Alexander & his prynce&yogh; saw &thorn;is alde ma&ntail; &thorn;ay
kneli&dtail; dounne on &thorn;aire kneesse and saluste hy&mtail;.  And
he ansuer&dtail; & saide: 'Welco&mtail; Alexander,' quo&thorn; he, 'I
te&llbar;e the &thorn;ou sa&llbar; see, &thorn;at neuer flescly
ma&ntail; bi-fore this tyme sawe; And &thorn;ou sa&llbar; here
&thorn;at neuer erthly ma&ntail; herde are.' And Alexander
ansuer&dtail; & say&dtail;: Maste blysse&dtail; alde ma&ntail;,' quoth
he, 'how hase &thorn;ou knawyng of me ?'  'For sothe,' quoth he,
'bi-fore Noy flode couerde a&llbar; &thorn;e erthe, knewe I bathe the,
& thi dedis.  I wate wele &thorn;ou desyres for to See &thorn;e haly
tree&yogh; of &thorn;e So&ntail; And &thorn;e Mone &thorn;e whilke
telle&yogh; thynge&yogh; &thorn;at ere to come.'  '&YOGH;aa for
sothe,' quo&thorn; Alexander, '&thorn;er es na-thynge &thorn;at I
desyre mare, &thorn;a&ntail; for to see &thorn;a&mtail;.'  And he was
ri&yogh;t glad&dtail;.  &THORN;a&ntail; saide &thorn;e alde ma&ntail;
ti&llbar; hym: 'And &yogh;e be clene of flescly dede wit wome&ntail;,
&thorn;a&ntail; es it leefu&llbar; to &yogh;ow to see &thorn;a&mtail;
and to entir in-to &thorn;at haly place &thorn;at es a sette of
god&dtail;.  And if &yogh;e be no&yogh;te clene, it es no&yogh;te
leefu&llbar; to &yogh;ow.'  '&YOGH;is, sir, sothely,' quo&thorn;
Alexander, 'we ere clene.'  &THORN;a&ntail; raise &thorn;e alde
ma&ntail; vp of &thorn;e bed&dtail; &thorn;at he lay in, and
sai&dtail; vn-to &thorn;a&mtail;: 'Putte&yogh; offe &yogh;our
rynge&yogh;,' quo&thorn; he, 'and &yogh;oure clathes, & &yogh;our
schone, and folowes me.'  And &thorn;ay dy&dtail; so.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; Alexander tuk wit hym tholomeus and Antiochus, &
folowe&dtail; &thorn;e alde ma&ntail;, and went thurg&hbar; &thorn;e
wod&dtail; &thorn;at was abou&ntail; o&ntail; &thorn;e Mountayne
close&dtail; with mannes hande&yogh;.  &THORN;e<MILESTONE N="39 bk." UNIT="leaf"> treesse of &thorn;at wod&dtail; ware an hundreth .c. fote lange & hye, and &thorn;ay ware
lyke lorers or Olyue treesse; And out of &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;are
ra&ntail; rykyles & fynne bawme.  And as &thorn;ay went thurg&hbar;
&thorn;at wod&dtail; &thorn;ay saw a tree wondere hye, in &thorn;e
whilke &thorn;are satt a meki&llbar; fewle.  &THORN;at tree had&dtail;
no&thorn;er &thorn;are-o&ntail; lefes ne fruyte.  &THORN;e fewle
&thorn;at satt &thorn;are-o&ntail; had&dtail; o&ntail; his hedd a
creste lyk ti&llbar; a pacokke, & his beeke also creste&dtail;.
Abowte his nekke, he had&dtail; fethirs lyke golde. &THORN;e hynder of
hym was lyk purpure;
<PB N="94">
and &thorn;e tayle was ownnde&dtail; ouerthwert, wit a colour reede as
rose & wit blewe.  And his fethers ware ri&yogh;te faire
schynan&dtail;.  Whe&ntail; Alexander saw &thorn;is fewle he was
gretely meruaille&dtail; of &thorn;e faire&dtail; of hym;
&thorn;a&ntail; saide &thorn;e Alde ma&ntail;: 'Alexander,' quo&thorn;
he, '&thorn;is ilke fewle &thorn;at &thorn;ou here seese es a fenix.'  And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ay went for&thorn;er thurg&hbar; &thorn;e
forsai&dtail; wod&dtail;, And come to thiese haly tree&yogh; of
&thorn;e so&ntail; & &thorn;e mone &thorn;at growe&dtail; in
mydde&yogh; of &thorn;e wodde.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e alde
ma&ntail; saide ti&llbar; Alexander: 'Luke vp,' quo&thorn; he, 'to
&yogh;one haly tree&yogh;, and thynke in thi hert what preuatee so
&thorn;e liste, and &thorn;ou sa&llbar; hafe a trewe ansuere.  Bot
luke &thorn;at &thorn;ou speke na worde in opy&ntail;.  And
&thorn;are-by sa&llbar; &thorn;ou witt &thorn;at it es a gude spiritt,
&thorn;at knawes thi thoghte.'  Thir twa tree&yogh; were wonder hye.
And &thorn;e tree of &thorn;e So&ntail; ha&dtail; leues lyk fyne
golde, reed & faire schynande.  And &thorn;e tree of &thorn;e mone had
lefes whitt als syluer & faire schynande.  And &thorn;a&ntail; walde
Alexander hafe Offrede Sacrafyce to &thorn;ir tree&yogh;.  Bot
&thorn;e alde ma&ntail; walde no&yogh;te suffre hy&mtail;, bot
sai&dtail;: 'It es no&yogh;te leuefu&llbar;,' quo&thorn; he, 'in &thorn;is
haly place, now&thorn;er to offre encense, ne to slaa na beste&yogh;,
Bot to knele dou&ntail; to &thorn;e boles of &thorn;ir tree&yogh; &
kysse &thorn;a&mtail; & pray &thorn;e so&ntail; & &thorn;e mone to
giffe trew ansuers.'  And &thorn;an Alexander spirre&dtail; &thorn;e
alde ma&ntail;, in what langage &thorn;e tree&yogh; sulde giffe
&thorn;aire answers.  And &thorn;e alde ma&ntail; ansuer&dtail; &
sai&dtail;: 'The tree of &thorn;e Son,' quo&thorn; he, 'answers
ow&thorn;er a&llbar; in &thorn;e langage of Inde or e&llbar;s of
grewe.  And &thorn;e tree of &thorn;e Mone begynne&yogh; wit &thorn;e
langage of grewe & ende&yogh; wit &thorn;e langage of Inde.'
</P>
<P>And as &thorn;ay stode &thorn;us spekande, Sudaynly &thorn;are come
a bryghte beme fra &thorn;e weste &thorn;at schane ouer a&llbar;
&thorn;e wodde.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Alexander knele&dtail;
dou&ntail;, and kyssede &thorn;e tree&yogh; an thoght &thorn;us in his
hert: 'Sa&llbar; I conquere a&llbar; &thorn;e werlde, and
efterwarde&yogh; wit &thorn;e victorye wende hame to Macedoyne
ti&llbar; my moder Olympias, and my sisters?  And<MILESTONE N="40" UNIT="leaf"> &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e tree of &thorn;e so&ntail; ansuer&dtail; softly in &thorn;e
langage of Inde, And said &thorn;ir verse&yogh;: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT"><Q
TYPE="verse"><L>'Tu dominatorum orbis dominus simul et pater extas,</L><L>Set patrum rignum per tempora nulla videbis;'</L></Q>
</FOREIGN>&thorn;at es at say, '&thorn;ou ert bathe lorde & fader of a&llbar;e
&thorn;e werlde, Bot &thorn;e Rewme of thy Fadyrs sa&llbar; &thorn;ou
neuer see wit thy&ntail; eghne.'  &THORN;a&ntail; byga&ntail;
Alexander to thynke how lange he sulde lyffe,
<PB N="95">
and whate ded&dtail; he sulde dye.  And &thorn;e tree of &thorn;e Mone
ansuer&dtail; by &thorn;ir twa verse&yogh;: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT"><Q TYPE="verse"><L>'Anno
completo viues & mensibus octo,</L><L>De quo confidis tibi mortis
pocula dabit.'</L></Q></FOREIGN> &THORN;at es at saye, 'A twluemonthe & aughte
monethes sa&llbar; &thorn;ou lyffe.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he &thorn;at
&thorn;ou traiste&yogh; o&ntail;, sa&llbar; giffe &thorn;ee a drynke
of ded&dtail;.'  &THORN;a&ntail; bi-ga&ntail; Alexander to thynke in
his hert o&ntail; &thorn;is wyse, <Q TYPE="verse"><L>'Tell me now,
haly tree,</L><L>Wha he es &thorn;at sall slaa mee.'</L></Q> And
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e tree of &thorn;e so&ntail; ansuer&dtail; by
&thorn;ir twa verse&yogh;: <FOREIGN LANG="LAT"><Q TYPE="verse"><L>'Si tibi pandatur vir
qui tua facta resoluet,</L><L>Illum confrynges & sic mea carmina
fallent.'</L></Q></FOREIGN> &THORN;at es at say: 'And I schew the &thorn;e manes
name, &thorn;at sa&llbar; vndo thi dedis, &thorn;ou wi&llbar; slaa
hy&mtail;, and so sa&llbar; my prophycye fayle.'  And &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;e forsaide ald ma&ntail; say&dtail; ti&llbar; Alexander:
'Disese na mare &thorn;ir trees,' quo&thorn; he, 'wit thyne askynges.
Bot tourne we agayne, as we come hedir.'  And &thorn;a&ntail;
Alexander & his twa prynce&yogh; wit hym tourne&dtail; agayne wit
&thorn;e alde ma&ntail;.  And ay as he went, he wepe&dtail; bitterly,
bi-cause of his schorte tyme; and his prynce&yogh; also weped
ri&yogh;te sare.  Bot he commande&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at
&thorn;ay schulde no&yogh;te te&llbar;e to na ma&ntail; of his Oste
&thorn;at that &thorn;ay had&dtail; herde & sene.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;ay ware come&ntail; to &thorn;e forsaide Palace &thorn;e alde
[man] sai&dtail; vn-ti&llbar; Alexander: ' Torne bakke agayne,' quoth
he, 'for it es no&yogh;te leefu&llbar; to na ma&ntail; to passe
forthire.  If &thorn;e liste wende towar&dtail; &thorn;e weste,
&thorn;ou sa&llbar; no&yogh;te traue&llbar;e fu&llbar; lange are
&thorn;ou come to &thorn;e place, whare &thorn;e liste to bee.'  Aud
whe&ntail; &thorn;e alde ma&ntail; had sai&dtail; &thorn;ir
worde&yogh;, he went in-to &thorn;e palace and Alexander and his twa
prynce&yogh; went dou&ntail; by &thorn;e forsaide gree&yogh; & come to
&thorn;e Oste.
</P>
<P>Apon &thorn;e morne Alexander & his Oste remowe&dtail; &thorn;eine
& went agaynewar&dtail; fyftene days, And come agayne to &thorn;e
forsai&dtail; playne & &thorn;are &thorn;ay luged &thorn;a&mtail;.
And &thorn;are at &thorn;e entree of &thorn;a twa forsai&dtail; ways,
Alexander gart rayse vp twa pelers of Marble, and by-twixe
&thorn;a&mtail; he haude a table of golde, on &thorn;e whilke was
wretyn in &thorn;e langage of grewe, hebrew, of latyne, and of Inde,
one this wyse: 'I, Alexander, Phillip&ptail; so&ntail; of Macedoyne,
 
<PB N="96">
sett thir pelers here, after &thorn;e ded&dtail; of Darius kyng of
Perse and of Porus kynge of Inde.  What ma&ntail; so wi&llbar; passe
for&thorn;er late hy&mtail;<MILESTONE N="40 bk." UNIT="leaf"> tourne one &thorn;e lefte hand.  For wha so tourne&yogh; one &thorn;e ri&yogh;te hande he sa&llbar; fynde many obstacle&yogh; & greuance&yogh; &thorn;at sa&llbar; perauenture lett
his agayne-commynge.
</P>
<P>Fra &thorn;eine &thorn;ay remowe&dtail; thurg&hbar; &thorn;at
playne and lefte &thorn;ase strayte wayes, takan&dtail; &thorn;e way
westewar&dtail; &thorn;e gayneste towarde Macedoyne.  And at &thorn;e
laste &thorn;ay come ti&llbar; a cuntree &thorn;at highte Prasiac, And
&thorn;are &thorn;ay luge&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail;.  And whe&ntail;
me&ntail; of &thorn;at cuntree her&dtail; of &thorn;e commynge of
Alexander, wit grete wirchipe &thorn;ay broghte hym grete
presante&yogh; of swilk thynge&yogh; as &thorn;ay had&dtail; in
&thorn;aire lande, &thorn;at es at say, skynnes of fischez lyke vn-to
&thorn;e skynnes of pardes, or of lyouns also, and lawmpray skynnes of
sex cubites lange.  In &thorn;at cuntree was a noble citee a&llbar; of
precyous stanes made wit-owtte&ntail; &lbar;yme or sande, sett
apo&ntail; an hi&llbar;.  Of &thorn;e whilke citee, a wirchipfu&llbar;
lady and a faire had&dtail; &thorn;e lordechipe.  &THORN;is lady was
wedowe and scho had&dtail; three sones.  The firste of &thorn;a&mtail;
highte Candeolus, &thorn;e secan&dtail; Marcipius, And &thorn;e thirde
hight Carator.  To &thorn;is lady Alexander sent a lettre of &thorn;is
tenour:
</P>
<P>'Alexander &thorn;e so&ntail; of god&dtail; Amo&ntail; & of
&thorn;e quene Olympias, kyng of kynges & lorde of lordes vn-to quene
Candace of Mero&ntail; ioy & gretyng.  We sende &yogh;ow ane ymage of
god&dtail; Amo&ntail; a&llbar; of fyne golde; And &thorn;arefore
come&yogh; ti&llbar; vs &thorn;at we may wende togeder to &thorn;e
Mountayne for to make sacrafyce &thorn;are to god&dtail; Amon.'
Whe&ntail; &thorn;e Qwene Candace had&dtail; red&dtail; &thorn;is
lettre, Scho sent hir embassatours ti&llbar; kyng Alexander wit grete
presante&yogh; and with a lettre of this tenour: <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P>'Candace, quene of Mero&ntail;, vn-ti&llbar; Alexander, kyng of
kynge&yogh;, ioy.  Wele we knawe &thorn;at &yogh;e hafe by
reuelacio&ntail; of god&dtail; Amo&ntail; &thorn;at &yogh;e schulde
couquere Perse, Inde and Egipte, and subiecte vn-to &yogh;ow a&llbar;
o&thorn;er nacions.  And a&llbar; &thorn;at &yogh;e hafe done,
no&yogh;te allanly was graunte&dtail; bot also of a&llbar; o&thorn;er
godde&yogh;.  Ti&llbar; vs &thorn;at hase faire saules & bryghte it
nede&yogh; noghte to make sacrafyce to god&dtail; Amo&ntail; in
&thorn;e Mountaynes.  Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse bicause we wi&llbar;
no&yogh;te offende &yogh;owere maiestatee, we sende ti&llbar;
<PB N="97">
Amo&ntail; &yogh;oure god&dtail; a Coro&ntail; of golde and precyouse
stanes, And te&ntail; chynes of golde sett fu&llbar; of precious
stanes.  And vn-to &yogh;ow we sende a hundrethe Besaunte&yogh; of
golde; And twa hundreth papeiayes close&dtail; in cage&yogh;<MILESTONE
N="41" UNIT="leaf"> of golde,
c childer of Ethipes, cc apes, cccc Olyphantis, xxxiiii <NOTE
ID="n5">In printed text, "xx" inserted superscript above "xxxiiii," i.e., thirty-four score.</NOTE> vnycornes, iij <NOTE ID="n6">A tilde appears above "iij" in printed text, i.e., three hundred?</NOTE>panters skynne&yogh;, of parde&yogh; & lyounes cccc, and we beseke
&yogh;owre hye maieste &thorn;at &yogh;e wi&llbar; notyfye
vn-ti&llbar; vs bi &yogh;our wirchipfu&llbar; lettres, wheder &yogh;e
haue conquere&dtail; a&llbar;e &thorn;e werlde and made it subiecte
vn-to &yogh;ow or no&yogh;te.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>Amange&yogh; her
embassatours &thorn;at scho sent ti&llbar; Alexander &thorn;are was a
wonder crafty & a sute&llbar; payntoure.  And hym scho charge&dtail;
&thorn;et he schulde besely by-halde Alexander & purtray his fygure in
a parchemy&ntail; skyn&ntail; and brynge it to hir.  And so he
di&dtail;. Alexander ressayue&dtail; &thorn;e forsai&dtail; gyftes
reuerently and sent hir noble gyftes agayne wit hir embassatours.  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;ay come hame &thorn;e payntour tuke hir &thorn;e
fegure of Alexander purtraye&dtail; as I saide be-fore.  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;e quene saw it, Scho was ri&yogh;te gladde, for scho
desyre&dtail; gretly for to see his fygure.
</P>
<P>After &thorn;is ane of &thorn;e quene sonnes &thorn;at hight
Candeolus went furthe of &thorn;e Citee wit his wyfe and a fewe of his
men&yogh;ee for to take &thorn;e sporte.  And onane &thorn;e kyng of
&thorn;e Bebrikes, knawyng &thorn;e fairehe&dtail; of Candeolus wyfe,
come appo&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail; with a grete multitude of me&ntail;,
and slew many of Candeolus men&yogh;ee and refte hym his wyfe & went
his way.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Candeolus and his me&ntail; &thorn;at
ware lefte on lyfe went ti&llbar; Alexander Oste for to be-seke hym of
helpe agaynes &thorn;e kynge of Bebrikes.  And &thorn;e waches of
&thorn;e oste tuke Candeolus & broghte hym bi-fore Tholomeus,
&thorn;at was &thorn;e secun&dtail; perso&ntail; after Alexander.  And
Tholomeus spirre&dtail; hym what he was, & what he di&dtail;
&thorn;are.  'I am,' quo&thorn; he, 'quene Candace so&ntail; and
&thorn;is day als I went wit my wyfe & a preuee men&yogh;ee for to
take &thorn;e sporte, &thorn;e kynge of &thorn;e Bebrikes come
apo&ntail; vs wit a grete multitude of me&ntail; uand hase slayne many
of my men&yogh;ee & refte me my wyfe.  And &thorn;are-fore I am
come&ntail; heder for to beseke my lor&dtail;, &thorn;e Emrerour, of
helpe & socoure.'  When Tholomeus had her&dtail; &thorn;is onane he
garte take kepe of Candeolus & went ti&llbar; Alexander tentis and
wakkne&dtail; Alexander & talde hym & talde ilk a dele &thorn;at
Candeolus had talde hym.  And whe&ntail; Alexander had&dtail; herde
 
<PB N="98">
his tale he bad&dtail; hym gange agayne ti&llbar; his tent and do a
corou&ntail; o&ntail; his hede and putt apo&ntail; hy&mtail; &thorn;e
kynge&yogh; clothynge,<MILESTONE N="41 bk." UNIT="leaf"> and sett hym in the kynge&yogh; trone & say
Vn-to Candeolus &thorn;at he was kyng Alexander.  'And bid&dtail; an
of thi me&ntail;,' quo&thorn; he, 'feche vn-to &thorn;e Antyochus,
An&dtail; late hym bryng me to &thorn;e insteed&dtail; of Antyochus,
and whe&ntail; I come bi-for thee telle me bi-fore Candeolus a&llbar;
&thorn;at he talde the.  An&dtail; aske me conse&llbar;, als I ware
Antyochus, what es beste to do in &thorn;at mater.'  Tholomeus went
and did&dtail; a&llbar; als Alexander bad&dtail; hym.  An&dtail; he
asche&dtail; Alexander in sted&dtail; of Antyochus be-fore Candeolus
what was beste to do.  And Alexander ansuer&dtail; & sayde on
heran&dtail; Candeolus: 'Wirchipfu&llbar; Emperour,' quo&thorn; he,
'if it be plesynge to &yogh;our maiestee I wi&llbar; go wit Candeolus
&thorn;is same nyghte to &thorn;e kynge of &thorn;e Bebrikes, and
comande hym one &yogh;our byhalue &thorn;at he &yogh;elde Candeolus
his wyfe agayne.  And if he wi&llbar; no&yogh;te do soo, I sa&llbar;
late hym witt &thorn;at &yogh;e sa&llbar; sende a grete powere to his
Citee & bryne it vp stikke & stourre.'  When Candeolus had&dtail;
herde hym say &thorn;us, he knely&dtail; vn-ti&llbar; hym &
sai&dtail;: 'A a, wirchipfu&llbar; Antyochus,' quo&thorn; he, ' wele
walde it seme &thorn;e for to be a kyng for &thorn;e hye witt
an&dtail; &thorn;e manhede &thorn;at es in the.'  Tha&ntail; kyng
Alexander tuke wit hym a grete powere and went apo&ntail; &thorn;e
same nyghte wit Candeolus vn-to &thorn;e Citee, whare &thorn;e kyng of
&thorn;e Bebrikes lay.  An&dtail; wha&ntail; &thorn;ay come to
&thorn;e citee, &thorn;e waytes crye&dtail; apo&ntail;
&thorn;a&mtail;, and askede what &thorn;ay ware.  And Alexander
ansuer&dtail; & say&dtail;: 'Candeolus,' quo&thorn; he, 'es here wit
ane Oste of me&ntail;, and &thorn;e cause of his commynge es to be
restorede agayne of his wyfe &thorn;e whilke &yogh;our kynge raueste
away fro hy&mtail; &thorn;is same day.  And my lor&dtail; kyng
Alexander commande&yogh; &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e delyuer hir anone,
or sewrely we sa&llbar; brynne this citee & &yogh;our selfe are we
passe hethy&ntail;.' And whe&ntail; &thorn;e me&ntail; of &thorn;e
citee herde this, &thorn;ay ware ferde ynoghe and onane went to
&thorn;e kynge&yogh; palace & brakke vp &thorn;e &yogh;ates, & tuke
Candeolus wyfe & delyuer&dtail; hir ti&llbar; hir
lorde. &THORN;a&ntail; Candeolus knele&dtail; dou&ntail; ti&llbar;
Alexander & saide vn-ti&llbar; hym: 'A a, my dere frende,' quo&thorn;
he, 'wirchipfu&llbar; Antyochus, Blyssed mot &thorn;ou be for
&thorn;is grete gudnes &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase schewe&dtail; mee. And
I beseke the nowe &thorn;at

<PB N="99">
&thorn;ou wi&llbar; vouche-saffe for to wende with me vn-to my moder
quene Candace, &thorn;at scho may rewarde &thorn;e for &thorn;is
&thorn;at &thorn;ou hase done for me.'  And whe&ntail; Alexander herde
this he was ri&yogh;te gladde.  For he had gretely desyrede for to see
quene Candace & hir citee also.  And &thorn;an he say&dtail;: 'Goo
we,' quo&thorn; he, 'to &thorn;e emperour and asche hym leue.'  And
&thorn;ay di&dtail; soo; and whe&ntail; he had leue, he went wit
Candeolus.  And as &thorn;ay went to-gedir &thorn;ay come ti&llbar;
heghe mountaynes &thorn;at reched vpto &thorn;e clowdes and apo&ntail;
&thorn;am &thorn;are growe&dtail; trees of a wonderfu&llbar; heghte
lyke<MILESTONE N="42" UNIT="leaf"> vn-to cedres &thorn;at bare appi&llbar;s of Inde ri&yogh;te
grete, Of &thorn;e whilk Alexander wonnderde hym gretly.  &THORN;ay
saw also &thorn;are vynes growe wit wondere grete bobbis of grapes;
for a ma&ntail; my&yogh;te vnnethe&yogh; bere a&ntail; of
&thorn;a&mtail;.  &THORN;are ware also trees &thorn;at bare
nutte&yogh; als grete als gourdde&yogh;.  And &thorn;are ware also
many apes.  Fra &thorn;eine &thorn;ay went & come to &thorn;e citee of
quene Candace.
</P>
<P>And whe&ntail; Candace herd te&llbar; &thorn;at hir so&ntail;
Candeolus and his wyfe ware comande and ware safe & sounde, An&dtail;
at a messangere of kyng Alexander come wit &thorn;ai&mtail;, scho was
wonder gladde; and onane scho araye&dtail; hir ryally as a quene suld
be, and sett apo&ntail; hir hedde a crou&ntail; fu&llbar; ryche
a&llbar; of golde sett fu&llbar; of precyouse stanes, an&dtail; went
furthe wit hir lordes to &thorn;e &yogh;ates of hir palace, for to
mete hir so&ntail; Candeolus an&dtail; Alexander messanger.  This
quene was a wondere faire lady & a semely; And whe&ntail; Alexander
saw hir, hym thog&hbar;te als he hade sene his moder Olympias.  Hir
palace was wonder rya&llbar;e & precyouse an&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e
ruffe &thorn;are-of schane wit golde & precyouse stanes. Tha&ntail;
quene Candace tuke Alexander bi &thorn;e hande, And led&dtail; hym vp
ti&llbar; hir chambir, whare &thorn;are ware beddes araye&dtail; wit
&thorn;e fyneste clathes of golde &thorn;at myghte be gety&ntail;; And
&thorn;at chambir was of golde & precyous stanes, &thorn;e whilke are
calle&dtail; Onychyns & &thorn;e burde&yogh; & &thorn;e bynkes of
euour & Smaragde&yogh; & Amatistes.  &THORN;e Pelers of &thorn;e
Palace ware a&llbar; of Marble, An&dtail; &thorn;ar ware graue&ntail;
in &thorn;a&mtail; cartes of werre, &thorn;at seme&dtail; to mannes
sighte as &thorn;ay had&dtail; bene rynnan&dtail;; And Olyphanntes
tredan&dtail; me&ntail; vnder &thorn;aire fete.  Vndernethe &thorn;at
Palace rane a water wonder swete, & clere as any crista&llbar;e.
 
<PB N="100">
&THORN;at day Alexander ete wit quene Candace & hir childire.
</P>
<P>Apo&ntail; &thorn;e morne quene Candace tuk Alexander by &thorn;e
right hande & led&dtail; hym in-ti&llbar; hir bed&dtail;-chambir, and
nane wit &thorn;a&mtail;, Bot &thorn;ay twa alla&ntail;.  &THORN;is
chambir was couerde a&llbar; ouer wit-in wit golde & precious stanes.
And it schane wit-in, as it had bene &thorn;e sonne.  And oute of
&thorn;is chambir scho led&dtail; hym in-ti&llbar; a wit-drawyng
chambir made of cypresse. &THORN;is chambir was sett apo&ntail; foure
wheles by crafte of clergy; And twenty xx<HI>ti</HI> Olyphauntis drewe
it whedir as scho wolde hafe it.  And whe&ntail; Alexander & &thorn;e
quene ware entrede in-to &thorn;at chambir, onane it stirred&dtail; &
by-gan for to remowe.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Alexander was astonayde &
meruaylle&dtail; hy&mtail; gretly & said vn-to &thorn;e quene : For
sothe,' quo&thorn; he, ' & &thorn;ir meruai&llbar;s ware in oure
cuntree &thorn;ay ware ri&yogh;te commendable & meki&llbar; worthy<MILESTONE
N="42 bk." UNIT="leaf"> to be praysede.'  The quene answerde: '&THORN;ou saise sothe, Alexander,'
quo&thorn; scho, '&thorn;ay ware mare commendable amange&yogh;
&thorn;e Greke&yogh;, &thorn;a&ntail; amange&yogh; vs.  And also sone
als Alexander herde hys name be neuenede, he was gretly trubblede, and
his vesage bi-ga&ntail; to waxe pale, and his chere to change.  And
than the quene said efte vn-to hym: 'Alexander,' quo&thorn; she, 'for
to schewe &thorn;e mare verrayly &thorn;at &thorn;ou ert Alexander,
co&mtail; with me.'  And &thorn;a&ntail; scho tuk hy&mtail; by
&thorn;e hande & leedde hym in-ti&llbar; ano&thorn;er chambir, and
schewe&dtail; hym &thorn;are his awen&ntail; Fygure purtraye&dtail; in
a parchemy&ntail; skyne.  And whe&ntail; Alexander saw &thorn;at, he
wex pale & wanne & biganne to tremblee.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e
quene said vn-ti&llbar; hym: 'Alexander,' quo&thorn; scho,' where-fore
ert &thorn;ou ferde, & why chaunge&yogh; &thorn;ou chere.  Thou
&thorn;at hase distroye&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e werlde; conquerour of
Perse, of Inde, of Mede, and many o&thorn;er rewmes & lande&yogh;, Now
arte &thorn;ou witowtte&ntail; scheddynge of blode falle&ntail; in
&thorn;e dawngere & in &thorn;e hande&yogh; of quene Candace
vnauysyli.  And &thorn;are-by may &thorn;ou wele knawe &thorn;at a
manes hert sulde on na wyse be enhance&dtail; in pride.  For if
a&llbar; it bee &thorn;at ofte tymmes grete prosperitee fa&llbar; to
ma&ntail;, Sodaynly falle&yogh; adversitee ti&llbar; hym whe&ntail; he
leste wenes.'  Whe&ntail; Alexander herde &thorn;is he biga&ntail; to
grayste wit &thorn;e teethe and to torne his hede hedir & thedir, And
quene Candace saide vn-ti&llbar; hy&mtail;: 'Whare to angers &thorn;ou
&thorn;e,' quo&thorn; scho, '& truble&yogh; thi selfe?  What may now
thi grete Imperia&llbar; glory, thi witt & thi mighte serue
<PB N="101">
the offe?'  Alexander ansuerde & sai&dtail;: Forsothe,' quo&thorn;
Alexander, 'resonably I am angry at my selfe bi-cause I hafe na swerde
here.'  Quo&thorn; &thorn;e quene: 'I suppose &thorn;ou hadd a swerde,
nowe, what walde do &thorn;are-wit?'  'Sothely,' quo&thorn; he,
'bi-cause I hafe wilfully betraye&dtail; my-selfe vn-to &thorn;e.
First I solde sla &thorn;e and &thorn;a&ntail;, I dowte it no&yogh;t,
I sulde be slayne for &thorn;e.'  'Now for sothe,' quo&thorn; scho,
'&thorn;is was wisely & ma&ntail;fully sayde.  Neuer-&thorn;e-less be
nathynge heuy.  For as &thorn;ou delyuerde my so&ntail; wyfe Candeolus
oute of &thorn;e daungere of &thorn;e kyng of Bebrikes Swaa sa&llbar;
I delyuer the oute of &thorn;e daungere of thy&ntail; enemys &thorn;at
&thorn;ou hase here.  For I say &thorn;e in certayne, and it ware
knawe&ntail; &thorn;at &thorn;ou ware here vn-to my men&yogh;ee, onane
&thorn;ay walde slaa &thorn;e by-cause &thorn;ou slewe Porus &thorn;e
kynge of Inde.  For my so&ntail; wyfe Carator was his doughter.'  And
whe&ntail; scho had said &thorn;is, Scho tuk Alexander bi &thorn;e
hande & led&dtail; hym forthe in-ti&llbar; hir forchambire and
sai&dtail; vnti&llbar; hir sones: 'My dere sonnes,' quo&thorn; scho,
'I pray &yogh;ow late vs make &thorn;is knyghte of Alexander gude
chere, and schew hy&mtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e humanytee &thorn;at we
ca&ntail;.  For Alexander has schewe&dtail; vs grete frendchipe and
grete gudnesse.'  And &thorn;a&ntail; hir &yogh;ongeste ansuerde &
sai&dtail;: 'Moder,'<MILESTONE N="43" UNIT="leaf"> quo&thorn; he, 'sothe it es &thorn;at he es a
messangere of Alexanders, & a knyghte of his, and &thorn;at he
delyuerde my bro&thorn;er wyfe of &thorn;e hande&yogh; of &thorn;e
kynge of &thorn;e Bebrikes and broghte hym & hir hame
vn-ti&llbar; vs bathe safe & sownde.  Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse my wyfe
constreyne&yogh; me for to do Antyochus to dede bi-cause of &thorn;e
dede of hir Fadir Porus, whilke Alexander slewe, So &thorn;at
Alexander may hafe sorow for his knyghte.  Quo&thorn; quene Candace
&thorn;a&ntail;: 'Lefe so&ntail;, what wirchi&ptail; may we get
&thorn;are-offe if we slaa this knyghte &thorn;us traytourusly.'  And
&thorn;a&ntail; Candeolus sayde wit a grete Ire, '&THORN;is knyghte,'
quo&thorn; he, 'saue&dtail; me & my wyfe & broghte vs hedir safe &
sonde; And als saffe sa&llbar; I hafe hym, agayne ti&llbar; his lorde,
or I sa&llbar; be dede &thorn;arefore.'  And Carator ansuerde & saide:
'Bro&thorn;er,' quo&thorn; he, 'what says &thorn;ou?  wi&llbar;
&thorn;ou &thorn;at aythere of vs here slaa o&thorn;er?' 'In gud
faythe bro&thorn;er,' quo&thorn; he, 'it es no&yogh;te my wi&llbar;,
ne my liste.  Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse if it be thi liste, I am redy,
rather &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;is knyghte be dedde.'  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;e quene saw &thorn;at hir sonnes walde ayther of
&thorn;a&mtail; slaa o&thorn;er, scho was wonder sary, and tuk
Alexander o&ntail; syde, and saide vn-ti&llbar; hym preualy: 'A, a,
kyng Alexander,'
 
<PB N="102">
quo&thorn; scho, 'whi wi&llbar; &thorn;ou no&yogh;te schewe thi witt,
and helpe thurg&hbar; thi wisdo&mtail; &thorn;at my sonnes slaa
no&yogh;t ayther of &thorn;a&mtail; o&thorn;er ?'  And Alexander
answerde and sai&dtail;: 'Late me goo speke wit &thorn;am,' quo&thorn;
he.  And scho lete hym goo.  And he went to &thorn;a&mtail; and sayde
vn-to Carator: 'For sothe, Carator,' quo&thorn; he, 'I late &thorn;e
wite &thorn;at if &thorn;ou slaa me, &thorn;ou sa&llbar; wynne bot
lytti&llbar; wirchipe &thorn;areoffe.  For I say &thorn;e, kyng
Alexander hase many worthyer knyghtis wit hym &thorn;a&ntail; I
a&mtail;; And &thorn;are-fore he wi&llbar; hafe litti&llbar; sorowe for
my dede.  Trowes &thorn;ou &thorn;at and Alexander had&dtail; lufed me
wele &thorn;at he walde hafe sent me hyder to be kille&dtail;
amange&yogh; &yogh;owe.  Bot if &thorn;ou wi&llbar; &thorn;at I
beke&ntail; the Alexander &thorn;e slaere of &thorn;i wyfe fader &
bryng hym bi-for the, Swere me &thorn;at what so I asche &thorn;e,
&thorn;ou sa&llbar; graunte mee it, And I sure &thorn;e bi &thorn;e
faythe of my body, I sa&llbar; bryng Alexander in-to &thorn;is palace
be-fore &thorn;e.'  And whe&ntail; Carator herde this, he was
ri&yogh;te glade, and trowed &thorn;at that Alexander sai&dtail;.
And so ware &thorn;e twa bre&thorn;er pesede, And highte Alexander
&thorn;at his askynge sulde be fulfille&dtail; als ferforthe als
&thorn;aire powere reched, if so ware &thorn;at he helde
couenant. &THORN;a&ntail; quene Candace leedd Alexander on syde &
say&dtail; vn-ti&llbar; hym in preuatee: 'Wele ware me,' quo&thorn;
scho, 'myghte I ilke day hafe &thorn;e present be-fore my&ntail; eghne
as I hafe my&ntail; awen&ntail; childere.  For thurgh the sulde I
ouercome a&llbar; my&ntail; Enemys.' And &thorn;a&ntail; [scho] gaffe
Alexander a corou&ntail; of golde sett fu&llbar; of precyous
dyamande&yogh;, and a manti&llbar; Imperia&llbar; of a clathe of golde<MILESTONE
N="43 bk." UNIT="leaf">
wit sternes wofen &thorn;are-i&ntail;, and sett fu&llbar; of precyouse
stanes.  And &thorn;a&ntail; scho kysse&dtail; hym & o&thorn;er preuee
thynge&yogh; did&dtail; ti&llbar; hym, And badde hym goo in hir
blyssynge.
</P>
<P>Than kyng Alexander and Candeolus went furthe a&llbar; that daye,
And come ti&llbar; a grete spelunc, and &thorn;are &thorn;ay herberde
&thorn;a&mtail;.  And Candeolus saideti&llbar; Alexander: 'In this
spelunc,' quo&thorn; hee, '&thorn;at you here see&yogh; a&llbar;
godde&yogh; ere wount for to ete and halde &thorn;aire consai&llbar;.'
And &thorn;a&ntail; onane Alexander made sacrafyce&yogh; ti&llbar;
his godde&yogh; and enterde in-to &thorn;e caue by hym ane.  And
&thorn;are he sawe a myrke clowde, & in &thorn;at myrknesse, he sawe
as it ware bryghte sternes, and amange&yogh; &thorn;ase sternes he saw
a grete god&dtail; sitt, And his eghne lyke twa lanternes.  And
whe&ntail; Alexander saw hy&mtail; he was so fere&dtail; &thorn;at he
was as it had&dtail; bene
<PB N="103">
in a transynge.  And &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e god&dtail; said vn-to
hy&mtail;: 'Haile, Alexander,' quo&thorn; he. And Alexander ansuerde &
sai&dtail;: 'Lorde,' quo&thorn; he, 'what art &thorn;ou ?'  'I am,'
quo&thorn; he, 'Senso&ntail;chosis &thorn;at gouerne&yogh; &thorn;e
kyngdo&mtail; of &thorn;e werlde and &thorn;at hase made me&ntail;
sugettes vn-to the.  And &thorn;ou hase bigge&dtail; &thorn;iselfe
many rya&llbar;e citee&yogh;.  Bot temple walde &thorn;ou nane make in
&thorn;e wirchippe of me.' And Alexander ansuer&dtail; & sai&dtail;:
'Lorde,' quo&thorn; he, '& &thorn;ou wi&llbar; graunt me &thorn;at I
sa&llbar; wit prosperitee come in-to Macedoyne I sa&llbar; ordeyne the
a temple &thorn;are sa&llbar; no&yogh;te be swilke ano&thorn;er in
a&llbar; &thorn;e werlde.'  And he ansuer&dtail; agayne & saide: 'For
sothe,' quo&thorn; hee, 'Macedoyne sa&llbar; &thorn;ou neuer see wit
thy&ntail; eghne.  Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse walke Innermare & luke what
&thorn;ou see&yogh;.'  Alexander &thorn;a&ntail; went forthirmare &
saw ano&thorn;er myrke clowde and saw a god&dtail; sitt in a trone
lyke a kynge, and Alexander said vn-ti&llbar; hym: 'Lorde,' quo&thorn;
he, 'what art &thorn;ou ?' 'I am,' quo&thorn; he, '&thorn;e begynnynge
of a&llbar; godde&yogh; and Serapis es my name.  I sawe the in
&thorn;e lande of liby & nowe I see &thorn;e here.'  'Serapis,'
quo&thorn; Alexander, 'I beseke &thorn;e te&llbar;e me wha it es
&thorn;at sall sla me.'  Quod Serapis: 'I talde &thorn;e bi-fore,
&thorn;at and &thorn;e cause of a manes dede ware knawe&ntail;
vn-ti&llbar; hym, he solde dy for sorowe.  &THORN;ou hase bygged a
glorious citee agaynes &thorn;e whilke many emperours sa&llbar;
fighte.  &THORN;are-in sa&llbar; thi graue be made and &thorn;are-in
sa&llbar; &thorn;ou be berie&dtail;.'  And &thorn;a&ntail; Alexander
come oute of &thorn;e caue, and tuke his leue at Candeolus and went
ti&llbar; his Oste.
</P>
<P>One &thorn;e morne he remowe&dtail; his Oste And come ti&llbar; a
valay &thorn;at was fu&llbar; of grete serpentes &thorn;e whilk hade
in &thorn;aire heuedis Grete smaragde&yogh;. Thir serpente&yogh;<MILESTONE
N="44" UNIT="leaf">
lyffede a&llbar; wit gyngere and pepir &thorn;at growede in &thorn;e
valaye.  And ilke a &yogh;ere &thorn;ay feghte to-gedir and many of
&thorn;a&mtail; slae&yogh; o&thorn;er.  Off &thorn;e forsaid Smaragdes
tuk Alexander su&mtail; wit hym of &thorn;e gretteste &thorn;at he
couthe gett.
</P>
<P>Fra &thorn;eine &thorn;ay remowe&dtail; & come in-ti&llbar; a place
in &thorn;e whilke &thorn;are ware beste&yogh; &thorn;at hade one ilke
a fote twa clees as swyne hase, and &thorn;ase clees ware three fote
brade wit &thorn;e whilke &thorn;ay smate Alexander knyghtes.
&THORN;ay had also heuedes lyke swyne & tayles lyke lyouns. &THORN;are
ware also amange&yogh; &thorn;a&mtail; grypes &thorn;e
 
<PB N="104">
whilke smate <SIC>kynghtes</SIC> in &thorn;e vesage&yogh; reghte felly. &THORN;ay ware so strange &thorn;at ane of &thorn;a&mtail; wolde bere away an arme&dtail; knyghte & his horse also. &THORN;a&ntail; kynge
Alexander rade hedir & &thorn;edir amange&yogh; his me&ntail; and
comforthe&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; and bad&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; feghte
manly agaynes &thorn;a&mtail; wit speres and wit arowes.  And so
&thorn;ay di&dtail;.  Bot &thorn;are was slayne of Alexander knyghtes
ccviii.
</P>
<P>And fra &thorn;eine &thorn;ay remowe&dtail; and come ti&llbar; a
grete ryuer &thorn;e whilke was twenty furlange on brede fra &thorn;e
ta banke to &thorn;e to&thorn;er.  And on &thorn;ase bankes &thorn;are
growe&dtail; redis wonder grete and hye.  Of &thorn;ase redes garte
Alexander mak bates & anoynte &thorn;a&mtail; wit terre & talg&hbar;
of beste&yogh;, And bad&dtail; his knyghtis row ouer &thorn;e water in
&thorn;ase bates.  And &thorn;ay di&dtail; soo.  And whe&ntail;
&thorn;e [pople] of &thorn;e cunntree herde te&llbar; of &thorn;e
commynge of Alexander & his Oste, &thorn;ay sent hym gyftes of swylk
thynge&yogh; als was in &thorn;aire cuntree, &thorn;at es at say Grete
spounge&yogh; bathe whitte & purpure & schelles of &thorn;e see so
grete &thorn;at an of &thorn;a&mtail; walde halde twa pekkes or three.
&THORN;ay sent hym also wormes &thorn;at &thorn;ay drew owte of
&thorn;at ryuer grettere &thorn;a&ntail; a manes thee, and &thorn;ay
ware swetter of taste &thorn;a&ntail; any fysche.  &THORN;ay gaffe hym
Cukstoles a&llbar; rede &thorn;at ware of a wonderfu&llbar; gretnesse.
In &thorn;at ryuer ware womans &thorn;at ware wonder faire & &thorn;ay
hade o&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail; meki&llbar; here &thorn;at reched&dtail;
dou&ntail; to thaire fete.  &THORN;ir wome&ntail;, when &thorn;ay saw
any straunge me&ntail; swymme in &thorn;at riuer, ow&thorn;er
&thorn;ay drownne&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; in &thorn;e water, or
e&llbar;s &thorn;ay walde lede &thorn;a&mtail; to &thorn;e rede&yogh;
&thorn;at growe&dtail; o&ntail; &thorn;e water bankes and garre
&thorn;a&mtail; lye by &thorn;a&mtail; ay ti&llbar; any lyfe was in
&thorn;a&mtail;.  &THORN;e Macedoynes persued &thorn;a&mtail; & tuke
twa of &thorn;a&mtail; and broghte &thorn;a&mtail; ti&llbar;
Alexander,<MILESTONE N="44 bk." UNIT="leaf"> and &thorn;ay ware als white as any snawe, and &thorn;ay
ware ten fote lange and &thorn;aire teethe ware lyke dogge teethe.
</P>
<P>Efter this Alexander went and close&dtail; in a maner of folkee
&thorn;at are calle&dtail; Gog & Magog, with-in &thorn;e hille&yogh;
of Caspy.  &THORN;is folke&yogh; were of &thorn;e ten kynde&yogh; of
Israel, and &thorn;ay ware leed&dtail; owte of &thorn;aire awen&ntail;
lan&dtail; bi a kyng of Perse be-cause of &thorn;aire synne&yogh; and
halden in thralledo&mtail;.  And &thorn;ay asche&dtail; Alexander leue
for to wende furt&hbar; of &thorn;at cuntree.  And Alexander gert
spirre &thorn;e cause of &thorn;aire thraldo&mtail;, and he was
encense&dtail; &thorn;at be-cause &thorn;ay
<PB N="105">
had&dtail; forsake&ntail; &thorn;aire godde&yogh; lawe, &thorn;at es
at say, god&dtail; of Isr&lbar;, and wirchipe&dtail; Calues &
o&thorn;er Mawmettes, &thorn;are-fore &thorn;ay ware led&dtail; oute
of &thorn;aire awen&ntail; lande & halde&ntail; in thralldo&mtail;,
and &thorn;at prophetes had prophice&dtail; be-fore &thorn;at
&thorn;ay sulde neuer come oute of thraldo&mtail; bi-fore agayne
&thorn;e day of dome. And &thorn;a&ntail; Alexander ansuerde & said
&thorn;at he sulde sperre &thorn;a&mtail; I&ntail; mare seurely. And
&thorn;a&ntail; he garte close a&llbar; &thorn;e entree&yogh; wit
stane & lyme & san&dtail;, Bot a&llbar; &thorn;at he garte make on
&thorn;e day was fordone o&ntail; &thorn;e nyghte. And whe&ntail;
Alexander saw &thorn;at mannes laboure myghte no&yogh;te stande in
stede, he bi-soghte god&dtail; of Isr&lbar; &thorn;at if it ware his
liste &thorn;at &thorn;ay habade &thorn;are, &thorn;at he walde close
&thorn;a&mtail; in. And &thorn;e nexte nyghte aftir ilk a cragge
fe&llbar;e ti&llbar; o&thorn;er, and so &thorn;are may nathynge passe
in nor owte. And &thorn;are-by it seme&yogh; &thorn;at it es
no&yogh;te godde&yogh; wi&llbar; &thorn;at &thorn;ay come oute.
Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse abowte &thorn;e Ende of &thorn;e werlde &thorn;ay
sa&llbar; breke oute and do meki&llbar; schathe & slaa many me&ntail;.
</P>
<P>Fra &thorn;eine &thorn;ay remowe&dtail; & come to &thorn;e grete
See Occeane.  In &thorn;at See &thorn;ay sawe ane Ile a litti&llbar;
fra &thorn;e lande.  And in &thorn;at Ile &thorn;ay herde me&ntail;
speke grewe.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Alexander commande&dtail; &thorn;at
su&mtail; of his knyghts sulde do off &thorn;aire clathes and swyme
ouer to &thorn;e ile.  And &thorn;ay di&dtail; soo.  And als sone als
&thorn;ay come in &thorn;e See &thorn;are come gret crabbes vp oute of
&thorn;e water & pullede &thorn;a&mtail; downne to &thorn;e grounde &
drownne&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail;.
</P>
<P>Thanne remowe&dtail; &thorn;ay fra thethy&ntail; and went ay
endlande &thorn;e See syde to-warde &thorn;e solstice of wynter
trauellande x&lbar; days; and at &thorn;e laste &thorn;ay come to a
reede See, and &thorn;are &thorn;ay lugede &thorn;a&mtail;.
&THORN;are was faste by a Mountayne wonder hye, One &thorn;e whilke
Alexander went vp.  And whe&ntail; he was abow&ntail; o&ntail;
&thorn;e heghte &thorn;are-offe, hym thoghte &thorn;at he was nerre
&thorn;e Firmament &thorn;an &thorn;e erthe; &thorn;a&ntail; he
ymagne&dtail; in his hert swilk a gyn&ntail; how he myghte make<MILESTONE
N="45" UNIT="leaf">
grippes bere hym vp in-to &thorn;e ayere.  And onane he come doune of
&thorn;e Mountayne and garte come bi-fore hy&mtail; his Maistre
wrightes and comandi&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at &thorn;ay sulde
make hym a chayer and trelesse it wit barre&yogh; of Ire&ntail; one
ilk a syde so &thorn;at he my&yogh;te sauely sitt &thorn;are-in.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he gart brynge foure gripes and tye &thorn;a&mtail;
faste wit Ire&ntail; cheynes vn-to &thorn;e chayere, and in &thorn;e
ouermare party of &thorn;e chayere he gart putt
 
<PB N="106">
mete for &thorn;e grippes.  And pa&ntail; he wente and sett hy&mtail;
in &thorn;e chayere.  And onane &thorn;e grippes bare hym vp in
&thorn;e ayer so hye &thorn;at Alexander thoghte a&llbar; &thorn;e
erthe na mare &thorn;a&ntail; a flure &thorn;are me&ntail;
thressche&yogh; corne, and &thorn;e See lyke a drago&ntail; abowte
&thorn;e erthe.  &THORN;a&ntail; sodaynly a specya&llbar; vertu of
god&dtail; vmbilapped &thorn;e grippes &thorn;at gart &thorn;a&mtail;
discende douue to &thorn;e erthe in a felde: ten .x. day iournee fra
&thorn;e Oste, and he had&dtail; na hurt ne na schathe in &thorn;e
chayere.  Bot wit grete disesse at &thorn;e laste he come ti&llbar;
his Oste.
</P>
<P>After &thorn;is Alexander ymagened in his hert &thorn;at he walde
knaw &thorn;e preuates &thorn;at are in &thorn;e see.  And onane he
gart come bifore hy&mtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e Maister glasyers
&thorn;at ware in &thorn;e Oste, And comandede &thorn;a&mtail; to make
hym a grete tounne of passandly clere glasse &thorn;at he myghte
thurg&hbar; it clerely see a&llbar; maner of thynge &thorn;at ware
wit-owtte&ntail; it.  And whe&ntail; it was made he gart trelesse it
al abowte witowtte&ntail; wit barres of yre&ntail; and feste
&thorn;are-to lang cheynes of yre&ntail;, and gart a certane of
&thorn;e strangeste & maste tristy knyghtes &thorn;at lange&dtail;
vn-ti&llbar; hym halde &thorn;ir cheynes. And &thorn;a&ntail; he went
in-to &thorn;e tounne & gart pykke wele &thorn;e entree whare he went
in, and &thorn;a&ntail; late it dou&ntail; into &thorn;e See.  And
&thorn;are he sawe dyuerse schappes of fisches of dyuerse colours; and
su&mtail; he sawe hafe &thorn;e schappe of dyuerse beste&yogh; here
one &thorn;e lande, gangande on fete as beste&yogh; dose here & etande
fruyte of treesse &thorn;at growe&yogh; on &thorn;e See grunde.
&THORN;ir beste&yogh; come ti&llbar; hym.  Bot onane as &thorn;ay saw
hym thorow &thorn;e glasse &thorn;ay fledde fra hym.  He sawe
&thorn;are also many o&thorn;er meruaylous thynge&yogh;, &thorn;e
whilke he walde te&llbar; na ma&ntail; bi-cause me&ntail; walde noghte
hafe trowe&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; if he had talde &thorn;a&mtail;, and
at a certayne houre &thorn;ase &thorn;at he had&dtail; assyngned
be-fore, his knyghtes drewe hym vp oute of &thorn;e See.
</P>
<P>Fra &thorn;eine &thorn;ay Remowe&dtail; Folowande &thorn;e bankes
of &thorn;e Rede See, and luged &thorn;a&mtail; in a place, whare
&thorn;are ware wylde Beste&yogh; that hade o&ntail; &thorn;aire
heuedis hornes lyke vn-to<MILESTONE N="45 bk." UNIT="leaf"> sawes, and &thorn;ay ware als scharpe als
swerde&yogh;. And with thire hornes &thorn;ay slewe & hurte many
knyghtis of Alexanders & cloue &thorn;aire cheldes in sonder.
Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse Alexander knyghtis slew of &thorn;a&mtail;
ccccli.
</P>
<P>And fra beine &thorn;ay remowe&dtail; and come in-ti&llbar; wilderness
<PB N="107">
bitwex &thorn;e ree&dtail; See and Araby, whare grete multitude of
Pepir growe&dtail;; And &thorn;are ware many grete nedders wit hornnes
on &thorn;aire hedes lyke tuppe hornes, wit &thorn;e whilke &thorn;ay
smate Alexander knyghtis ri&yogh;t felly. Off &thorn;ase nedderes slew
&thorn;e Macedoynes a grete party.
</P>
<P>&THORN;eine &thorn;ay remowe&dtail; and luge&dtail; in a place
whare many Rynosephales ware, &thorn;e whilke hade heuedes & manes
lyke horse&yogh;.  And &thorn;ay hade grete bodys, and wonder grete
teethe and lange, and oute of &thorn;aire mouthes &thorn;ay schotte
flawme&yogh; of fyre.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ay saw &thorn;e Oste luge
&thorn;are &thorn;ay come & assaylle&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail;.  And
Alexander ra&ntail; hyder and thedir amange&yogh; &thorn;e oste and
comforthe&dtail; his knyghtes and bad &thorn;a&mtail; feghte manly wit
&thorn;ase monstres.  And so &thorn;ay did&dtail;.  Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse &thorn;are ware a grete multitude of his knyghtis slayne of &thorn;ase beste&yogh;.  Bot of &thorn;e Rynocephales &thorn;are was
slayne an hugge multitude.
</P>
<P>&THORN;a&ntail; &thorn;ay remowe&dtail; fra &thorn;eine and come
in-ti&llbar; a champayne cuntree and luge&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail;
&thorn;are, And lay &thorn;are a certane days, Bi-cause of his horse
Buktyphalas &thorn;at fe&llbar; seke &thorn;are; of &thorn;e whilke
sekenesse he dye&dtail;. And whe&ntail; Alexander saw hym ded&dtail;
he made grete dole for hym and wepe&dtail; for hym ri&yogh;t sare.
For he had&dtail; borne hym in many a Bate&llbar;e, and broghte [hym]
oute of many pere&llbar;s.  And &thorn;are-fore whe&ntail; he was dede
Alexander gart doo aboute hym grete exequyes and gart make hym a
fu&llbar; riche toumbe & a hye and di&dtail; hym &thorn;are-in and
made a grete citee &thorn;are, &thorn;e whilke in mynde of his horse
he gart ca&llbar; Buktyphalas.
</P>
<P>Fra &thorn;eine &thorn;ay remowe&dtail; and come ti&llbar; a ryuere
&thorn;at was calle&dtail; Cytan or Deciracy whare me&ntail; of
&thorn;e cuntree broghte hy&mtail; &vtilde; Olyphantes and &vtilde;
cartes of werre.  And fra &thorn;eine &thorn;ay remowe&dtail; & come
ti&llbar; kynge &yogh;erses palace.  And in &thorn;at Palace &thorn;ay
fande bedde&yogh; of clene golde many a thowsande.  &THORN;are ware
also grete fewles white als doufes, &thorn;e whilke had knawyng
be-fore of a seke ma&ntail; wheder he schulde lyffe or dye.  For if
&thorn;ay by-helde &thorn;e seke ma&ntail; in &thorn;e vesage, he
schulde mende & fare wele.  And if &thorn;ay tourne&dtail; &thorn;am
awaywarde witowtte&ntail;
 
<PB N="108">
doute he schulde dye,<MILESTONE N="46" UNIT="leaf"> and if &thorn;ay tourned hym &thorn;e bakke wit owtte&ntail; dowte he sulde dye.
</P>
<P>FRa &thorn;eine &thorn;ay remowe&dtail; and come to &thorn;e grete
Citee of Babiloyne and wanne it oo werre and slew &thorn;e kynge
&thorn;are-offe & &thorn;e Captayne also. And pare he duelle&dtail;
vn-ti&llbar; his lyffes en&dtail;, and pat was Bot vij seue&ntail;
Monethes.  In &thorn;at mene tyme Alexander sent a lettre ti&llbar;
Olympias his Moder and ti&llbar; his Mayster Arestotle, latan&dtail;
&thorn;a&mtail; witte of &thorn;e Bate&llbar;s and &thorn;e dyssese
&thorn;at &thorn;ay suffre&dtail; bathe wynters and Somers in Inde and
o&thorn;er cuntree&yogh;, and also of &thorn;e Bate&llbar;s &thorn;at
&thorn;ay ha&dtail; had&dtail; wit dyuerse Monstres.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; Arestotle wrate ano&thorn;er lettre ti&llbar;
Alexander agayne &thorn;e whilke was of this tenour: <Q TYPE="letter"><TEXT>
<BODY>
<P>'Un-ti&llbar; Alexandere &thorn;e grete kynge of kynge&yogh;
Arestotle sende&yogh; ioy and seruyce.  Whe&ntail; I hade redde
&yogh;our wyrchipfu&llbar; lettres I was gretly astonay&dtail;.  For
whilke cause I desyre with a&llbar; my&ntail; hert for to fynde
lonynge &thorn;at I myghte &yogh;elde vn-to &thorn;e.  I take witnesse
at oure godde&yogh; &thorn;at for &thorn;e passande hardenesse of
&thorn;i &hbar;ert & &thorn;e grete auentours &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase
put &thorn;e in, &thorn;ou erte wele worthy for to be loue&dtail; &
praysede.  For &thorn;ou hase sene & assaye&dtail; thynge&yogh;
&thorn;at neuer ma&ntail; or &thorn;is durste assaye. Whare-for
thankynge & lonynge I &yogh;elde to &thorn;e makere of a&llbar;
&thorn;is wyde werlde &thorn;at swylke victoryes hase grantede vn-to
&thorn;e. For &thorn;ou hase ouercomme&ntail; a&llbar; & nane hase
ouercome&ntail; &thorn;e.  Fu&llbar; blyssede are a&llbar; thy
prynce&yogh; &thorn;at hase bene obeyande vnto &thorn;e, and
helpe&dtail; &thorn;e in a&llbar; thi
disesse&yogh;.'</P></BODY></TEXT></Q>
</P>
<P>Afftir &thorn;is Alexander gart make in Babyloyne a wonder curious
trone of golde, &thorn;are was no&yogh;te swilke ano&thorn;er in
&thorn;e werlde. For &thorn;e greke&yogh; broghte so meki&llbar; golde
oute of perse & oute of Inde, &thorn;at it ware wonder for to telle.
&THORN;is ilke toure was twlue cubyte&yogh; hye and by twelue
grece&yogh; me&ntail; ascende&dtail; &thorn;are-too, and &thorn;ase
gree&yogh; ware a&llbar; of golde.  &THORN;is trone was wonderfully
wroghte and sett apo&ntail; twelue ymage&yogh; of golde, &thorn;e
whilke trone &thorn;e forsai&dtail; ymage&yogh; helde vp wit
&thorn;aire hende. And on &thorn;ase twelue ymage&yogh; ware
wrety&ntail; &thorn;e names of &thorn;e twelue prynce&yogh; of
Macedoyne.  &THORN;e seet of &thorn;e trone was of a Smaragde,
<PB N="109">
& &thorn;e syde&yogh; &thorn;are off ware of Topa&yogh;es & in
ilka&ntail; of &thorn;e gree&yogh; ware sett dyuerse maneres of
precyouse stanes.  In &thorn;e summyt of &thorn;is trone &thorn;are
wassett a ruby &thorn;at schane on &thorn;e nyghte as it hade bene
&thorn;e Mone.  In &thorn;is trone also was &thorn;are sett o&ntail;
ilke a syde dyuerse ymage&yogh; on &thorn;e whilke ware wrety&ntail;
bathe in latyne & in grew<MILESTONE N="46 bk." UNIT="leaf"> verse&yogh; &thorn;at contene&dtail;
a&llbar; &thorn;e nammes of &thorn;e rewmes & cuntree&yogh; &thorn;at
Alexandere had conquere&dtail; and ware sugetes vn-ti&llbar; hym.
</P>
<P>After &thorn;is Alexander gert make a coro&ntail; of golde sett
fu&llbar; of a&llbar; maner of precyouse stanes, and gert wryte
apo&ntail; it a tytle in grew & in laty&ntail;: 'Ortus & occasus,
Aquilo michi seruit & Auster.'  &THORN;at es at saye: 'Est & weste,
Northe & southe dose seruyce vn-to me.'  In the mene tyme whils
Alexander was in babyloyne, a woma&ntail; was delyuer of a knaue
childe &thorn;e whilke fra &thorn;e heuede to &thorn;e nauy&llbar;
had&dtail; schappe of ma&ntail;, & was borne ded&dtail;.  And fra
&thorn;e nauy&llbar; downwarde&yogh; it had lyknesse of dyuerse
beste&yogh; and was qwykke.  &THORN;is Monstre was take&ntail; &
broghte ti&llbar; Alexander; and als so&ntail; als he saw it he
meruaylle&dtail; gretly &thorn;are-off, and gart come bi-fore
hy&mtail; a philosopher &thorn;at couthe of wiche-crafte, & aschede
hym what it sygnyfye&dtail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;e philosopher saw
it, he syghede, & saye wepan&dtail; sayde vn-to hym: 'Sothely
wirchipfu&llbar; emperour,' quo&thorn; he, '&thorn;e tyme comme&yogh;
nere that &thorn;ou sa&llbar; passe oute of this werlde.'  'Telle me,'
quo&thorn; Alexander, 'whareby &thorn;ou knawes &thorn;at.'  And
&thorn;e philosophre ansuerde & sayde: 'My lorde,' quo&thorn; he,
'&thorn;e halfe of &thorn;is Monstre &thorn;at hase &thorn;e schappe
of ma&ntail; & es ded&dtail;, betakens &thorn;at &thorn;ou sa&llbar;
passe out of &thorn;is werlde in haste.  And &thorn;e to&thorn;er
party &thorn;at hase &thorn;e lyknes of dyuerse beste&yogh; & es on
lyfe, betakynges &thorn;e kynges &thorn;at sa&llbar; come after
&thorn;e.  Bot &thorn;are sa&llbar; nane of &thorn;a&mtail; be lyke
vn-to &thorn;e, na mare &thorn;a&ntail; a beste es lyke vn-ti&llbar; a
ma&ntail;.'  Whe&ntail; Alexander herde &thorn;is he was wonder heuy,
and sare wepan&dtail; he sayde on &thorn;is wyse: 'O A&llbar;myghty
Iubiter,' quo&thorn; he, 'what mene&yogh; it &thorn;at my dayes
sa&llbar; be so schortte ?  Me thynke &thorn;at it had bene semely
&thorn;at I had leffe&dtail; langere for ti&llbar; haf endi&dtail;
thynge&yogh; &thorn;at are in my thoghte.  Bot for als meki&llbar; als
it es no&yogh;te plesande vn-to &thorn;e, I beseke the &thorn;at
&thorn;ou resayffe me whe&ntail; I sa&llbar; passe hethe&ntail; als
thy&ntail; awe&ntail; seruante.'
</P>
<P>In this mene tyme &thorn;are was in Macedoyne a lorde &thorn;at
highte
 
<PB N="110">
Antipater, &thorn;e whilke of langetyme be-fore had&dtail; casten for
&thorn;e dedde of Alexander; And wit many o&thorn;er &thorn;at he
had&dtail; confedre&dtail; vn-ti&llbar; hy&mtail; he conspyre&dtail;
for to brynge it ty&llbar; ende, bot he myghte neuer come aboute
&thorn;er-with.  For Olympias, Alexander moder, wrate vn-ti&llbar; hym
ofte-sythes and warne&dtail; hym &thorn;at he scholde be warre wit
Antipater & his childre, and here-fore was Antypater wonder sary.  So
apo&ntail; a tyme he vmbythoghte hym &thorn;at he myghte neuer come
aboute wit his purpose for to slaa Alexander, bot if it ware
thurg&hbar; enpuysonynge.<MILESTONE N="47" UNIT="leaf">  And so apo&ntail; a daye he went ti&llbar;
a Sote&llbar; leche, and boghte of hy&mtail; a maner of drynke made of
puyso&ntail; that was so fe&llbar;e & se ranke &thorn;at &thorn;are
myghte no vesse&llbar;e halde it Bot a vesse&llbar; made of
Ire&ntail;; and &thorn;are-in he putt it.  And &thorn;a&ntail; he
gaffe it his so&ntail; Cassandre, and ba&dtail; hym bere it ti&llbar;
his bro&thorn;er Iobas and by&dtail; hym, quo&thorn; he, gyffe it to
kyng Alexander in his drynke, whe&ntail; he see&yogh; his tyme. This
ilk Iobas was a faire &yogh;ong ma&ntail; & was duellyng with
Alexander, and gretly by-luffede & cheriste of hym.  Bot so it
be-fe&llbar;e apo&ntail; a tyme &thorn;at Alexander smate Iobas on
&thorn;e heue&dtail; wit a warderere for na trespasse.  Whare-fore
Iobas was gretly angre&dtail; and greue&dtail; at Alexander and
consente&dtail; ti&llbar; his dede, and tuke &thorn;e puyso&ntail; of
his bro&thorn;er &thorn;at was ordeyne&dtail; for Alexander dede
&thorn;at luffe&dtail; hy&mtail; so meki&llbar;.
</P>
<P>And apo&ntail; a daye Alexander gart ordeyne a grete reue&llbar;e
in Babyloyne and calle&dtail; &thorn;are too a&llbar; his prynce&yogh;
o&ntail; ilke a syde.  And as he satt at &thorn;e mete Imange his
prynce&yogh; he was wonder mery & gladde & iocun&dtail;, and
rehete&dtail; his lorde&yogh; & praye&dtail; &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at
&thorn;ay schulde be mery.  &THORN;a&ntail; Iobas &thorn;at
serue&dtail; &thorn;e kyng of his coupe tuke of &thorn;e puyso&ntail;
a porcyo&ntail;, and putt it vnder &thorn;e nayle of his thowme, and
broghte &thorn;e coppe to &thorn;e kynge fu&llbar; of wyne.  And as he
gaffe it to &thorn;e kynge, he lete &thorn;e puyso&ntail; fa&llbar;e
in &thorn;e wyne priualy.  And als sone als &thorn;e kyng had&dtail;
dronke&ntail; &thorn;e puyso&ntail;, Sudaynly he gaffe a grete scryke,
and lene&dtail; hym down&ntail; towarde &thorn;e ri&yogh;te syde. For
hym thoghte reghte als a ma&ntail; had&dtail; smyte&ntail; hym in-to
&thorn;e lyuere wit a suerde.  Neuer-&thorn;e-lesse he feyne&dtail; &
forbare a while & suffre&dtail; a grete penance, and whe&ntail; he
my&yogh;te na langere habyde, he rase vp fra &thorn;e burde and saide
ti&llbar; his lorde&yogh; & his knyghtes: 'Lordyngis,' quo&thorn; he,
<PB N="111">
'I pray &yogh;ow sitt &yogh;e sti&llbar; & ete&yogh; & drynke&yogh; &
bee&yogh; mery.'  Bot &thorn;ay ware gretly troubble&dtail; and rase
vp fra &thorn;e burde&yogh; and stode witowtte&ntail; for to see
&thorn;e ende.  And Alexander went in-ti&llbar; his chambir gretly
tourmenti&dtail; and soghte a fethir for to putt in his throtte for to
garre hym hafe a vomet of &thorn;e puyso&ntail; &thorn;at he
had&dtail; resayffe&dtail;. And Iobas, &thorn;at was cheffe of
a&llbar; this hye treso&ntail;, gatt a fethir & enoynt it wit &thorn;e
same puyso&ntail; & broghte it ti&llbar; Alexander; and he tuk it &
putt it in his throtte, and belyfe<MILESTONE N="47 bk." UNIT="leaf"> &thorn;e puyso&ntail; vexe&dtail;
hym ay mare & mare.  And &thorn;a&ntail; Alexander bade ane gange &
ope&ntail; &thorn;e palace &yogh;ates &thorn;at ware on Eufrates
banke.  And a&llbar;e &thorn;at ny&yogh;te he woke in grete
payne&yogh; & tourment.  And aboute mydny&yogh;thte he rase oute of
&thorn;e bedde &thorn;at he lay in and putt oute &thorn;e lyghte
&thorn;at brynt by-fore hym, and for he myghte noghte ga
vprighte&yogh;, he crepe&dtail; one hende & one fete doune to-warde
Eufrate&yogh; for ti&llbar; hafe drownne&dtail; hym selfe, &thorn;at
&thorn;e strenth of &thorn;e water my&yogh;th hafe borne hym away
whare neuer ma&ntail; solde hafe fu&ntail; hym.
</P>
<P>And Rosa&ntail; his wyfe folowe&dtail; as faste as scho myghte. And
whe&ntail; scho come to hym scho fe&llbar;e vpo&ntail; hym &
enbrace&dtail; hym in hir armes & sai&dtail; vn-ti&llbar; hym: 'Allas,
my lorde Alexander,' quo&thorn; scho, 'wi&llbar; &thorn;ou now leue me
& gaa slaa thi-selfe.'  And scho wepe &thorn;at it was dole to see;
and Alexander ansuerde & sayde: 'I beseke &thorn;e Rosa&ntail;,'
quo&thorn; he, '&thorn;at ert so dere to me & so swete, late nane wit
of my&ntail; Endynge, if a&llbar; it be &thorn;at we may na langare
hafe ioy togedir.'  And &thorn;a&ntail; Rosa&ntail; led&dtail;
Alexander agayne to his bed&dtail;, and layde her armes aboute his
nekke and kyssede hym many a tyme, and sare wepan&dtail; sai&dtail;
vn-ti&llbar; hy&mtail;: 'A, A, my swete lorde,' quo&thorn; scho, 'if
&thorn;ine ende be nowe comme&ntail;, ordayne firste for vs or &yogh;e
passe he&thorn;ine.'  And onane he callede vn-ti&llbar; hym Iobas &
bade hym feche vn-ti&llbar; hym Semyo&ntail; his notary.  And
whe&ntail; he was come&ntail; he garte bere hym dow&ntail; in-to
&thorn;e hau&llbar;e, and he garte come by-fore hym a&llbar; his
prynce&yogh; & bade his notary wryte his testament bi-fore
&thorn;a&mtail; a&llbar; o&ntail; &thorn;is wyse.
</P>
<P>' ARestotle oure dere Maister, we comande the & prayse the,
&thorn;at of oure awe&ntail; tresour &thorn;ou sende to &thorn;e
preste&yogh; of Egipt &thorn;at ministre&yogh; in &thorn;e temple,
whare-in oure body sa&llbar; be beryed
 
<PB N="112">
& entere&dtail;, &jtilde; besande&yogh; of golde.  Also I wi&llbar;
that Tholomeus &thorn;at es kepare of oure body be &yogh;our
Gouernour, And forgetis noghte my laste wi&llbar;, Bot late&yogh; my
testament be alway bi-fore &yogh;our eghne so &thorn;at it be
fulfille&dtail; & noghte forgety&ntail;.  My wi&llbar; es also
&thorn;at if Rosa&ntail; my wyfe be delyuer of a knafe childe
&thorn;at he be &yogh;our Emperour and gyffe&yogh; hym what name so
&yogh;ow liste, and if scho be delyuer of a mayden childe,
&thorn;a&ntail; es it my wi&llbar; &thorn;at the Macedoynes chese
&thorn;a&mtail; a kynge, and &thorn;at my wyfe be lady of<MILESTONE
N="48" UNIT="leaf"> a&llbar; my
mobles.  Also I wi&llbar; &thorn;at Tholomeus be kyng of Egipt, and
&thorn;at he tak ti&llbar; his wyfe Cleopatra, &thorn;at my Fader
wedde&dtail; sum-tyme here bi-fore, and &thorn;at he be lorde & prynce
ouer a&llbar; &thorn;e lorde&yogh; of &thorn;e Este eue&ntail; vn-to
Bactria&ntail;.  Also I wi&llbar; &thorn;at my bro&thorn;er Arrideus
be kynge of &thorn;e Pelopones, also &thorn;at Cleopater be kyng of
Perse, Mellagere kyng of Ethopy, And Anthiochus be kyng vn-to &thorn;e
lande&yogh; of Gog & magoge, Areste&yogh; kynge of Inde, Lissymacus
lorde of Seleuce, Lythamo&ntail; kyng of hungary, Caulus kyng of
Ermony, Illicus kyng of Dalmace.  Symeo&ntail; my Notary, wi&llbar; I,
be Kyng of Capadoce & Pamphily, Cassander & Iobas be lorde&yogh; vn-to
&thorn;e Ryuer &thorn;at es calle&dtail; So&llbar;, Antipater
&thorn;aire Fader be kyng of Cicile.'  Whe&ntail; this testament was
in wrytynge bi-fore Alexander Sodeynly &thorn;are come a thonnere & a
leuennynge & ane erthedou&ntail; ri&yogh;te a hedous, so &thorn;at
a&llbar; babyloyne qwoke &thorn;are-wit.  And than thorowte a&llbar;
Babyloyne &thorn;e noyse rase &thorn;at Alexander was dede.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;e Macedoynes rasse hallely and come
arme&dtail; to &thorn;e Palace, and crye&dtail; on &thorn;e
prynce&yogh; & sai&dtail; vn-to &thorn;a&mtail; : 'Sothely,'
quo&thorn; &thorn;ay, 'but if &yogh;e onane schewe vs oure Emperour we
sa&llbar; slaa &yogh;ow ilk ane.' And whe&ntail; kyng Alexander herde
swilke noyse he askede whate it ment, and &thorn;e prynce&yogh;
ansuerde & sayde: '&THORN;e Macedoynes,' quo&thorn; &thorn;ay, 'are
come&ntail; armede hedir before &thorn;e &yogh;ates, & says sekerly
bot if &thorn;ay see &yogh;ow &thorn;ay sa&llbar; slaa vs a&llbar;e
are &thorn;ay passe he&thorn;ine.'  And whe&ntail; Alexander herde
&thorn;is, he bad&dtail; his knyghtis &thorn;at &thorn;ay scholde take
hym vp, and bere hym in-to &thorn;e consistorye.  And &thorn;ay did
soo. And &thorn;a&ntail; he garte ope&ntail; &thorn;e Palace
&yogh;ates &thorn;at &thorn;e Macedoynes my&yogh;te come by-fore hym.
And &thorn;a&ntail; kyng Alexander be-ga&ntail; to comen&dtail;
&thorn;a&mtail; of &thorn;aire strenth & &thorn;aire grete doghtynes,
and charged &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at &thorn;ay scholde be in pesse &
reste ilkane wit o&thorn;er.  &THORN;a&ntail; &thorn;e Macedoynes,
sare wepande, sayde vn-ti&llbar; Alexander: 'A, A, wirchipfu&llbar;,'
quo&thorn; &thorn;ay, 'ordayne & te&llbar;e vs are &yogh;e passe
<PB N="113">
heyne wha&mtail; &yogh;e wi&llbar; &thorn;at be oure emperour efter
&yogh;ow.'  And Alexander ansuer&dtail; & sayde, ' A, A, my dere
knyghtis,' quo&thorn; he, ' whe&ntail; I am dede whay&mtail; so
&yogh;e wi&llbar; chese, be &yogh;our emperour efter mee.'  And
&thorn;ay ansuerde, ' Lord,' quo&thorn; &thorn;ay, ' we beseke
&yogh;owe &thorn;at &yogh;e wi&llbar; graunt vs Perdic to be oure
Emperour.'  'I vouche wele saffe,' quo&thorn; Alexander, '&thorn;at
Perdic be &yogh;our Emperour.  Gers hym come be-fore mee.'  And
whe&ntail; he was come&ntail; by-fore hym he gaffe hym &thorn;e
kyngdome<MILESTONE N="48 bk." UNIT="leaf"> of Macedoyne wit &thorn;e Emperourchipe. And he gaffe hym
also Rosa&ntail; for to be his wyffe, and praye&dtail; hym &thorn;at
he walde be gude & genti&llbar; ti&llbar; hir.  And &thorn;an he
kyssede a&llbar; &thorn;e lorde&yogh; & &thorn;e knyghtis of Macedoyne
ilkane after o&thorn;er, and sighed and wepe&dtail; wonder sare.
&THORN;are was &thorn;a&ntail; so grete dole & wepynge, &thorn;at it
was lyke a thonere.  For me&ntail; Suppose&yogh; &thorn;at no&yogh;te
allanly me&ntail; made Sorow for &thorn;e dede of so worthy ane
Emperour, Bot also &thorn;e so&ntail; and a&llbar; &thorn;e o&thorn;er
planetis and elementes ware troubled.
</P>
<P>A prynce of Macedoyne stode nere Alexander bed&dtail; &thorn;at
highte Seleucus, & wit grete dole & wepynge he say&dtail;: 'A, A,
&thorn;ou wirchipfu&llbar; emperour,' quo&thorn; he, 'what sa&llbar;
we do whe&ntail; &thorn;ou ert dede.  Philippe &thorn;i fader
gouerne&dtail; vs wele & a&llbar;e oure rewme, Bot &thorn;e gentilnes
& &thorn;e largesse of the na tunge may te&llbar;.'  And
&thorn;a&ntail; Alexander sett hym vp in his bed&dtail; and gaffe
hy&mtail; selfe a grete flappe on &thorn;e cheke and by-ga&ntail; for
to wepe ri&yogh;te bitterly, and in &thorn;e langage of Macedoyne, he
sayde on &thorn;is wyse:
</P>
<P>'Fu&llbar; waa es me vnhappy wreche,' quo&thorn; he, '&thorn;at
euer I was borne to ma&ntail;.  For now Alexander dyes and Macedoyne
sa&llbar; waxe ay lesse & lesse and emenische day bi day.'  Tha&ntail;
a&llbar; &thorn;e Macedoynes wit an hye voyce and bitter wepynge sayd
vn-ti&llbar; hym: 'Better it ware ti&llbar; vs,' quo&thorn; &thorn;ay,
' for to dy wit &thorn;e &thorn;a&ntail; for to se &thorn;e dy in oure
presence.  For wele we wate &thorn;at, efter &thorn;e dede of the,
&thorn;e kyngdo&mtail; of Macedoyne es vndone for euere.  Allas oure
wirchipfu&llbar; Alexander, why lefes &thorn;ou vs here and
wende&yogh; away be thy&ntail; ane, withowte&ntail; thi Macedoynes ?'
Tha&ntail; kyng Alexander alway sighan&dtail; & wepan&dtail; said
vn-to &thorn;am: 'A, A, my dere Macedoynes,' quo&thorn; he, 'fra this
ty&mtail; forwarde sa&llbar; neuer &yogh;our name hafe lordchipe ouer
&thorn;e Barbarenes.'  And ba&ntail; &thorn;e Macedoynes crye&dtail;
and sayde: 'O wirchipfu&llbar; lorde,' quo&thorn;
<PB N="114">
&thorn;ay, '&thorn;ou led&dtail; vs in-to Perse, Arraby, and Inde, and
vn-to the werlde&yogh; ende, and in-to what cuntree &thorn;at &thorn;e
liste wende; why, lorde, flee&yogh; &thorn;ou now fra vs ? Lede vs wit
the whedir so &thorn;ou gase.'  &THORN;a&ntail; kyng Alexander sent to
&thorn;e templee of Appollo i&ntail; Athenes many riche iowels, and on
&thorn;e same wyse ti&llbar; a&llbar; o&thorn;er temples.  And
&thorn;a&ntail; he commande&dtail; &thorn;at whe&ntail; he ware dede,
&thorn;ay schulde enoynte his body and embawme it wit riche
oynementes, &thorn;e whilke kepis menes bodys in graues
wit-owtte&ntail; corupciou&ntail;. &THORN;a&ntail; he badde Tholomeus
&thorn;at he scholde [take] a &ctilde; besantes of golde, &
&thorn;are-off gere make hym a tombe in Alexander.  And onane<MILESTONE
N="49" UNIT="leaf"> as he ha&dtail; commande&dtail; hym &thorn;us, one-seean&dtail;
&thorn;a&mtail; a&llbar;, he swelt. And &thorn;a&ntail; his
prynce&yogh; lifte vp his body, and di&dtail; apo&ntail; his clethyng
of astate and putt a riche coro&ntail; o&ntail; his heued, and sett
hym in &thorn;e emperours chayer, &thorn;e whilke twelue prynce&yogh;
drewe wit &thorn;aire breste&yogh; fra Babiloyne ti&llbar; Alexander.
Tholomeus went alway bi-fore &thorn;e chayere wepande & sayande one
&thorn;is wyse: 'Fu&llbar; waa es me, My lor&dtail; Alexander, waa es
me. For in a&llbar; thi lyfe slew &thorn;ou neuer so many me&ntail; as
&thorn;ou dose nowe after &thorn;i dede.'  A&llbar; Alexanders
knyghtis also wepe&dtail; & made grete dole & sayde o&ntail; &thorn;is
wyse: 'Waa es vs weches ! whatt scha&llbar; wee now do after &thorn;e
dede of oure lorde Alexander ? Whedir sa&llbar; we now gaa or whate
partye may we now chese?  Whare scha&llbar; we now get any helpe
ti&llbar; oure lyfelade?'  One &thorn;is wyse &thorn;ay went
wepan&dtail; after Alexander, ti&llbar; &thorn;ay come ti&llbar;
&thorn;e citee of Alexander.  And &thorn;are &thorn;ay berye&dtail;
hym in a toumbe &thorn;at was ri&yogh;te hye and wonder curyouslye
wroghte.  &THORN;is tombe was a&llbar; of fyne golde sett fu&llbar; of
precyous stanes, and o&ntail; &thorn;at toumbe &thorn;er was sett xxx
ymages of golde wonder craftily made.
</P>
<P>Alexander was a ma&ntail; bot of a como&ntail; stature, wit a lange
nekke, Faire eghne & gla&dtail;, his chekes ruddy, and a&llbar;
&thorn;e remenant of his lymmes ware faire & semely & lyke
vn-ti&llbar; a lorde.  He ouercome a&llbar; me&ntail; & neuer was
ouercome&ntail;.  The lenthe of his lyffe was xxxij &yogh;ere, twa &
thritty &yogh;ere & seue&ntail; monethes.  Fra &thorn;e twenty&dtail;
&yogh;ere of his birthe he gaffe hym to werre, and in twelue &yogh;ere
he conquere&dtail; a&llbar; &thorn;e werlde, and made subiect
un-ti&llbar; hym alky&ntail; nacyonns. Seue&ntail; monethes he ristede
hym. He was borne on &thorn;e vij k&lbar; of January, and dye&dtail;
o&ntail; &thorn;e vij k&lbar; of August.
<PB N="115">
He byggi&dtail; also in his lyfe xij grete citee&yogh; &thorn;at
hider-to-warde&yogh; bene enhabyt, and &thorn;is are &thorn;aire
names.  Firste Alexander &thorn;at es calle&dtail; yprysilicas,
&thorn;e secund Alexander es calle&dtail; Bepyporum, &thorn;e
thri&dtail; Alexander es callede Sithia, &thorn;e ferthe Alexander es
calle&dtail; Bicontristi, &thorn;e fifte Alexander es called
&THORN;eraucto&ntail;, &thorn;e sext Alexander es calle&dtail;
Buctiphalo&ntail;, &thorn;e seuent es calle&dtail; vnder &thorn;e
ryuer of Tygre, &thorn;e aghten&dtail; New Babiloyne, &thorn;e
nyen&dtail; Aptreada&mtail;, &thorn;e ten&dtail; Messagetes, &thorn;e
elleuen&dtail; Ypsyaco&ntail;, &thorn;e twelfe&dtail; es called Egipt.
</P>
<P><FOREIGN LANG="LAT">Explicit vita Alexandry magni conquestoris.</FOREIGN>
</P>
<P>Here ende&yogh; &thorn;e lyf of gret Alexander conquerour of
a&llbar; &thorn;e worlde.</P></DIV1></BODY></TEXT></TEI.2>

